<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chamber Music Pianist Dies at 62 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Pianist Samuel Sanders, who had a career in the  
shadows as accompanist to many of the world's best-known musicians 
and compared his job to a baseball catcher dealing with star 
pitchers, has died at age 62. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders, a Manhattan resident, died of liver failure Friday,  
said his publicist, Lee Walter. He underwent a heart transplant, 
his second, in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders had performed with such musicians as singers Beverly  
Sills and Jessye Norman, violinists Itzhak Perlman and Pinchas 
Zukerman and cellists Yo-Yo Ma and Mstislav Rostropovich. 
</P>
<P>
	``Playing with Sam was always a great pleasure and an  
adventure,'' Perlman said Monday. ``He knew what I wanted to do, I 
knew what he wanted to do. It was just like breathing together. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had the greatest sense of humor. He was a wonderful, kind  
fellow, together with his wonderful musicianship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders, who took up the piano because his heart ailment kept  
him from other childhood activities, performed as a soloist with 
the New York Philharmonic when he was 16. But he was ambivalent 
about a solo career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't particularly love piano music,'' he once said. ``I  
didn't even like going to piano recitals. My teachers would drag me 
along and say, `Did you see how wonderful those thirds were?' And I 
could only think, `Let me out of here.''' 
</P>
<P>
	He took movie courses in college and considered becoming a film  
composer but found his niche when he began accompanying friends in 
recitals. 
</P>
<P>
	Using his baseball analogy, the Bronx-born Sanders said  
accompanists are like catchers because ``the catcher is in on every 
play and he really does see the whole field in a way that no other 
player sees it. ... The pitcher is the glamour figure. But if 
there's an errant pitch, the catcher has to be there. I expect the 
musical equivalent all the time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once, he said, a singer skipped an entire page of a Bach  
composition, and ``I went right to where she was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders strove to win recognition for the often overlooked  
accompanists, demanding that his name be included in concert 
advertisements. 
</P>
<P>
	He joined the faculty of the Juilliard School in 1963 and  
persuaded school officials to establish a master's degree program 
for accompanists. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was absolutely right,'' said Perlman, who won two Grammy  
awards for performances with Sanders. ```Accompanist' is the wrong 
term, really. When you talk about the major repertoire written for 
the violin and piano, both instruments are totally equal. I would 
say he was my musical partner.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
