<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- The president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce  
landed in Cuba on Tuesday to promote more private enterprise in the 
communist country. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are here to observe changes in the economic and political  
system, and particularly in learning about the independent 
businesses setting up in the country,'' Thomas Donohue said after 
his arrival. 
</P>
<P>
	The business leader met with Ricardo Alarcon, president of  
Cuba's National Assembly, the unicameral parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	The trip was permitted by the U.S. Treasury Department, which  
must license such missions because of the long-standing U.S. trade 
embargo against Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, State Department spokesman James Foley said in Washington  
he ``wouldn't read too much into this at this point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The chamber opposes the embargo. Many countries trade freely  
with Cuba, taking the position it is a way to promote economic and 
political reform on the island. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Clinton administration continues to back the trade  
sanctions, aimed at forcing a change in Fidel Castro's government. 
</P>
<P>
	The politically powerful Cuban-American community strongly  
opposes relaxation of the U.S. stance. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- A Brazilian state will conduct tests to  
determine if 500,000 tons of lime produced by a local subsidiary of 
a Belgian company is contaminated with dioxin, the Sao Paulo state 
environmental agency said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenpeace alleged in March that the dioxin-tainted lime treated  
citrus pulp was used for animal feed exported to Europe in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The subsidiary, Solvay, as well as Greenpeace and the  
Environmental Protection Agency agreed Tuesday to conduct the 
inspection at the company's lime stockpile in Santo Andre, an 
industrial suburb on the outskirts of Sao Paulo. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said the lime it produces contains dioxin ``of  
extremely low toxicity levels that don't represent a health 
hazard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- El Salvador's largest teachers'  
union held a one-day strike Tuesday to demand a pay increase. 
</P>
<P>
	The 29,000-member National Association of Salvadoran Educators  
is asking for increases of $30 to $70 a month. Its members now earn 
$390 to $645 a month. 
</P>
<P>
	Education Minister Evelyn Jacir de Lovo criticized the strike  
and told teachers not to make ``social earthquakes'' out of 
differences that can be resolved through negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	VILLAHERMOSA, Mexico (AP) -- A leading candidate for the Mexican  
governing party's presidential nomination got a big boost Tuesday -- 
the backing of important union locals in his main rival's home 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	Francisco Labastida received the backing of 23 of the 36 locals  
of the Petroleum Worker's Union, including all six locals in 
Tabasco state, where his chief opponent, Roberto Madrazo served as 
governor until June. The remaining 13 locals of the 100,000-member 
union haven't endorsed any candidate yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Labastida, the former Interior secretary, and Madrazo are  
considered the two top candidates for the presidential nomination 
of the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party. 
</P>
<P>
	The party, which has ruled Mexico for 70 years, will hold its  
first-ever primary in November to choose a candidate for the July 
2000 presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Chile will grant Nazi hunter Simon  
Wiesenthal its highest decoration in recognition to ``his 
commitment to justice, truth, reason and people's dignity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Osvaldo Puccio, Chile's ambassador to Austria, told the Santiago  
daily La Hora that he will deliver the Great Cross of the Bernardo 
O'Higgins Order to the founder of the Jewish Documentation Center 
in Vienna on July 22. 
</P>
<P>
	The decoration is named after Chile's main independence hero.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Police arrested three leaders of a strike  
by taxi and bus drivers that has brought much of Ecuador to a 
standstill, union leaders said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Strike leaders warned the detentions could hinder talks to end  
the strike, which is trying to force President Jamil Mahuad to 
rescind a 13 percent gasoline price increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Police, empowered by a 60-day state of emergency declared last  
week, say they have detained 300 strikers, but would not confirm 
the arrests of the leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	The strike has become another test of Mahuad's ability to enact  
tough economic reforms demanded by international lenders to cut 
Ecuador's massive budget deficit, lower inflation and modernize its 
statist economy. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- Four convicted killers were found hanged  
in their Guatemalan prison cells Tuesday, four days after they had 
been sentenced to 33 years each for homicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities ordered an investigation into the deaths at the  
high-security prison, popularly known as ``El Infierno'' or 
``Hell,'' in Escuintla, about 30 miles south of Guatemala City. 
</P>
<P>
	The four had been transferred to the prison Friday after being  
sentenced for the Sept. 26 killings of two other prisoners. 
</P>
<P>
	During the sentencing hearing one of the men, Guillermo  
Castellanos, 30, threatened to kill presiding Judge Ana Ayerdi 
Castillo and her family, prompting her to ask the Supreme Court for 
protection. 
</P>
<P>
	The other three men were identified as Fredy Ayala, 21; Enio  
Rodriguez, 29; and Sergio Monzon, 25. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- The mastermind of Venezuela's beauty  
queen school says he wants to bring one of his extravaganzas to 
Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Osmel Sousa, the man who has helped Venezuela win 10  
international beauty pageants in the last two decades, says he has 
approached Cuban officials in Caracas to discuss holding a pageant 
at a Cuban tourist spot, Varadero beach. 
</P>
<P>
	Sousa said his proposed pageant would involve contestants from  
throughout Latin America. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
