<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Stocks Bob Back 4.6 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Argentina's leading stock index  
ticked upward Tuesday, recovering about half of the ground it lost 
a day earlier on election-year worries about the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Merval Index of leading shares rose 4.6 percent to close at  
474.71. Bargain hunters entered the market in search of cheap 
equities after Monday's selloff, in which the index plummeted 8.7 
percent. Advancing shares more than doubled decliners on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Argentina's deficit, an election-year recession and the ongoing  
presidential campaign for an Oct. 24 election helped sow a climate 
of investor uncertainty, according to analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the damage was blamed on damaging remarks by  
presidential hopefuls ahead of the election. Eduardo Duhalde, the 
ruling party candidate, stirred markets with talk of supporting 
Roman Catholic church proposals calling for leniency for poorer 
countries saddled with big debts. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Tuesday he was surprised by the market action Monday.  
Speaking at a news conference, he said he was prompted to raise the 
issue after the Group of Seven leading countries recently agreed to 
broaden debt relief under the so-called Heavily Indebted Poor 
Countries Initiative. 
</P>
<P>
	Duhalde's main competitor for the presidency, Fernando de la Rua  
of the opposition Alliance, told Argentine television that all 
politicians should measure their words when discussing issues like 
debt restructuring. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this one must be careful with what one says,'' de la Rua  
said. ``We need to act with a lot of seriousness to affirm 
confidence in the Argentine economy.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 13:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains Lower; Soybeans Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat and corn futures retreated Tuesday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade, while soybean futures finished mostly higher. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat and corn futures finished only marginally lower in listless  
trading, however, as conflicting weather reports kept pricing action 
to a minimum. 
</P>
<P>
        The National Weather Service's 10-day forecast, released after  
trading ended Monday, called for above-normal rainfall in key Midwest 
growing states, including Illinois and Iowa. But some private forecasters 
continue to predict only scant rainfall as temperatures climb once 
more into the 90s. 
</P>
<P>
        If those forecasts hold true, the crops could begin to see  
some weather-related stress that might reduce yields. Still, analysts 
believe that much of the corn crop is out of the woods after going 
through the crucial pollination period in which kernels form. 
</P>
<P>
        Soybeans also faced the same differing weather reports, but  
edged higher on continued reports of strong export demand for soybean 
meal. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat for December delivery fell 1 cent to $2.59 1/4 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1/4 cent to $1.96 1/2 a bushel; December oats fell 
1/4 cent to $108 3/4 a bushel; November soybeans rose 1 cent to $4. 
19 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Beef and lean hog futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while pork bellies finished mixed. 
</P>
<P>
        August live cattle fell .68 cent to 63.12 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .50 cent to 76.97 cents a pound; August lean hogs 
fell 1.55 cents to 44.42 cents a pound; August pork bellies rose .40 
cent to 33.27 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
