<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Company Charged in ValuJet Crash  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A maintenance firm for ValuJet was charged today  
with murder and manslaughter in the 1996 Everglades crash that 
killed 110 people. SabreTech Inc. also was charged with unlawful 
transportation of hazardous waste. The third-degree murder and 
second-degree manslaughter charges, both state charges, are 
felonies. It was not immediately clear what penalties the company 
could face. Federal indictments were also expected today, naming 
SabreTech employees involved in the packaging of the illegal cargo 
blamed for the crash, Justice Department sources told The 
Associated Press. 

</P>
<P>
	Resendez-Ramirez Surrenders in Texas  
</P>
<P>
	EL PASO, Texas (AP) -- Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, the train-riding  
fugitive suspected of killing eight people, surrendered at a border 
checkpoint today in a deal brokered by his sister. The 39-year-old 
drifter, who is charged or wanted for questioning in three states, 
surrendered to Texas Rangers Sgt. Drew Carter, state investigators 
said. The surrender agreement included assurances of family 
visitation rights, a psychological evaluation and promises that 
Resendez-Ramirez would be safe in jail, said state Department of 
Public Safety Capt. Bruce Casteel. It does not shield him from the 
death penalty. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Wants Tax Cut Resistance  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- President Clinton today urged congressional  
Republicans to resist the temptation of a large tax cut and instead 
devote more of the expected federal budget surpluses to salvaging 
Social Security and Medicare. Clinton said it would be a mistake if 
Republicans opt for an immediate, large tax reduction without 
finding a way to extend the life of the programs. House Republicans 
today officially rolled out a proposed $864 billion tax cut that 
would reduce income tax rates by 10 percent over a decade, cut 
capital-gains rates and eliminate the ``marriage penalty.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Kasich To Withdraw, Endorse Bush  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ohio Rep. John Kasich has decided to withdraw  
from the race for the Republican presidential nomination and 
intends to endorse Texas Gov. George W. Bush, Republican officials 
said today. The officials said they expected Bush to be present for 
Kasich's formal announcement, set for tomorrow afternoon. 
Republican officials said they did not expect the 47-year-old 
Kasich to reverse an earlier decision to retire from Congress at 
the end of his current term. The Ohio Republican was first elected 
to the House in 1982. 

</P>
<P>
	Balkan Funding May Hinder Other Aid  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The hundreds of millions of dollars it  
will cost to rebuild the Balkans may sap the world's ability to 
respond to other humanitarian crises, the president of the World 
Bank said today. James Wolfensohn spoke as finance ministers from 
the top seven industrialized democracies and other officials 
launched a campaign to raise $500 million for reconstruction in 
Kosovo and surrounding nations. Wolfensohn warned that it may be 
difficult to handle multiple humanitarian projects at once -- and he 
insisted that rebuilding Kosovo should not come at the expense of 
aid to Asia, Africa or other areas that have not captured the 
attention of the media or the public. 

</P>
<P>
	Nasal Spray Prevents Flu  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- An ouchless flu vaccine that is sprayed up the  
nose has proved effective in protecting people against the virus. 
``There are significant hurdles, but our goal is to have it 
available for the flu season of 2000-2001,'' said Dr. J. Leighton 
Reed, chairman of Aviron Inc. of Mountain View, Calif., which 
developed the vaccine and helped pay for the research. The nasal 
vaccine, called FluMist, would offer an alternative to the standard 
flu shot millions of Americans get in the arm each year. It still 
needs Food and Drug Administration approval. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Fall; Dow Down 19.31  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks dropped today as concerns about Latin  
America's economic recovery muted investor optimism about strong 
second-quarter profit reports. Just before the close, the Dow Jones 
industrial average was down 19.31 at 11,181.67 after having 
achieved three closing highs in the past four sessions. NYSE 
decliners led advancers 1,793-1,172. The Nasdaq composite index 
fell 10.85 to 2,779.59. 

</P>
<P>
	All-Stars Set To Play in Boston  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Many of the players on the All-Star roster are  
excited about playing tonight's game at 87-year-old Fenway Park, 
which is one of the oldest parks in baseball. Ten-time All-Star Ken 
Griffey Jr., who considers Fenway ``a classic,'' plans to chip some 
paint from the famed Green Monster, the left field wall. Tony 
Gwynn, who will sit out the game due to injuries, brought a book 
detailing the park's history. He still wanted to take batting 
practice and maybe field a few balls off the wall. The Red Sox hope 
to build a new ballpark by the 2003 season. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
