<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Tours N.Y. Beach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WANTAGH, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton talked welfare  
reform with suburban New Yorkers and house prices with Long Island 
beachgoers on Tuesday as she continued a tour of the state in a 
prelude to a likely Senate run. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've heard about it literally all my life, from many friends  
who would come here and spend lots of glorious summer days,'' Mrs. 
Clinton said before a cheering crowd of several hundred people at 
Jones Beach. ``I'm just delighted to be here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, two Republicans who are likely GOP contenders for the  
Senate seat continued jockeying for the support of Washington 
politicians. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Lazio, a Long Island congressman, announced Tuesday that  
several Senate GOP leaders, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott among 
them, would be holding a Washington fund-raiser for him. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund-raiser came after a June 17 fund-raising dinner in  
Washington for New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, also hosted by 
Lott and other GOP senators. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, who has established an exploratory committee for a  
likely Senate campaign, chatted with shirtless men, women in 
bikinis and several dozen others in her beach stop. 
</P>
<P>
	She began making visits through the state last week in what she  
has described as a ``listening tour.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She also talked about her househunt, remarking on the high cost  
of real estate like any other middle-class New Yorker might: ``If I 
can afford it, I'd buy, but I probably will end up renting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton said she'd looked at some houses herself, seen  
brochures and videos and gotten reports from friends who'd checked 
out properties for her, but she hasn't yet made up her mind. 
</P>
<P>
	Melanie Antonelli, a hair salon owner from upstate Cornwall,  
said she was a Republican but would vote for Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need more women in politics,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton began Tuesday at Westchester Community College in  
Valhalla at a forum with 50 parents, educators, students and former 
welfare recipients who now have jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I support welfare reform,'' she said. ``I believe we needed to  
make those changes, but it can only work if we have childcare, 
support and other necessities that people need to move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rebecca Hodges, a once-homeless, single mother who now works at  
a center for AIDS patients after getting a childcare grant, said 
she worries about losing the grant and appreciated Mrs. Clinton's 
interest. 
</P>
<P>
	``It showed me she was concerned,'' Miss Hodges said. ``She  
really was listening. She was very friendly, very open to 
suggestion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone was impressed.  
</P>
<P>
	``She spoke in generalities. I wouldn't think Giuliani would  
have any problem agreeing with any of it,'' said Sarah Stern, a 
Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton also expressed support for universal  
pre-kindergarten, which New York state has declined to fund; for 
making college tuition tax-deductible; and for a federal initiative 
to pay for school construction that the White House has backed but 
Congress has not. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have a lot of old schools and a lot of fast-growing  
suburbs,'' she said. ``It's not just an inner-city problem, it's 
also a suburban -- and as I learned last week -- a rural problem as 
well. The local tax burden in many parts of New York is incredibly 
high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	AP reporter Marc Humbert contributed to this story from Albany,  
N.Y. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
