<DOCNO> APW19990713.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 15:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Journal Spurs Dow Jones Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dow Jones &AMP; Co. credited strong growth in  
advertising in The Wall Street Journal for second-quarter net 
earnings of $57.2 million, results that beat Wall Street 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	The profits reported Tuesday were equivalent to 62 cents per  
share, better than the 61 cents predicted by analysts surveyed by 
First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same quarter a year ago, Dow Jones had a net loss of  
$51.7 million, or 54 cents per share, mainly because of a loss on 
the sale of its money-losing Telerate subsidiary, a financial 
markets information service. Without the Telerate loss, the company 
earned $54.7 million, or 56 cents a share, in the year-ago quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues rose 4.9 percent to $510.6 million from $486.7 million,  
not counting results from the Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Jones chairman Peter Kann attributed the earnings growth to  
improved results from the Journal and the company's Ottaway 
community newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	Advertising lineage at The Wall Street Journal rose 6.9 percent  
in the quarter and 18.9 percent in June. Excluding a one-time 
charge in connection with severance costs after converting to 
electronic pagination of the Journal, the company's publishing 
operations posted an 18.4 percent rise in operating income to $82.6 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues from electronic publishing rose 1.4 percent to $98.8  
million. But operating income in that segment fell 44 percent to 
$10.2 million due to increased spending on advertising and higher 
costs for content. Dow Jones reported that the online Journal now 
has 306,000 subscribers, making it the largest paid subscription 
site on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Not counting the results from Telerate, Dow Jones' earnings for  
the first six months of the year edged up to $108.7 million, or 
$1.18 per share, from $104.3 million, or $1.07 per share, in the 
same period a year ago. Revenues rose to $972.7 million from $936.7 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Jones stock edged up 6 1/4 cents to $52.68 3/4 on the New York  
Stock Exchange Tuesday. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 15:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Madison Ave.'s Latest Hot Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Brandi Chastain may have created the best-known  
new undie since the Wonderbra when she doffed her jersey after 
delivering the winning kick at the Women's World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Nike, which makes sports bras for the U.S. women's soccer team,  
is now trying to figure out how to convert that moment of marketing 
magic into new sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Chastain and her teammates are seeing a burst of marketing  
interest that experts had predicted if the team won the title. 
</P>
<P>
	The maker of Wheaties said Tuesday it has begun talks about  
putting the team's picture on the box. And Walt Disney has been 
running its signature post-championship television ads with the 
team shouting ``We're going to Disneyland'' and ``We're going to 
Disney World.'' The World Cup matches drew unexpectedly large 
crowds to arenas across the country in the past three weeks and the 
TV ratings grew as the tournament climaxed last Saturday in the 
Rose Bowl where the United States beat China in the finale. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Solomon, a top commercial buyer at SFM Media, said Tuesday  
that team members captured American's imagination ``not only by 
their playing but by their demeanor'' and expects the feeling will 
have ``some staying power.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They didn't argue, they didn't bad-mouth anybody, they were  
always going out of their way to be gracious. The whole idea of the 
teamwork aspect captured the fancy of the public,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kathryn Reith, a spokeswoman for Nike, said Chastain was one of  
10 U.S. team members wearing the new Nike Inner Actives sports bra 
that goes on sale for $40 on July 25. 
</P>
<P>
	She insisted Nike had not scripted Chastain's decision to rip  
off her jersey and expose the black bra. She noted Chastain has 
described it as a moment of ``temporary insanity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, she said Nike ``certainly will capitalize on it.''  
The company will use a photo of Chastain in her sports bra for 
displays in stores and may have Chastain make extra personal 
appearances promote the bra. But Reith was unaware of any broader 
advertising plans. 
</P>
<P>
	A picture of Chastain in her sports bra drew a hearty cheer at a  
rally staged by Nike on Tuesday in midtown Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Colson, managing editor of Sports Illustrated, presented  
Chastain -- who was fully clothed -- with a giant framed copy of the 
magazine's upcoming cover, featuring her kneeling on the field in 
celebration. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, General Mills Inc. is talking with the team and the  
players about an appearance on a Wheaties cereal box, company 
spokesman Greg Zimprich said Tuesday. ``We are definitely 
interested,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company from Golden Valley, Minn., has heard from hundreds  
of people wondering if the team will be featured on the boxes as 
champions like the U.S. women's hockey team was after winning gold 
in the 1998 Olympics in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been inundated with calls,'' said company spokeswoman  
Natalie Peterson. 
</P>
<P>
	Mia Hamm, a member of the soccer team, had earlier told Fox News  
Channel that it appeared Wheaties was not interested, and added she 
and her teammates ``like the sweeter cereals'' anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney shot two ads with the soccer team Saturday in the Rose  
Bowl after its victory. The television spots were airing around the 
nation on Monday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has been using the approach in similar ads for its  
theme parks for the past 12 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Marketing experts have warned the team's notoriety could prove  
short-lived because of the lack of a women's professional league 
and America's relative disinterest in soccer versus other sports 
like football, baseball and basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	The team will stay in the public's eye for at least several  
months thanks to a planned soccer exhibition tour. 
</P>
<P>
	It will compete against a world all-star team in 11 matches  
starting Oct. 22 in Pittsburgh and ending Dec. 12 in Tacoma, Wash. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee Berke, a vice president at the sports marketing firm SFX  
Sports Group which helped organize the tour, said it will allow the 
players to earn money from soccer, stay close to their fans and 
demonstrate the viability of a professional league. 
</P>
<P>
	He said a number of sponsors including beverage, financial  
services and packaged goods companies have expressed interest in 
the tour. He said talks are underway about producing a TV special 
during the tour. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
