<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Welcomes Soccer Team Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- President Jiang Zemin led an official welcoming  
ceremony Tuesday for the Chinese women's soccer team, which brought 
home a World Cup silver medal. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-4 loss to the United States on overtime penalty kicks in a  
politically charged match chagrined Chinese fans. But their sorrow 
has been tempered by pride that China's women made it to the finals 
and held the Americans scoreless in regular play. 
</P>
<P>
	``You didn't disappoint the wishes of the masses,'' Jiang told  
the team during a reception at the Great Hall of the People in the 
center of Beijing. ``You showed on the playing field the 
self-reliance and self-confidence of Chinese women.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team returned Monday night from the United States to a  
raucous welcome by hundreds of fans who beat drums, crashed cymbals 
and sang the Chinese national anthem outside Beijing airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Also at the ceremony Tuesday were Communist Party leaders Li  
Peng, Li Ruihuan, Hu Jintao and Wei Jianxing. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Chinese had looked on the World Cup final in Pasadena,  
Calif., as a grudge match against a rival with whom China has a 
range of political and trade disputes. 
</P>
<P>
	Jiang said he hoped the women's soccer team and other Chinese  
athletes made ``persistent efforts'' to win other honors for the 
country. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 06:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Prints New Currency Notes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- Singapore will issue a new series of currency  
notes to mark the millennium, the government announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bills will have new themes, colors and high-tech additions  
to prevent counterfeiting, the Board of Commissioners of Currency 
of Singapore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Security features include a so-called latent image, which  
changes from one picture to another when viewed from different 
angles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although currency counterfeiting has never been a serious  
problem in Singapore, the advent of ... color copiers and computer 
scanners has prompted the BCCS to take additional precautionary 
measures,'' the board said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The new notes will have the country's first showing a portrait  
of a person, Singapore's first President Yusof bin Ishak, said the 
board's director of administration, Martin Teo. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the bills' seven denominations -- from 2 to 10,000  
Singapore dollars -- will portray the themes of education, garden 
city, sports, arts, youth, government and economics. 
</P>
<P>
	The denominations will remain the same, with bills of 2, 5, 10,  
50, 100, 1,000 and 10,000 Singapore dollars. Some new bills will be 
slightly smaller in size, and the 100 and 10,000 Singapore dollar 
bills will undergo color changes, the board said. 
</P>
<P>
	The cash will debut at an exhibition Sept. 9, when visitors can  
exchange old money for it. Banks will begin circulating the new 
bills alongside existing ones on Sept. 13, Teo said. 
</P>
<P>
	One Singapore dollar currently trades at 59 U.S. cents.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
