<DOCNO> APW19990713.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 19:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rio Sues U.S. Tobacco Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Rio state government announced  
Tuesday it has begun a lawsuit against U.S. tobacco firms in a bid 
to recover the public health care costs of treating sick smokers. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, the first of it kind by a Brazilian authority, was  
launched by four Texas lawyers acting for the state, said 
government lawyer Jose Calisto Ushoa Ribeiro. On Tuesday, the four 
filed papers in a U.S. court. 
</P>
<P>
	Ribeiro declined to immediately name the state, ``for strategic  
reasons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The lawsuit will be against all the American tobacco companies  
who, either directly or indirectly, have caused the government of 
Rio to incur costs in public health care,'' Ribeiro said at a news 
conference. He named 15 firms involved including Philip Morris and 
RJR Nabisco. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit would likely be for billions of dollars, said  
Ribeiro. The state would begin to calculate the cost of treating 
cancer patients and those with smoking-related illnesses over ``the 
last 20 or 30 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Texan lawyers -- W. Mark Lanier, Charles Siegel, Vaughan O.  
Stewart and Henry Saint Dahl -- will pay all costs and receive a 
percentage of any damages received, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a radio interview, Rio governor Anthony Garotinho said he  
hoped to negotiate a settlement and expected the state to receive 
$10 billion in reimbursements. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Brazil's Health Minister Jose Serra met with U.S.  
lawyers to discuss a possible lawsuit by the federal government 
against U.S. tobacco companies. He has not announced plans to begin 
legal action. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 16:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Motorola Earnings Beat Expectations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Motorola Inc.'s second-quarter earnings beat Wall  
Street expectations Tuesday as it continued to benefit from a 
rebound in its semiconductor business and strong digital cellular 
phone sales. 
</P>
<P>
	For the period ending July 3, the company earned from operations  
of $273 million, or 44 cents a share, compared with $6 million, or 
1 cent a share, in the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The results beat Wall Street expectations of 41 cents a share,  
according to a survey of analysts by First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorola also recorded a charge of $94 million, reflecting a  
move to prop up its 18 percent investment in the Iridium 
go-anywhere satellite phone project. The year-ago quarter included 
a charge of $1.91 billion for restructuring. Including the charges, 
Motorola earned $206 million, compared to a loss of $1.3 billion in 
the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorola shares fell $2.50 to $96.50 during a general retreat  
Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange. Earnings were released 
after trading had ended. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales jumped 7 percent to $7.5 billion from $7 billion. As  
expected by analysts, Motorola's paging and wireless infrastructure 
segments remained sluggish, but the sales results reflected an 
overall improvement in Motorola's outlook and of the semiconductor 
industry in general. 
</P>
<P>
	For Motorola, sales of semiconductors -- the chips that run  
everything from phones to computers -- jumped 9 percent for the 
quarter to $2 billion, while orders jumped 20 percent. That was 
helped by a boost in orders from all regions except Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel Corp. on Tuesday also reported a rebound in its  
computer-chip business, although its profits were below forecasts. 
The Semiconductor Industry Association reported last week that 
sales were up 11 percent in May as the Asian economy showed signs 
of a rebound. 
</P>
<P>
	After long delays in introducing digital wireless phones, the  
Schaumburg, Ill.-based company appeared to be gaining on 
competitors Nokia, Ericsson and Qualcomm. 
</P>
<P>
	The company reported orders jumped 21 percent in the quarter to  
$3.2 billion, helped in part by Bell Atlantic's purchase of 1 
million digital StarTac phones and accompanying accessories. Sales 
rose 17 percent to $2.8 billion for the quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The good news, however, was tempered by warnings the third  
quarter could be further affected by Motorola's Iridium 
obligations. 
</P>
<P>
	The troubled company has repeatedly received extensions from its  
creditors as it falls well short of the amount of subscribers it 
had promised would be on board by earlier this year. Motorola 
indicated it will play a major hand in Iridium's recent efforts to 
restructure its business, lower costs and bring in new customers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 11:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Veterinarian Guilty in Cruelty Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OLD BRIDGE, N.J. (AP) -- A veterinarian accused of choking,  
throwing and punching pets under his care was found guilty of 
cruelty to animals. 
</P>
<P>
	Municipal Judge Emery Toth convicted Dr. Howard Baker yesterday  
and ordered him to pay $3,500, attend anger management classes and 
perform community service. 
</P>
<P>
	The case centered on a video secretly made by an animal rights  
activist who had been a Baker assistant. The tape showed the doctor 
striking a Dalmatian twice. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker was also accused, among other things, of grasping a cat  
around the neck and flailing it to its death. 
</P>
<P>
	He denied the cruelty allegations, saying he gave only light  
slaps or taps to pets and grabbed cats by the scruff of the neck to 
calm them. He said the Dalmatian had tried to bite him. 
</P>
<P>
	The former assistant ``was one witness in the face of four  
others who were there and said it didn't happen,'' defense attorney 
Michael Rosenbaum said. ``That's round one. We have a bunch more 
rounds to go.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 11:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Tax Cut Resistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- President Clinton today urged congressional  
Republicans to resist the temptation of a large tax cut and instead 
devote more of the expected federal budget surpluses to salvaging 
Social Security and Medicare. ``Join us in putting first things 
first,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said it would be a mistake if -- 16 months before the  
next presidential election -- Republicans opt for an immediate, 
large tax reduction, ``whether it's right for America or not,'' 
without finding a way to extend the life of programs on which 
millions of senior citizens depend. 
</P>
<P>
	``I realize that it's tempting. It's a severe test for us,''  
Clinton said of the surplus. He noted that his administration's 
proposal for the surplus combined smaller tax cuts with protections 
for Social Security and Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can still have a good-sized tax cut, but not as large as  
the one the Republicans propose,'' he said in a speech to the 
annual convention of the Communications Workers of America. ``I am 
asking Republican leaders, in the interest of saving Medicare, to 
reconsider the size of their tax cut plan. ... Reduce the size of 
the tax cut and join us in putting first things first.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tonight, Clinton was attending a fund-raiser at the Coral Gables  
home of sugar magnate Alfonso Fanjul. The event was raising between 
$500,000 and $1 million for the Florida Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican congressional leaders say Clinton seems ready to work  
with them on revamping Medicare, cutting taxes and other budget 
issues, but their first face-to-face budget meeting Monday yielded 
no consensus on how to spend $2.9 trillion in budget surpluses 
expected over the next 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want cooperation, not partisanship,'' said Senate Majority  
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., after the hourlong session Monday 
night. ``His tone was the same.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, among Clinton's most  
outspoken foes, said ``there's no doubt'' Clinton's message was 
that he was ready to seriously tackle the issues separating the 
White House and Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans and Democrats alike cast the tone of the meeting  
positively, which considering the distrust many Republicans feel 
for Clinton might be a major achievement in itself. 
</P>
<P>
	But members of both parties, speaking on condition of anonymity,  
said there was no change in the likely scenario that Clinton would 
veto a GOP-written tax cut and perhaps some spending bills before 
any substantive negotiations start, probably in September or later. 
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans today officially rolled out a proposed $864  
billion tax cut that would reduce income tax rates by 10 percent 
over a decade, cut capital-gains rates for individuals and 
corporations, eventually abolish estate taxes and the alternative 
minimum tax and eliminate the ``marriage penalty'' paid by millions 
of two-income couples by raising the standard deduction for them. 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Clinton announced a legislative proposal to  
require employers to better inform their employees when changes are 
being made to their pension plans. Under the proposal, employers 
must offer a ``clear and complete explanation'' of pension 
reductions at least 45 days before they take effect. Under current 
law, disclosures must be made at least 15 days in advance. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bill Archer, chairman of the House Ways and Means  
Committee, said the tax cut could be accomplished without 
threatening Social Security and Medicare or forcing cuts in key 
programs. He said the plan reflected GOP priorities to reduce the 
size of government. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we are talking about is a defining difference between the  
Republicans and Democrats,'' said Archer, R-Texas. ``We believe the 
people can spend their money more wisely than the bureaucrats in 
Washington.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the White House meeting was over, the dispute between the  
two sides loomed as large as ever. 
</P>
<P>
	While they generally agree the $1.9 trillion part of the surplus  
generated by Social Security should be used to reduce the national 
debt, Republicans want to use most of the remaining $1 trillion for 
tax cuts. Clinton and Democrats want to use it for Medicare, a much 
smaller $250 billion tax reduction, and defense and domestic 
spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we're not going to do is collapse to their position if we  
think their position is wrong-headed,'' said House Minority Leader 
Dick Gephardt, D-Mo. ``We think it's wrong to do a $1 trillion tax 
cut.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats familiar with the meeting said Clinton opened it by  
saying that prior to considering a tax cut, the two sides first 
must agree to revamp Social Security and Medicare for the 
retirement of the 76 million baby boomers, beginning in a decade. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 20:30:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Male Soccer Team Readies for Battle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- U.S. national men's team coach Bruce Arena watched  
every minute and every kick of the victory the U.S. women's team 
enjoyed over China. But not once did he figure it would add any 
pressure on him or his team as it prepares for the upcoming 
Confederation Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``I congratulate them for winning, but don't feel any more  
pressure at all for us to win a world championship,'' Arena said. 
``I don't anticipate us winning one, not with the talented teams of 
the world like Brazil and Mexico, but see us doing well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arena has more pressing matters. On Tuesday night, the U.S.  
men's team played Derby County Club of the English Premier League 
at Mile High Stadium, the team's final tuneup before the 
Confederation Cup. The Americans won 2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our main objective will be to fill out our roster and a  
secondary one to train and play at altitude,'' Arena said before 
the game. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team will join some of the world's best teams for the  
July 24-Aug. 4 competition in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our players know the game is important,'' Arena said. ``We  
need to name a 20-man roster by Wednesday and I will make that 
decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among those on the team for Tuesday night's game were veterans  
Claudio Reyna, Joe-Max Moore and Jeff Agoos. Ben Olsen and Joey 
DiGiamarino come from the Under-23 National team. 
</P>
<P>
	Goalkeeper Kasey Keller, midfielders Chris Armas, Jovan Kirovski  
and Eddie Lewis and forward Cobi Jones were key performers in the 
team's victory over Argentina. 
</P>
<P>
	``In order to be successful in Mexico, we must take a healthy  
team, an experienced team and one that has depth at every 
position,'' Arena said. ``We play three matches in seven days and 
possibly four matches in nine days, so I feel every player will 
have to contribute.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
