<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Allowed To Adopt Black Boy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- The state has let a white woman  
adopt the 4-year-old black boy she has raised since birth, ending a 
long case by also agreeing to pay her $135,000 in legal costs for 
the discrimination lawsuit she filed. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a settlement approved Monday, the Florida Department of  
Children and Families also apologized to Shirley Fitzgerald and 
acknowledged it made a mistake in trying to place the boy with 
black relatives whom Fitzgerald said ignored his medical needs. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy, named Shaq (pronounced ``Shay''), was born to a  
drug-addicted woman and has asthma, epilepsy, damaged hearing and 
delayed speech development. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement says medical opinions clearly establish it is  
best for Shaq to remain with Ms. Fitzgerald and her two adopted 
daughters, the only family he has known. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, Ms. Fitzgerald agreed to drop her civil rights  
lawsuit, one of the first in the nation to challenge an adoption 
decision under state and federal anti-discrimination laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit alleged state officials discriminated against Ms.  
Fitzgerald because she is white and against her adopted daughters 
because they have the AIDS virus. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement provides for supervised, three-hour visits once a  
month between Shaq and his relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very progressive agreement,'' said Ms. Fitzgerald's  
lawyer, Alan Mishael. ``A lot of time and effort went into this to 
try to give this child the best of both worlds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fitzgerald, 63, is a longtime foster parent for children with  
medical problems, primarily the AIDS virus. The state placed Shaq 
with her just days after he was born; he was HIV-positive at the 
time but tested negative a year later. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaq's great-aunt and great-uncle, Carolyn and Paul Simmons, are  
raising two of his five half-siblings as foster children and sought 
custody of him in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fitzgerald alleged that the aunt didn't give Shaq  
medications as needed and that the couple's smoking triggered his 
asthma attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Simmons said Monday she didn't know anything about the  
settlement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
