<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Company Charged in ValuJet Crash  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Murder and manslaughter charges were announced  
today against the airline maintenance company that packaged the 
oxygen canisters blamed for the 1996 ValuJet crash. The crash 
killed 110 people in the Everglades. The third-degree murder and 
second-degree manslaughter charges, both Florida state charges, are 
felonies. It was not clear what penalties the company, SabreTech 
Inc., would face if convicted. Federal indictments were also 
expected today, naming SabreTech employees involved in the 
packaging of the illegal cargo, Justice Department sources told The 
Associated Press on condition of anonymity. It is believed to be 
the first time in U.S. aviation history that criminal charges were 
filed against maintenance workers after an accidental airplane 
crash, said Mike Boyd, president of the Evergreen, Colo.-based Mike 
Boyd Group, which researches aviation issues. 

</P>
<P>
	Intel's Second-Quarter Profit Jumps  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE (AP) -- Intel Corp. reported today that its  
second-quarter profit rose 49 percent, but the results failed to 
meet Wall Street expectations amid a shift in company sales to less 
expensive computer chips. Intel, the world's largest maker of 
microprocessor chips, said it earned $1.75 billion, or 51 cents a 
share, two cents below Wall Street expectations. That compared to a 
profit of $1.17 billion, or 33 cents a share, in the second quarter 
of 1998. Revenue rose 14 percent to $6.75 billion from $5.93 
billion. The Santa Clara, Calif.-based Intel said microprocessor 
sales dropped slightly in the second quarter compared to the first 
quarter of this year. In addition, the company's average selling 
price for chips dropped as the company sold more microprocessors 
for inexpensive personal computers. Intel stock was down 1/16 at 
65 1/8 today. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Lower; Dow Down 25.96  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks dropped today as concerns about Latin  
America's economic recovery muted investor optimism about 
second-quarter earnings reports. At the close on Wall Street, the 
Dow Jones industrial average was down 25.96 at to 11,175.02 after 
having fallen as much as 114 points in early trading. The Dow's 
loss came after the blue chips achieved new closing highs in the 
past four sessions. Broader stock indicators also declined. The 
Nasdaq composite index fell 24.48 to 2,765.45. J.P. Morgan and 
Citigroup slipped as the financial services sector stumbled on 
worries about its exposure to weak capital markets in Latin 
America. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close  
Dow Industrials:        11,175.02  - 25.96
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1275  Declines 1723  Unchgd  560
