</P>
<P>
	FTC: No New Internet Privacy Laws  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Trade Commission recommended to  
Congress today that new Internet privacy laws are not needed to 
protect consumers because companies on the Web are voluntarily 
creating rules for handling sensitive personal information. In a 
14-page report, the FTC acknowledged that the online industry's 
efforts are not widespread, and some Web sites ``still do not 
understand the importance of consumer privacy.'' But with a 3-1 
endorsement, commissioners decided that new federal privacy laws 
are ``not appropriate at this time'' for the Internet. ``That is 
not to say all that needs to be done has been done,'' FTC Chairman 
Robert Pitofsky told the House Commerce Committee's 
telecommunications panel. He said that if progress does not 
continue at about the present pace, legislation might become 
necessary. 

</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch, Paine Webber Report  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and Paine Webber Group have  
the strong stock market to thank for their robust second-quarter 
earnings, which beat analysts' expectations. Merrill Lynch today 
reported net earnings of $664 million, or $1.57 a share, compared 
with $540 million, or $1.31 a share in the second quarter last 
year. The positive news came less than 24 hours after Merrill's 
president and chief operating officer abruptly resigned. Paine 
Webber reported profits of $157.6 million, or $1.02 a share. Those 
results were 27 percent better than the year-ago quarter when Paine 
Webber earned $123.6 million, or 82 cents a share. 

</P>
<P>
	SUV Sales Growth Still High but...  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- While sales of sport utility vehicles continue to  
increase faster than any other segment of the automotive market, 
demand for some models is leveling off as the category becomes more 
crowded. Demand has fallen, though, among models that have not been 
redesigned in several years. Industrywide, SUV sales were up 11 
percent in the first half, while the entire car and light truck 
market was up 7 percent. While the torrid sales pace of the last 
few years is unlikely to be sustained, analysts don't forecast a 
drop in SUV sales anytime soon. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S., Russia Sign Steel Agreement  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Russia has agreed to limit shipments of steel  
to the United States over a five-year period to avoid imposition of 
punitive American tariffs, Commerce Secretary William Daley 
announced today. The two sides signed the agreements covering 
different types of steel following marathon bargaining talks in 
Paris. The deals will set annual quotas for Russian steel 
shipments, reducing imports for all Russian steel shipments by 64 
percent this year compared to 1998, the Commerce Department said in 
a fact sheet. The quotas will gradually rise over four years, 
climbing to a high of 725,000 metric tons for hot rolled steel in 
2003, the department said. 

</P>
<P>
	Media General Profit Down 24 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Media General Inc. reported a 24 percent  
decrease in profits for the second quarter, a drop it blamed 
largely on lower revenues in its newsprint production division. The 
Richmond-based media conglomerate reported today that earnings for 
the quarter ended June 27 were $16.5 million, or 61 cents per 
share, down from $21.5 million, or 80 cents per share, in the same 
period of last year. Despite the drop, the results were well above 
analyst expectations of 55 cents per share, according to First Call 
Corp. Revenues for the quarter also dropped. The company reported 
$199.6 million in revenues, down from $211.5 million for the second 
quarter of 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	Wis. Records Opened in Tobacco Case  
</P>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Three law firms that represented Wisconsin  
in its lawsuit against the tobacco industry earned $3,032 an hour 
for each of the 24,733 hours they worked, newly released documents 
show. The state attorney general's office released the information 
yesterday in an attempt to end an open records lawsuit filed by 
three newspapers seeking to learn details on work the firms 
performed in winning the state a $5.9 billion settlement with 
cigarette makers. The hundreds of pages detail such activities as 
hundreds of hours spent reviewing thousands of previously secret 
tobacco documents and frequent travel to Washington in sometimes 
luxurious style. 

</P>
<P>
	Medicare Worrying Drug Companies  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Drug companies are lobbying hard against  
Medicare coverage for prescriptions, warning that research on new 
drugs for the elderly will depend on strong profits. ``Profits 
attract investment, investment pays for research and research leads 
to the new cures and treatments that will help and heal patients,'' 
said Alan Holmer, president of the Pharmaceutical Research and 
Manufacturers of America. He suggested that government price 
controls, would push down revenues to the companies and that in 
turn could have adverse impact on investment. 

</P>
<P>
	Roche Sales Up 7 Pct. in First Half  
</P>
<P>
	ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) -- Swiss pharmaceutical giant Roche's  
sales rose 7 percent in the first half, helped by demand for its 
new weight loss drug Xenical. Roche said it also expects good 
results for the full year. Sales in the first half of 1999 were 
$8.5 billion, up from $7.9 billion in the same period a year ago. 
First-half profit, which will be announced at a later date, should 
be up from a year ago, the company said. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Producer prices  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Retail sales  
</P>
<P>
	Thursday: Business inventories  
</P>
<P>
	Thursday: Consumer prices  
</P>
<P>
	Thursday: Jobless claims  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Industrial production  



  	   	
