<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Wants Pension Change Warning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Employers would be required to give  
workers at least 45 days notice for pension plan changes that could 
reduce their benefits, under a bill proposed by President Clinton 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Too many workers are left in the dark when their pension plans  
change,'' Clinton said in a written statement during a visit for a 
speech to the Communications Workers of America and a fund-raising 
dinner. ``Every worker deserves meaningful and timely information 
about changes to their retirement benefits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal is aimed primarily at alerting workers to a new  
kind of pension program called a ``cash balance'' plan, which is 
increasingly popular among big firms, such as Bell Atlantic, Bank 
of America, Chase Manhattan and the International Business Machines 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM said earlier this year it would save $200 million annually  
by switching its 141,000 U.S. employees to a cash balance program, 
in which pension benefits accumulate uniformly each year rather 
than growing slowly at the start of a worker's employment and 
accelerating as retirement approaches. 
</P>
<P>
	Cash balance plans typically are advantageous to younger  
employees who do not stay with a company long enough to get the 
benefits of a traditional pension program whose pay-out is 
calculated to a combination of age and service. 
</P>
<P>
	Long-term employees could wind up with fewer benefits in a cash  
balance plan than their traditional plan. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 12:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> All-Stars Feast on Home Cooking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Pete Rose running over Ray Fosse to score the  
winning run at Riverfront Stadium. Ted Williams hitting two homers 
at Fenway Park. Carl Hubbell striking out five straight future Hall 
of Famers at the Polo Grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	When it comes to hometown heroes, the All-Star game has produced  
more than its share. 
</P>
<P>
	Be it Hank Aaron homering in Atlanta, Sandy Alomar earning the  
MVP award in Cleveland or Johnny Vander Meer winning at old Crosley 
Field, the local star often highlights the show. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Pedro Martinez, Nomar Garciaparra and Jose Offerman  
got their chance in Boston on Tuesday night. And just like all the 
rest, they had cheering fans and comfortable surroundings on their 
side. 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra was greeted by a standing ovation from the Fenway  
faithful during Monday night's home run derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was unbelievable, it really is, going up there,'' the Red  
Sox shortstop said. ``I was nervous, without a doubt, but it's also 
kind of a nice, warm feeling when you just hear the crowd behind 
you like that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure you saw my face with a smile from ear to ear, and it  
still hasn't left. It was just something special,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he was just watching the sluggers swing away, Martinez  
drew an equally enthusiastic response. The packed crowd began 
chanting ``Pe-dro! Pe-dro!'' when he was introduced. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez was to get an early chance to make his mark Tuesday  
night. Starting for the AL, he was to face an imposing heart of the 
NL batting order -- Sammy Sosa, Mark McGwire, Matt Williams, Jeff 
Bagwell and Mike Piazza. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez looked forward to pitching to Sosa, a fellow star from  
the Dominican Republic. He figured Dominican fans would also enjoy 
the matchup. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going to be really confused because they love me as  
much as they love Sammy,'' he said. ``I think it's going to be a 
lot of fun for them to see us play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hubbell pitched his way into All-Star history in 1934, the  
second year the game was played. Starting in his own park, the New 
York Giants ace used his famed screwball to strike out Babe Ruth, 
Lou Gehrig, Jimmie Foxx, Al Simmons and Joe Cronin in succession. 
</P>
<P>
	Then in 1938, Vander Meer, best known for becoming the only  
pitcher to throw consecutive no-hitters, tossed three scoreless 
innings to get the victory in Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	In later years, the hitters took over at home. Joe DiMaggio  
homered at Yankee Stadium in 1939, Stan Musial connected at 
Sportsman's Park in St. Louis in 1948 and Al Rosen homered twice at 
Municipal Stadium in Cleveland in 1954. 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar's go-ahead home run in the seventh inning at Jacobs Field  
in 1997 made him the only hometown player to win All-Star MVP 
award. Then again, the honor was not presented until 1962, too late 
for either Williams -- who went 4-for-4 with five RBIs in 1946 -- or 
Rosen to get it. 
</P>
<P>
	Aaron (1972), Frank Howard (1969), Harmon Killebrew (1965) and  
Junior Gilliam (1959) also homered at home. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose made perhaps the most famous play in All-Star history when  
he crashed into Fosse to score the winning run in the 12th inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, several pitchers have fared well in their own parks,  
with Jerry Reuss winning at Dodger Stadium in 1980 and Jimmy Key 
getting the victory at SkyDome in Toronto in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	The last All-Star starter to win in his home park, however, was  
Montreal's Steve Rogers at Olympic Stadium in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez, Garciaparra and Offerman, a reserve infielder, hoped  
to help the AL narrow the NL's 40-28-1 lead Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what to expect,'' Garciaparra said. ``I kind of  
go out there and just take it all as it comes. But I tell you what 
-- me smiling, it will still be there tomorrow.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0038 </DOCNO>
