<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Elway Signs As Spokesman for Coors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- Coors Brewing Co. is hoping John Elway can  
lead another comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	Elway, who retired in April after 16 seasons with the Denver  
Broncos, is part of a campaign to revive lagging sales of Original 
Coors, the brewer's flagship brand. 
</P>
<P>
	A series of 30-second television ads featuring Elway and ESPN  
broadcaster Dan Patrick were set to debut Tuesday night during the 
major league All-Star Game. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a striking appropriateness between what John Elway  
represents as a human being and the character of the Original Coors 
brand,'' said senior vice president of marketing Bill Weintraub. 
``Each of them has a sense of values that's almost a mystique.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite its title as the flagship brand, Original Coors amounts  
to less than 10 percent of total sales for the brewery. Coors Light 
accounts for 70 percent of sales, according to Beer Marketer's 
Insights, a trade publication. 
</P>
<P>
	While sales of Coors Light increased 4 percent from 1997 to  
1998, Original Coors fell 5 percent, Beer Marketer reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The TV spots feature Patrick speaking from the bleachers of Mile  
High Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``He once scored 21 points in under two minutes,'' Patrick says.  
``He'll forever be known for a 15-play, last-scond drive to win a 
championship. You expected him to come from behind every once in a 
while. You just didn't expect him to do it 47 times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ad ends with Elway sitting outdoors wearing a denim shirt.  
He smiles for the camera and twists the cap off a bottle of Coors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Original Coors,'' he says. ``What'd you expect me to drink?''  
</P>
<P>
	Elway and Coors have discussed a marketing deal over the years,  
but beer industry guidelines prohibit brewers from using 
professional athletes until they retire. 
</P>
<P>
	Elway's spokesman Jeff Sperbeck said the future Hall of Fame  
quarterback decided to join Coors after meeting company CEO Peter 
Coors and president Leo Kieley III. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
