<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Presidental Field Shrinks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The crowded field of Republican presidential  
hopefuls began to dwindle Tuesday as Ohio Rep. John Kasich firmed 
up plans to drop out of the race and New Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith 
left the party. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said  
Kasich would quit the campaign on Wednesday with words of support 
for Texas Gov. George Bush, and that the Republican front-runner 
would be present to receive the endorsement. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich's planned exit, scripted to underscore his commitment to  
the GOP, couldn't have been more different than Smith's. 
</P>
<P>
	The second-term senator was defiant in a floor speech that  
sharply attacked the pollsters and consultants whom he said reigned 
supreme. ``I want my party to stand for something,'' the 
conservative lawmaker said, adding that Republicans routinely 
ignored their own party platform on issues as diverse as abortion, 
foreign policy and gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	As for his presidential hopes, Smith told reporters he had been  
in touch with the U.S. Taxpayers party and might run for president 
as its candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	While their leave-taking differed greatly in style, Kasich and  
Smith had found themselves in similar predicaments in the GOP 
presidential competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Both were mired in single digits in the nationwide public  
opinion polls -- Smith at 1 percent and Kasich at 3 percent. Both 
suffered from lagging fund raising that made the likelihood of 
political competitiveness increasingly remote, and left them unable 
even to join the tier of contenders closest to Bush. If anything, 
their situation worsened two weeks ago when Bush announced he had 
raised a record $36 million in the first six months of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith also faced the prospect of faring poorly in his home-state  
primary in New Hampshire. He had failed to draw the support of any 
of the other members of his state's congressional delegation. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign aides to Kasich declined comment on his plans.  
</P>
<P>
	The 47-year-old Ohio lawmaker had created a presidential  
exploratory committee and traveled the country energetically for 
months, with multiple trips to key states such as Iowa and New 
Hampshire. He also was willing to take potentially unpopular 
stands. 
</P>
<P>
	In one speech, he observed that eliminating government subsidies  
for business could finance a tax cut. In another, he outlined a 
proposal for Social Security under which baby boomers would accept 
smaller benefit checks in exchange for being allowed to divert part 
of their payroll taxes to potentially more lucrative but also 
riskier stock market accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said  
Kasich planned to say he does not intend to seek re-election to the 
House after his current term expires in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	House GOP rules impose a term limit on his tenure as chairman of  
the Budget Committee, and he must surrender that post at the end of 
his term. In nearly five years in the post, he has helped craft a 
series of spending cuts and was deeply involved in negotiations 
that led to passage of the balanced budget agreement of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	'' John is a good Republican, a fine candidate and he campaigned  
well for his vision of America. He's a good man and I wish him 
success,'' said Elizabeth Dole, another GOP presidential contender. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's departure poses a potential threat to the GOP's  
presidential hopes, however, particularly if he is followed out of 
the party by others trying to rally the Republicans to a more 
uncompromising set of conservative principles. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Bauer, a former Reagan aide running as a conservative,  
issued a statement that he had no intention of leaving the 
Republican Party. He urged Smith's supporters ``to continue their 
fight for the ideas we share by joining my campaign for the 
Republican nomination for president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Pat Buchanan, a third-time contender for the GOP nomination,  
issued a statement that contained no such urging. ``When a man as 
conservative and principles as Bob Smith walks away from the 
Republican Party, perhaps the problem is not with Sen. Smith, but 
with the Republican establishment,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, 58, has a strongly conservative voting record, and is one  
of the Senate's most consistent opponents of abortion. Recently, he 
has used his senatorial prerogative to slow efforts to write a 
final gun control compromise between the House and the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We won the revolution on issues. We won the revolution on  
principle,'' he said in a Senate speech that retraced Ronald 
Reagan's rise to power and the GOP takeover of the House and Senate 
in 1994. ``But the desire to stay in power caused us to start 
listening to the pollsters and the consultants again, who were 
telling us for some inexplicable reason that we need to walk away 
from issues...'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's GOP colleagues in the Senate reacted gingerly to his  
decision to quit the party and become an independent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know that he's doing this out of conviction,'' said Senate  
Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott said Smith had indicated that he still would like to be  
included in Republican caucus meetings and decisions. He said 
senators would discuss whether Smith should remain chairman of the 
ethics committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, chairman of the GOP senatorial  
campaign committee, said, ``Bob Smith has been a solid Republican 
... he ought to be treated as a member of the team.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
