<HEADLINE> House Congratulates U.S. Soccer Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The fever over the U.S. women's soccer team  
spread to Congress today. One female House member said the World 
Cup victory over China was ``an American dream come true.'' Another 
brought a soccer ball to the floor. 
</P>
<P>
	And House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has invited the  
champions to visit Washington for a ``national pep rally'' at the 
Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team won the championship 5-4 Saturday on penalty kicks  
after a scoreless tie through 120 minutes of play at the Rose Bowl 
in Pasadena, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	A nonbinding ``sense of the House'' resolution that passed by  
voice vote congratulates the team for raising the ``level of 
awareness and appreciation for women's sports'' nationwide and for 
becoming ``positive role models for American youth aspiring to 
participate in national and international level sports.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To illustrate the point, Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., brought a  
soccer ball to the House chamber. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we saw was an American dream come true,'' said Republican  
Rep. Judy Biggert of Illinois. She said little boys, for 
generations, could grow up wishing to emulate their athletic role 
models while girls had no one to idolize. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now little girls have the dream,'' Biggert said.  
  	   	
</P>
