<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 00:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Term-Limit Champion Mum on Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Tillie Fowler decried career  
politicians when she ran for Congress in 1992, vowing to serve no 
more than eight years if she won. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven years later, the top-ranking Republican woman in the House  
and one of its most influential leaders is facing the dilemma of 
whether to run again and risk the label of promise-breaker. 
</P>
<P>
	She will be the last to decide among 10 current House members  
who imposed term limits on themselves in 1992 and 1994; six have 
said they will not run again and three plan to seek another term. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fowler, 56, has been reluctant to talk about her term-limit  
pledge, calling it a ``non-issue.'' She also said she won't 
announce whether she will seek reelection until the end of the 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will not do so until I have the opportunity to learn about  
my leadership role and discuss the issue with my constituents,'' 
she said in a brief interview recently. 
</P>
<P>
	She referred other questions about her future to a letter she  
wrote to the Times-Union in Jacksonville last December. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bedrock of the commitment I made in 1992 is that I have no  
intention of being a career congressperson. Serving one additional 
term will not change that,'' she wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Term-limit supporters upset that she might break her pledge have  
panned Ms. Fowler while supporters think she should remain in 
Washington to wield her increasing political clout. 
</P>
<P>
	Her indecisiveness prompted a Florida Times-Union columnist to  
dub her ``Slick Tillie,'' a much different moniker than the ``Steel 
Magnolia'' nickname she has for her sweet Southern demeanor and her 
persistent -- some say stubborn -- personality. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fowler, who represents a majority Republican district in  
northeast Florida, is vice chairman of the Republican Conference, 
which includes all 223 GOP members of Congress. She ranks fifth in 
the House Republican hierarchy. 
</P>
<P>
	She recently filed paperwork to run for reelection. She said she  
was required to do so because she had received contributions and 
that it had nothing to do with whether she would run again. Her 
campaign already has collected $500,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fowler has run unopposed in the last three elections, and  
Democrats hope to line up a viable candidate if she runs again. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole basis for electing her was that she serve only eight  
years,'' said Tony Welch, a spokesman for the state Democratic 
Party. ``What is she going to say? Excuse me for lying to you eight 
years ago?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fowler's colleagues who won't seek reelection are Reps. Jack  
Metcalf, R-Wash.; Helen Chenoweth, R-Idaho; Matt Salmon, R-Ariz.; 
Mark Sanford, R-S.C.; Charles Canady, R-Fla.; and Tom Coburn, 
R-Okla. 
</P>
<P>
	Three who changed their minds and will seek reelection are Reps.  
George Nethercutt, R-Wash., Marty Meehan, D-Mass., and Scott 
McInnis, R-Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacksonville Mayor John Delaney, a Republican, would like Ms.  
Fowler to join the latter group, saying her leadership position 
will be good for the city and its two Navy bases. 
</P>
<P>
	``From a selfish point of view, I hope she abandons her four  
term-limit pledge,'' Delaney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dick Wilson, a Republican retiree, has voted for Ms. Fowler and  
thinks she has done a good job. But he wants her to call it quits. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of them ought to stick to their pledges,'' he said.  
``Fresh blood is a good thing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
