<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Murder Suspect Mistakenly Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- A man accused of killing his girlfriend by  
stabbing her more than 100 times was mistakenly set free because of 
a paperwork error, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen C. Brown was released July 6, but the error wasn't  
discovered until Monday, when he was scheduled for arraignment. He 
was still at large today. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, 37, was indicted on July 2 on a charge of first-degree  
murder in the May 22 death of Carol Buvik-Arnold, 37. The Pima 
County Jail apparently didn't receive notice of the indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheriff's Capt. Paul Wilson said the jail did receive notice of  
an earlier Justice Court complaint and arrest warrant against Brown 
that were dismissed, so he was released. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really isn't our place to question why that was the case,''  
Wilson said. ``The court sent us a document saying the charges were 
invalid, and we acted on that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, prosecutor Barbara LaWall said the document clearly  
stated that the earlier complaint and warrant were superseded by 
the July 2 indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the things that could have been done was, before you  
release someone on first-degree murder charges, is to verify 
whether or not they are supposed to be released,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Patti Noland, Superior Court clerk, said it's unclear what  
happened to a copy of the indictment that was placed in the 
sheriff's basket at the courthouse. 
</P>
<P>
	LaWall apologized, saying ``we're all very deeply concerned,''  
but said her office, the sheriff's office and the court ``are all 
operating short-staffed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The mistaken release is the jail's fourth in the past 16 months.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
