<HEADLINE> VA Supervisor Sentenced for Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- A former Veterans Affairs supervisor has been  
sentenced to 33 months in federal prison and two years probation 
for stealing $615,000 in disability benefit money. 
</P>
<P>
	Joy Cheri Brown, who was sentenced yesterday, will be permitted  
to remain free until her prison assignment is determined. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown had worked at the Veterans Service Center at Bay Pines in  
Pinellas County. She was arrested in January and charged with 
making false disability claims in the name of her fiance, a police 
officer who was unaware of the scam. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes good people make wrong decisions,'' Brown said prior  
to her sentencing. 
</P>
<P>
	She pleaded guilty March 9 and agreed to forfeit $339,000 in  
property and pay $615,472 in restitution, said executive Assistant 
U.S. Attorney Monte Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	VA Inspector General Richard Griffin cited the Brown case last  
month as an example of a flawed system in which the same workers 
who process claims also authorize payments. A copy of Griffin's 
report was obtained Monday by The Associated Press. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
