<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Senate Rejects First HMO Amendment  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrats trying to expand a GOP patients'  
rights bill lost the opening vote today as the Senate rejected 
their effort to allow women more HMO options in choosing doctors 
and hospitals. The vote was 52-48, mostly along party lines. The 
amendment, the first in a series of votes this week, would have 
allowed women to designate obstetrician-gynecologists as their 
primary care doctors. It also would have made sure that a woman 
could stay overnight in a hospital after a mastectomy if her doctor 
recommended it. 

</P>
<P>
	Alleged Railway Killer In Custody  
</P>
<P>
	EL PASO, Texas (AP) -- Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, the Mexican  
drifter suspected of killing eight people as he made his way around 
the country hopping freight trains, turned himself in today under 
an agreement that assures family visits, a psychological evaluation 
and promises that he would be safe in jail, said Bruce Casteel, 
commander of the Texas Rangers. The agreement does not shield 
Resendez-Ramirez from the death penalty, Casteel said. The tattoed 
ex-convict -- who is charged with three murders and linked to five 
other slayings, all of them in Texas, Kentucky and Illinois -- was 
on the FBI's 10 Most Wanted List. 

</P>
<P>
	SabreTech Charged in ValuJet Crash  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The airline maintenance company that packed up the  
oxygen canisters blamed for the 1996 ValuJet crash that killed 110 
people in the Everglades was charged with murder and manslaughter 
by state prosecutors today. Hours later, a federal grand jury 
indicted the company, SabreTech Inc., two of its mechanics and a 
maintenance director, alleging conspiracy, making false statements 
and, in the case of SabreTech, failing to properly train the 
personnel who handled hazardous material. A cargo fire virtually 
obliterated the aircraft and killed all 105 passengers and five 
crew members shortly after takeoff on May 11, 1996. 

</P>
<P>
	Iran Reformers, Hard-Liners Clash  
</P>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Tensions between reformers  
and hard-liners erupted into a sixth straight day of protests in 
the Iranian capital today. Riot police lobbed tear gas at thousands 
of activists, and gangs of hard-line vigilantes roamed Tehran with 
batons, trying to stave off more demonstrations. Shops and banks 
closed and pedestrians fled downtown as Iran faced its most raucous 
week since the 1979 Islamic Revolution. Since Thursday, two people 
have been killed in pro-democracy protests. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Urges China, Taiwan To Meet  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With China warning Taiwan it was ``playing  
with fire'' by hinting at independence, the State Department 
criticized both sides and urged them to hold ``meaningful 
substantive talks.'' In the meantime, American diplomats will meet 
in Taipei tomorrow with senior Taiwanese officials, spokesman James 
P. Rubin said. ``We're concerned that it is not helpful for the 
Taiwanese authorities to make statements that would make it harder 
to have dialogue,'' Rubin said today. Meanwhile, China intensified 
its attacks on Taiwanese President Lee Teng-hui, saying he was 
pursuing independence for the island. 

</P>
<P>
	Vatican Nixes Catholic Gay Ministry  
</P>
<P>
	VATICAN CITY (AP) -- The Vatican has ordered an American priest  
and a nun to end their 22-year ministry to gays and lesbians 
because they refused to condemn homosexuality as intrinsically 
evil. The Rev. Robert Nugent and Sister Jeannine Gramick are barred 
for life from ministering to gays and lesbians, the Congregation 
for the Doctrine of the Faith said. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Lower; Dow Down 25.96  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks dropped today as concerns about Latin  
America's economic recovery muted optimism about second-quarter 
earnings reports. At the close, the Dow Jones industrial average 
was down 25.96 to 11,175.02 after having fallen as much as 114 
points in early trading. On the NYSE, decliners outnumbered 
advancers 1,723-1,275. The Nasdaq composite index fell 24.48 to 
2,765.45. 

</P>
<P>
	Soccer Team Awaits Wheaties Decision  
</P>
<P>
	GOLDEN VALLEY, Minn. (AP) -- General Mills Inc. is working on a  
deal to bring the U.S. women's soccer team to a breakfast table 
near you. The Golden Valley-based maker of Wheaties is talking with 
the team and its players about an appearance on the cereal box, 
company spokesman Greg Zimprich said today. General Mills has been 
inundated with calls from people wondering if they would find the 
country's soccer sensations on supermarket shelves. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  





  	   	
