<DOCNO> APW19990713.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 07:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Credit Suisse Faces Losing License </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Financial Supervisory Agency has decided to  
recommend revoking the banking license of a unit of Credit Suisse 
Group AG because it allegedly tried to block an investigation of 
its handling of derivatives products, according to reports Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the Credit Suisse Group in Tokyo refused to  
comment on the reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese media said the FSA, which supervises financial markets,  
will seek the revocation of the license of Credit Suisse Financial 
Products, invoking Japan's banking law. 
</P>
<P>
	The FSA formally notified Japanese units of Credit Suisse of the  
findings of its investigation on Tuesday, Hideichiro Hamanaka, 
deputy head of the FSA, said at a news conference. But Hamanaka and 
other FSA officials refused to comment on the report's content. 
</P>
<P>
	The financial watchdog also turned over its report to the  
Financial Reconstruction Commission, which oversees the FSA and has 
the power to revoke the licenses of financial institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	Credit Suisse will have the opportunity at a hearing to respond  
to the findings, the media reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Financial Supervisory Agency has concluded that Credit  
Suisse Financial Products attempted to obstruct an examination 
launched by the watchdog agency on Jan. 20 by destroying documents 
and shipping others off to London, the media reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	The FSA also believes that Credit Suisse Group violated  
regulations separating banking and securities operations, the 
reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	The almost six-month investigation also covered three other  
group companies: Credit Suisse First Boston Tokyo branch, Credit 
Suisse Trust and Banking Co. and Credit Suisse First Boston 
Securities Japan Ltd. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
