<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Goldman Sachs To Acquire Hull Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Goldman Sachs Group Inc. has taken another step  
into electronic stock trading with the acquisition of the Hull 
Group for $531 million in stock, options and cash. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement Monday is the latest of several investments by  
Goldman Sachs this year in ventures that will challenge traditional 
stock markets like the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Hull Group, based in Chicago, is a leading market maker in  
stocks and stock derivatives worldwide. Market makers maintain firm 
bid and offer prices in a given security by standing ready to buy 
or sell shares at publicly quoted prices. Hull provides electronic 
market making and services on 28 exchanges in nine countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been looking at a lot of changes that have been  
affecting our various businesses,'' said Bob Steel, co-head of 
worldwide equities for Goldman Sachs. Goldman wants ``to enhance 
our skills in a way the marketplace is moving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Goldman formed a partnership with Merrill Lynch &AMP;  
Co. and Madoff Securities to develop an electronic trading system. 
In January, Goldman and E-Trade Group Inc. bought a minority stake 
in another electronic trading system called Archipelago. 
</P>
<P>
	A number of Wall Street firms are scrambling to form alliances  
and secure the technology that is changing the way people buy and 
sell stocks around the world. They are also putting pressure on 
traditional stock markets to make monumental changes, like staying 
open longer and listing more foreign stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and Salomon Smith Barney, for  
example, have linked up with Eclipse Trading, a new electronic 
trading company that will offer round-the-clock trading starting 
later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hull Group was founded in 1985 and today employs 250 people,  
including software developers, financial engineers, traders and 
support personnel. About two-thirds of its $103 million in revenues 
last year came from electronic trading. About 57 percent of 
revenues came from foreign exchanges, where countries rely more on 
electronic trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, the company filed documents with the Securities and  
Exchange Commission to sell its stock to the public, but decided to 
sell itself to Goldman Sachs. 
</P>
<P>
	This is Goldman's first purchase as a public company. The  
130-year-old investment bank raised $3.66 billion in its public 
offering in May, and is now using its stock as a currency to 
further its growth strategy. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
