<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Struggles Over Gun Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- While the Republican Congress struggles over  
relatively modest gun control measures, Democratic presidential 
rivals Al Gore and Bill Bradley are proposing far more stringent 
steps. And the NAACP is going to court to seek handgun 
restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	After a recess, the gun control issue is back.  
</P>
<P>
	Driven by the deadly outburst of school shootings last spring,  
the Senate passed a bill May 20 to tighten background checks for 
gun sales and require handgun safety locks. Republicans opposed to 
the gun restrictions stumbled over the issue before yielding to 
pressure to do something. Vice President Gore, in his capacity as 
president of the Senate, cast a tie-breaking vote for strengthened 
background checks on buyers at gun shows and pawnshops. People who 
buy guns from dealers already are subject to background checks, 
meant to keep guns away from people with records of crime, drug 
abuse or other patterns of misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	In the House, Republicans gained enough Democratic votes to ease  
the rules for gun-show sales. That led Democrats who wanted no less 
than the Senate had approved to vote against the whole business, on 
the ground that it would have weakened the current system. 
</P>
<P>
	The gun curbs were part of a bill aimed at controlling juvenile  
crime. It is now subject to negotiations between the Senate and 
House on their differing versions, which means bargaining over gun 
control provisions. 
</P>
<P>
	One question is how long to allow the government to check  
backgrounds of purchasers at gun shows for criminal records. The 
Senate bill provides three business days. The rejected House 
version was 24 hours, after which the buyer could get the gun 
unless that quick check turned up a disqualifying record. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate bill also includes a requirement that safety devices  
to lock or store handguns be sold with them and bans the import of 
high-capacity ammunition clips. 
</P>
<P>
	The next step for Congress would be to choose negotiators for  
the Senate and House to work on a final compromise bill. There are 
obstacles even to that, including a filibuster threat from a 
Republican opposed to the gun bill the Senate passed. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders have promised a conference on the bills involved.  
Republicans will control it, so what it produces almost certainly 
will be short of what the White House and Democratic leaders 
advocate. 
</P>
<P>
	And Gore upped his aims on Monday, proposing photo ID licenses  
for people who buy handguns, and a ban on the cheap pistols called 
``Saturday night specials.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, the former New Jersey senator challenging Gore for the  
Democratic presidential nomination, advocates those steps, plus 
registration of ``every one of the 65 million handguns in this 
country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said he isn't opposed but thinks his proposal would be just  
as effective. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are too many political leaders who take their marching  
orders from the gun lobby,'' Gore said in a speech at the Boston 
Police Department. ``Let's create a family lobby that is greater 
and more powerful than the gun lobby.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That would take some doing, given the powerhouse lobbying of the  
National Rifle Association. The last major gun control bills were 
enacted in 1993 and 1994, when Democrats controlled Congress -- and 
the gun lobby mobilized against them in the elections in which the 
Republicans took over. 
</P>
<P>
	``If politics is the art of the possible, it's time to expand  
the possible,'' Bradley wrote in The Washington Post. Bradley said 
that as president he would stand up to the NRA and to ``the 
conventional wisdom about what is politically feasible to reduce 
gun deaths in our country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Gore:  
</P>
<P>
	``As president, I will do whatever it takes to get the guns away  
from children and criminals and to close every loophole in our law 
books.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But a president can't keep promises like those without a  
Congress to pass his proposals. That wouldn't happen with the 
current lineup or one close to it. The Republicans majority in the 
Senate is just 55-45, and it's shakier in the House at 223-211 and 
an independent who normally votes Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People  
is filing suit for court-ordered gun controls to limit sales to 
licensed dealers and to keep people from buying more than one gun a 
month, arguing that black Americans are disproportionately affected 
by gun violence. 
</P>
<P>
	That won't win new laws. But it is another way to raise the  
issue. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and special  
correspondent for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington 
and national politics for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
