<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cisneros Aides' Charges Dropped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The independent counsel prosecuting former  
Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros has agreed to dismiss criminal 
charges against two former aides who were to stand trial with the 
one-time Clinton Cabinet member in September. 
</P>
<P>
	The action leaves Cisneros to stand trial alone on charges that  
he conspired with ex-mistress Linda Jones and the two aides to 
conceal during his Cabinet background check the scope of his 
financial payments to Ms. Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	Sylvia Arce-Garcia and John Rosales, who followed Cisneros from  
San Antonio to Washington when he became housing secretary, were 
indicted with Cisneros in December 1997 on charges they conspired 
to conceal details of the payments from FBI agents conducting 
Cisneros' Cabinet background check. 
</P>
<P>
	During a hearing Monday, prosecutors announced they will dismiss  
charges against Ms. Arce-Garcia and Rosales within six months after 
the Cisneros case is concluded provided that neither commits any 
crimes. Under the arrangement, the two admitted no wrongdoing and 
made no commitment to cooperate with the government's special 
prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones, who is serving 3 1/2 years in prison after herself  
running afoul of Independent Counsel David Barrett, is cooperating 
with the government under a deal that could result in a sentence 
reduction. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Ms. Arce-Garcia and Rosales welcomed prosecutors'  
action. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sylvia pled not guilty due to her strong belief that she  
should never have been charged,'' her lawyer, Abbe Lowell, said 
today. ``I am glad that the independent counsel has now seen fit to 
end this case against her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I have now been involved in perhaps my fifth or sixth case  
brought by independent counsels that never would have been brought 
by experienced career prosecutors,'' Lowell added. ``The end of the 
independent counsel statute is a good thing for the American 
justice system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffrey Gans, who represented Rosales, said he and his client  
were ``thrilled'' at prosecutors' decision to drop the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``John can get back to his life without having the cloud of an  
indictment hanging over his head,'' Gans said. ``It's been a 
tremendous weight lifted from his shoulders, a weight not of his 
own creation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rosales remained at the Department of Housing and Urban  
Development after Cisneros left in 1996 and is an assistant to 
Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo. Ms. Arce-Garcia is a top aide to 
Cisneros, who is president of the Spanish-language television 
network Univision. 
</P>
<P>
	The two were charged with one count each of conspiracy, and  
Rosales also was charged with two counts of making false 
statements. Prosecutors had hoped to convince the pair to become 
government witnesses, sources familiar with the investigation said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrett's office declined comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros acknowledged during his Cabinet background check that  
he gave Ms. Jones financial support after their extramarital affair 
became public in 1988, costing her marriage and career as a 
political fund raiser. But prosecutors contend he falsely told the 
FBI he never paid her more than $10,000 annually. 
</P>
<P>
	The 18-count indictment against Cisneros alleges he paid her  
more than $264,000 between 1990 and 1993. He has pleaded innocent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
