<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Intel's Second-Quarter Profit Jumps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE (AP) -- Intel Corp. reported Tuesday that its  
second-quarter profit rose 49 percent, but the results failed to 
meet Wall Street expectations amid a shift in company sales to less 
expensive computer chips. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel, the world's largest maker of microprocessor chips, said  
it earned $1.75 billion, or 51 cents a share, two cents below Wall 
Street expectations. That compared to a profit of $1.17 billion, or 
33 cents a share, in the second quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue rose 14 percent to $6.75 billion from $5.93 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Intel released its earnings after the markets closed. Intel  
shares were trading at $65.25 in after-hours trading on the Nasdaq 
Stock Market, after slipping 6 1/4 cents during the regular trading 
session to close at $65.37 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	The Santa Clara, Calif.-based Intel said microprocessor sales  
dropped slightly in the second quarter compared to the first 
quarter of this year. The company's average price for chips 
dropped, reflecting a shift to microprocessors as the brains of 
cheaper personal computers. Sales of sub-$1,000 PCs have boomed, 
prompting Intel to aggressively promote these less lucrative chips. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel chief executive Craig Barrett said the lower-than-expected  
earnings also ``reflected a seasonal slowdown, and we look forward 
to a strong second half.'' The company had regained share in the 
low-priced PC market and sales of the company's new microprocessor, 
the Pentium III, were growing strongly, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Pentium III processor, a high performance multimedia  
processor for the most demanding Internet applications, is on track 
to be our fastest ramping processor ever,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prudential Securities analyst Hans Mosesman agreed that Intel  
was in a better position to increase its sales during the second 
half of this year. ``They accomplished what they wanted to do and 
the outlook is positive,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mosesman noted that computer sales are always higher during the  
second half of the year, which should boost Intel's business. PC 
sales generally rise during this period due to back-to-school and 
holiday sales. 
</P>
<P>
	In the six months ended June 26, Intel said it earned $3.75  
billion, or $1.08 per share. That was up from a profit of $2.45 
billion, or 69 cents a share, in the first half of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue rose to $13.85 billion from $11.93 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	During the quarter, the company repurchased a total of 25  
million shares of common stock, at a cost of $1.5 billion, under an 
ongoing program. Since the program began in 1990, the company has 
repurchased 634.6 million shares at a total cost of $16.4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Although not reflected in this period, Intel acquired Dialogic  
Corporation for $780 million in cash. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
