<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 12:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bloody Tough for Brits in Home Open  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARNOUSTIE, Scotland (AP) -- It's tough being a British golfer at  
the British Open. 
</P>
<P>
	No one knows that better than Colin Montgomerie, who has labored  
under the expectations of a country growing increasingly desperate 
for a winner. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are well overdue, especially for a Scottish winner,  
especially my win,'' said Montgomerie, a Scot. ``Next question.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the better part of three decades, British golfers have  
struggled to win their Open. Aside from Nick Faldo's three wins, 
the only other British golfer to win on home soil in the last 30 
years was Sandy Lyle in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	The Claret Jug has gone out of the country so much it could  
qualify for frequent flyer miles. In that same 30 years, Americans 
have won 18 times, including the last four Opens. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anybody who wins it is a fantastic player,'' Northern  
Ireland's Darren Clarke said. ``It just so happens they've been 
Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Open returns this week to the game's Scottish roots at the  
Carnoustie Golf Links, just across the bay from St. Andrews. But 
even that may not boost British chances that pretty much begin with 
Montgomerie and end with Lee Westwood. 
</P>
<P>
	Though a full quarter of the 156-man field consists of British  
golfers, only a handful are serious threats to end a foreign 
dominance that began after Tony Jacklin won in 1969 at Royal 
Lytham. 
</P>
<P>
	Faldo, mired in the deepest slump of his career, is viewed as  
such a nonfactor that British bookies make him a 100-1 pick to win 
the Open he won three times during a six-year span ending in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still feel good about it, about being here,'' Faldo said.  
</P>
<P>
	And though Justin Rose captured the hearts and hopes of the  
country by finishing a shot behind last year as a 17-year-old 
amateur, he has played so badly since turning pro that he missed 22 
straight cuts before finally making it to the third round last 
month at the European Grand Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have any expectations this week,'' Rose said.  
</P>
<P>
	His countrymen do, though, and that has been the undoing of many  
British golfers in their home Open. 
</P>
<P>
	It took Faldo 11 British Opens and much criticism from the  
country's press before he broke through in 1987 at Muirfield with 
his first Open victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Montgomerie has won 20 times on the European tour, including at  
Loch Lomond last week with a closing 64. But he has missed the cut 
in five of the last seven Opens. 
</P>
<P>
	``The amount of pressure I put on myself is enough, so there is  
no added pressure,'' Montgomerie insisted. 
</P>
<P>
	Westwood had won the Loch Lomond the week before the Open last  
year and went into it anointed the favorite by the bookies and his 
country's press. But he shot himself out of contention with a pair 
of 78s in the last two rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would think there would be less expectation,'' Westwood  
said. ``I'm fairly comfortable with most situations now.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 19:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Slams GOP Tax Cut Approach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Accusing Republicans of taking a  
``spend now, pay later'' approach, President Clinton said Tuesday 
that GOP tax cut plans would leave no money for fixing Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	``That will not happen on my watch,'' Clinton pledged.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's sharp rhetoric drew loud cheers from the annual  
convention of the Communications Workers of America. 
</P>
<P>
	The combative stance marked a swift turn from what Republicans  
described as a cordial discussion -- but no agreement -- with the 
president Monday evening about how to spend $2.9 trillion in 
projected budget surpluses over the next decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, at a political fund-raiser, Clinton harshly condemned the  
Coast Guard's tactics in trying to prevent six Cuban refugees from 
swimming to shore in Miami on June 29. They were blasted with a 
hose in their rowboat and one was doused with pepper spray. 
</P>
<P>
	``What happened with the way those people were sprayed and all  
that, it was outrageous,'' Clinton said. ``I want you to know it 
was not an authorized policy. None of us knew anything about it in 
Washington until we saw it on the news or read it in the 
newspapers, just like you did. We have taken vigorous steps to make 
sure it does not happen again and the incident is being thoroughly 
investigated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In between his luncheon labor speech and the fund-raising  
dinner, the president squeezed in an afternoon of golf at the 
Indian Creek Country Club. He also helped raise up to $1 million 
for the Florida Democratic Party at the Coral Gables home of sugar 
grower Alfonso Fanjul. Guests were asked to contribute from $25,000 
to $100,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Medicare, the medical insurance program for the elderly and  
disabled, is a hot political topic, particularly here in Florida 
among its large population of senior citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	Suggesting Republicans were advocating tax cuts for political  
gains, Clinton said, ``I realize that it's tempting for a Congress 
to say ... 16 months before election, let's do what is most 
immediately pleasing, whether it's right for America over the long 
run or not. ... This is a mistake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and the Republicans generally agree that the $1.9  
trillion part of the projected surplus generated by Social Security 
should be used to reduce the national debt. However, Republicans 
want to use most of the remaining $1 trillion for tax cuts, while 
Clinton and Democrats want to use it for Medicare, a much smaller 
$250 billion tax reduction, and defense and domestic spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are putting together a tax plan today that leaves no  
resources available from the surplus for strengthening Medicare,'' 
the president said. ``That is why I am asking Republican leaders, 
in the interest of saving Medicare, to reconsider the size of their 
tax cut plan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said that without help from the surplus, Medicare spending  
increases would fall 60 percent below expected cost hikes in 
private insurance over the next quarter century. 
</P>
<P>
	``That would severely cut both the quality and the quantity of  
health care available to seniors on Medicare, and that will not 
happen on my watch. I won't let it happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said that with his own $250 billion tax cut proposal, ``We  
can still have a good size tax cut, but not as large as the one the 
Republican leaders propose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the nation faces a choice. It can wipe out the  
national debt, insure the solvency of Social Security and Medicare 
and approve his more modest tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Or a return to the spend now, pay later approach that will not  
save and strengthen Medicare, may or may not lengthen the life of 
Social Security, will certainly cut education and other vital 
programs and ... over the long run will be far more costly to every 
person in this room and every working family in the entire United 
States.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 14:10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ValuJet Crash Prompts Indictments  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- An airline maintenance company was charged today  
with murder and manslaughter in the 1996 ValuJet crash that killed 
110 people in the Everglades. SabreTech Inc. also was charged with 
unlawful transportation of hazardous waste. The third-degree murder 
and second-degree manslaughter charges, both state charges, are 
felonies. An attorney for SabreTech said the company was not going 
to be made a scapegoat for the accident. Kenneth Quinn said 
prosecutors ignored findings that the accident was caused by 
mistakes by ValuJet, SabreTech and the Federal Aviation 
Administration. 

</P>
<P>
	Alleged Railway Killer in Custody  
</P>
<P>
	EL PASO, Texas (AP) -- The sister of Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, the  
train-riding fugitive suspected of killing eight people, helped 
negotiate his surrender today to the Texas Rangers. 
Resendez-Ramirez, 39, turned himself in to Sgt. Drew Carter at a 
border checkpoint this morning. The surrender agreement included 
assurances of family visitation rights, a psychological evaluation 
and promises that he would be safe in jail. It does not shield 
Resendez-Ramirez from the death penalty. Carter was contacted 
Sunday by Resendez-Ramirez's sister, who said she had been in 
contact with her brother through an intermediary. Carter met with 
her Sunday night and yesterday to negotiate the surrender. 

</P>
<P>
	Kasich To Withdraw, Endorse Bush  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ohio Rep. John Kasich will withdraw from the  
race for the Republican presidential nomination and endorse Texas 
Gov. George W. Bush, Republican officials said today. The officials 
said they expected Bush to be present for Kasich's formal 
announcement, set for tomorrow afternoon. GOP officials said they 
did not expect Kasich to reverse a decision to retire from Congress 
at the end of his current term. The Ohio Republican was first 
elected to the House in 1982. 

</P>
<P>
	Movement Against Milosevic Growing  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serbia's main opposition group  
collected thousands of signatures today on a petition calling for 
Slobodan Milosevic's resignation, and a key opposition leader 
announced a separate effort to oust the Yugoslav president. In the 
latest of near-daily protests against Milosevic, several thousand 
people turned out for an opposition rally in a central Serbian town 
even though police tried to limit attendance by blocking roads. 
Opposition leader Vuk Draskovic unveiled a campaign aimed at 
persuading Milosevic to step down, promising a series of rallies 
starting Saturday in the central town of Kragujevac. 

</P>
<P>
	Study: Not-For-Profit HMOs Better  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Not-for-profit HMOs are more likely than  
for-profit ones to make sure patients get prenatal care, timely 
shots and other preventive tests and treatment, a study found. The 
study, published in tomorrow's Journal of the American Medical 
Association, concluded that for-profit HMOs' moneymaking mission 
compromises patient care. The findings have long been suspected 
because not-for-profit health plans generally spend a higher 
proportion of premiums on patient care compared with for-profits. 
That's because for-profits have to satisfy investors and pay higher 
wages. 

</P>
<P>
	Singapore No. 1 in Competitiveness  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Despite the impact of the Asian financial  
crisis, Singapore once again ranks as the world's most competitive 
nation, according to a survey released today. The United States 
moved up to second place from last year's third-place rating, while 
Hong Kong dropped to third. The report, prepared by the World 
Economic Forum, measures eight variables -- including government 
regulations, technology and labor conditions -- to try to determine 
which economies have the best ability to achieve rapid growth. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Lower; Dow Down 25.96  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks dropped today as concerns about Latin  
America's economic recovery muted optimism about second-quarter 
earnings reports. At the close, the Dow Jones industrial average 
was down 25.96 to 11,175.02 after having fallen as much as 114 
points in early trading. On the NYSE, decliners outnumbered 
advancers 1,723-1,275. The Nasdaq composite index fell 24.48 to 
2,765.45. 

</P>
<P>
	Selig Won't Reinstate Pete Rose  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Bud Selig said today that Pete Rose can forget  
about reinstatement to baseball as long as he's commissioner. While 
Rose is among the 100 players on the ballot for baseball's 
All-Century team, he wasn't invited to the news conference before 
tonight's All-Star game and won't be asked to any ceremonies if 
he's among the winners. Former commissioner Bart Giamatti kicked 
Rose out of baseball for gambling on the sport. Rose applied for 
reinstatement in September 1997, but Selig hasn't announced a 
decision. From his statements today, it's clear the only two 
options Selig is considering are rejection or never acting on the 
petition. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
