<HEADLINE> Euro Rallies After Hitting New Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell Tuesday against the euro and the  
Japanese yen, with the euro rallying back from a new low set 
earlier in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0164, up  
from late Monday's $1.0148. Earlier in Tuesday's trading, the euro 
slid to $1.0108, the currency's lowest level since it was 
introduced in January. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 121.32 Japanese yen, down from  
122.23 yen late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The afternoon recovery by the euro, which represents 11 European  
nations, came amid reports Japan's central bank may try to bolster 
the sagging currency against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the rebound, however, the euro remains about 15 percent  
below its peak of almost $1.19 on Jan. 4, its first day of trading, 
and many market analysts expect it will trade 1-to-1 with the 
dollar or lower before long. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Tuesday, the dollar also was quoted at 1.5766  
Swiss francs, down from 1.5830 a day earlier, and 1.4815 Canadian 
dollars, up from 1.4796. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound rose to $1.5574 from late Monday's $1.5559.  
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.9216  
German marks, down from 1.9290; and 6.4537 French francs, down from 
6.4609. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
