<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Ban a US Beef Dealer's Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERN, Switzerland (AP) -- An American beef distributor has been  
removed from the list of approved importers into Switzerland after 
traces of banned hormones were found in meat, Swiss health 
inspectors said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Swiss officials asked the United States to take action against  
the producer after two samples out of 26 tested were found to 
contain the cancer-causing hormone diethylstiloesterol, banned both 
in both countries. 
</P>
<P>
	In five other pieces of meat, inspectors from the Federal  
Veterinary Office found traces of melengestrol, a hormone banned in 
Switzerland but used in the United States to stimulate the growth 
of cattle. 
</P>
<P>
	The company involved was not identified  
</P>
<P>
	The news comes the day after the United States and Canada were  
given the green light to impose $124 million per year of sanctions 
against imports from the European Union over a long-running ban by 
Brussels on hormone-treated beef, which it claims may cause cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Switzerland is not a member of the EU, and the Federal  
Veterinary Office said there was no question of banning U.S. beef 
entirely, although the use of synthetic hormones and steroids is 
forbidden. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 1,000 tons of U.S. beef was imported into Switzerland  
in 1998. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
