<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Nove Lower; Dow Off 77.25 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell from their lofty highs today as  
banking and financial stocks were hit hard by concerns about Latin 
America's economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 77.25 at 11,123.73 after having achieved three closing highs 
in the past four sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also dropped. The Nasdaq composite  
index fell 21.72 to 2,768.72 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 slipped 
9.67 to 1,389.43. 
</P>
<P>
	J.P. Morgan fell 3 1/16 to 137 1/2 and Citigroup slipped 1 3/8 to 47 3/8,  
as the financial services sector stumbled on worries about its 
exposure to weak capital markets in Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	But Merrill Lynch rose 1 5/16 to 79 3/16 on  
stronger-than-expected second quarter profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Latin American markets fell sharply Monday on what  
analysts described as lingering concern about the state of the 
region's economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks also were under pressure from investor concerns that the  
brisk economy will cause the Federal Reserve to raise interest 
rates again this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market has been overbought quite a bit in the few weeks  
and we expected it to have some kind of reaction,'' said Eugene 
Mintz, financial markets analyst at Brown Brothers Harriman &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks were mostly down as investors prepared for  
Intel to release its second quarter earnings after the market 
closed. Intel, the world's leading computer chip maker, was down 3/8 
at 65 1/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Biotechnology giant Amgen soared 5 7/16 at 71 3/4 after the  
company's profit report late Monday beat Wall Street estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com rose 5 3/16 to 122 9/16 after announcing it is  
expanding it Web site to include toys and electronics. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 2-to-1 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 356.67 million 
shares, up from Monday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 3.98 at 651.81, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 6.96 at 808.58. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
