<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe Frets Over Euro's Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Champagne corks popped in a burst of  
``euro-phoria'' across the continent last January as Europe took 
its biggest step toward unity: launching a single currency for 11 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	But leaders who gushed about the newborn euro as a symbol of  
united Europe's economic power and political maturity are now faced 
with the embarrassment of dealing with a child who is not living up 
to expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than challenge the dollar for dominance in world  
financial markets, the euro has nose-dived -- weighted down by 
sluggish growth in Europe compared to the booming United States. It 
also is suffering from conflicting signals from European 
policy-makers about how low the currency would or should be allowed 
to go. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly there are teething troubles,'' said Peter Dixon,  
senior economist with Commerzbank in Frankfurt. ``This is not what 
was envisaged six months ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After peaking at almost $1.19 on Jan. 4, its first day of  
trading, the euro has lost 15 percent of its value, hitting a new 
low Tuesday in European trading of $1.0108. In New York, the euro 
finished at $1.0164. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite constant assurances from government leaders and central  
bankers about the euro's underlying value, market-watchers expect 
it will be 1-to-1 with the dollar or even lower before long. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven of the 15 European Union nations adopted the euro:  
Austria, Belgium, Germany, Finland, France, Ireland, Italy, 
Luxembourg, Netherlands, Portugal and Spain. Sweden, Denmark and 
Britain opted to stay out for now. Greece did not meet the economic 
criteria for entry, but hopes to join in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the currency is used mainly by corporate and government  
bookkeepers. Euro bills and coins won't start circulating until 
2002. 
</P>
<P>
	But its decline is still felt by ordinary people. German marks,  
French francs, Italian lira and other national currencies are 
locked into a fixed exchange rate with the euro, meaning they move 
in the same direction. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro's slide has its benefits, helping the European economy  
recover from last year's doldrums by boosting exports and 
encouraging growth. That improvement, in turn, fuels rallies on 
European stock markets, along with U.S. investors hunting for 
bargains. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet there are liabilities, and not just for Europeans who find  
their vacations abroad more expensive. 
</P>
<P>
	A weak euro irritates the United States, exacerbating its trade  
deficit and making it harder to sell U.S.-made products in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Going into a G-7 finance ministers meeting on Tuesday in  
Brussels, Belgium, U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers made no 
secret that he intended to talk about the euro. ``The U.S. can't be 
an importer of last resort,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The weak euro also hurts European homebuyers by pushing up  
mortgage rates, which are linked to rates on long-term bonds. Rates 
have climbed because of investor worries that higher prices 
Europeans have to pay for imports will reignite inflation, which is 
almost flat now. 
</P>
<P>
	And if the euro falls too far, it could spur the kind of  
investor flight that hit other parts of the globe over the past two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 1-to-1 parity is an important psychological level,'' said  
Joachim Fels, senior economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. If 
the euro drops much below that, ``investors may lose confidence in 
euro-assets. More people are likely to bail out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The European Central Bank, which sets monetary policy for the  
euro countries, insists the currency's fall is temporary and 
nothing to worry about. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech last week, bank vice president Christian Noyer  
acknowledged the euro has ``fluctuated significantly,'' but pointed 
out its current level is roughly where the constituent currencies 
were two summers ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet while European Central Bank president Wim Duisenberg has  
said he's not losing any sleep over the euro's slide, others, like 
Hans Tietmeyer, president of the respected German central bank and 
an ECB council member, have expressed dismay. 
</P>
<P>
	German Finance Minister Hans Eichel, who last week said the  
euro's level was ``no problem'' and ``good for exports,'' urged his 
EU colleagues on Monday to coordinate economic policy better to 
send a positive signal to financial markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, his Finnish colleague, Sauli Niinistoe, sent the euro  
lower by suggesting there were ``natural reasons'' for its 
weakness. 
</P>
<P>
	The mixed messages confuse the markets and contribute to the  
euro's downward trend, analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
	Duisenberg faces more questions on the bank's stance at his  
regular monthly news conference Thursday. But analysts say it may 
be too late for the ECB to try to intervene in the market to boost 
the euro. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be perceived as an admission of weakness,'' Dixon  
said, and probably end up sending the euro even lower. 
</P>
<P>
	At this point, he and other analysts say, the best strategy may  
be to wait for Europe's economic recovery to push the euro up 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market has to make the jump by itself,'' said Deutsche  
Bank analyst Joachim Goldberg, who projects the euro will be back 
up around $1.08 to $1.10 in six months. ``It's just a question of 
timing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 10:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
