<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: African Aid Key To U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stung by criticism that African countries get  
little more than lip service in humanitarian aid, Secretary of 
State Madeleine Albright told the NAACP today that ensuring freedom 
and economic stability on the African continent remain major U.S. 
priorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nowhere in the world are there stronger or braver people than  
those Africans working at the grass roots for justice and lasting 
peace,'' Albright told an audience of 2,000 at New York's Hilton 
Hotel, where the NAACP is holding its 90th annual national 
convention. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. policy-makers have been accused by many segments of black  
America, including the NAACP, of treating African nations like poor 
stepchildren when international aid dollars are passed out. 
</P>
<P>
	The criticism was renewed during the military action in  
Yugoslavia as aid flowed freely for Balkan refugees while less 
attention and funding were doled out to civilians displaced in 
conflicts in Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Others in black leadership also questioned why such aggressive  
military action was taken by U.S.-led NATO forces to blunt ethnic 
slaughter in Yugoslavia and no such force was used while lives were 
being taken in ethnic clashes in Rwanda a few years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright said the United States has been able to do more to stop  
the warring in Europe than in Africa because America has more 
allies in Europe to share risks and ``promote understanding and 
economic integration to foster peace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In Africa, such resources are scarce,'' Albright said. ``But  
that's no excuse for disengaging or giving up. Instead it is a 
challenge, as President Clinton has suggested, to use the lessons 
of Kosovo to help us do better in Africa.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albright announced Clinton will soon appoint a special envoy to  
focus on reducing human rights abuses and revitalizing the regional 
peace effort in strife-torn Sudan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have taken this step because the people of Sudan deserve  
not delay but decisiveness,'' Albright said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
