<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Refugee Threatened Fire on Boat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- One of 16 Cubans fleeing their country aboard a  
boat doused the vessel with fuel and threatened to set it afire 
during a four-hour standoff with the Coast Guard, The Miami Herald 
reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The standoff miles off the Miami Beach shoreline ended  
peacefully when the Cubans -- 13 men and three women -- willingly 
boarded a cutter Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Under U.S. policy, Cubans who reach land are allowed to stay but  
those picked up at sea are sent back. 
</P>
<P>
	Coast Guardsmen rode alongside the Cubans' 16-foot motorized  
wooden boat, urging them to stop. At one point, as the Guardsmen 
got close, one of the Cubans grabbed a container and sloshed fuel 
around the boat, motioning that he would set it afire if the boat 
was stopped. 
</P>
<P>
	``The crew could smell the fuel, it was so strong,'' Petty  
Officer Jeff Murphy told The Miami Herald. ``After he doused the 
vessel, it became clear they were serious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The standoff ended in international water about 17 miles off  
Miami Beach when the vessel's motor stopped, possibly because of 
mechanical failure, and the boat began to drift. 
</P>
<P>
	That peaceful conclusion was in contrast with a tense  
interdiction Friday in an inlet in north Broward County, which 
ended when a Coast Guard cutter collided with a boatload of 12 
Cubans. 
</P>
<P>
	The collision threw the refugees into the ocean and one woman  
drowned. The 11 survivors were taken to the U.S. Naval Station at 
Guantanamo, Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Coast Guard statistics show 951 Cubans have been detained at sea  
so far this year. That is almost as many as the 1,047 interdictions 
for all of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a threat of a mass exodus,'' said Jose Basulto,  
president of Brothers to the Rescue, a Miami-based Cuban exile 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard came under scrutiny last month after television  
helicopters captured images of Coast Guardsmen using pepper spray 
and water hoses to deter six Cubans trying to reach U.S. soil. 
</P>
<P>
	Two men who swam to shore were arrested by police. Four others  
were captured by the Coast Guard. The incident sparked protests, 
and all of six men were allowed to remain in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	A Coast Guard investigation led to the reassignment of eight  
Coast Guardsmen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
