<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EEOC Alters Complaint Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission  
announced regulations Monday intended to streamline the process for 
federal employees filing discrimination complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	The guidelines require all agencies to set up programs for  
informally resolving disputes both before and after complaints are 
filed. They also eliminate the authority of agencies to make final 
decisions in cases where an administrative judge has issued a 
recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	EEOC Chairwoman Ida L. Castro said the regulations are part of  
an effort to improve the complaint process for federal employees 
and applicants ``by eliminating unnecessary layers of review and 
addressing perceptions of unfairness in the system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For example, in the past, agencies could reverse or modify an  
administrative judge's decision on whether the law had been broken. 
The new regulations no longer allow agencies to alter the decisions 
of the judge. The agency can either implement the order or file an 
appeal with the commission. 
</P>
<P>
	By next year, agencies must establish or make available  
alternative dispute resolution programs that incorporate 
confidentiality, neutrality and enforceability. 
</P>
<P>
	Other regulations seek to relieve additional burdens on the  
system. For example, some cases currently would be broken down and 
then processed separately. The new rules seek to consolidate 
related claims brought by the same party and add a provision for 
the dismissal of spin-off complaints, which are complaints about 
the processing of existing complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	Other provisions encourage settlements between agencies and  
complaining parties. 
</P>
<P>
	The regulations -- published in the Federal Register -- will take  
effect Nov. 9 and apply to pending cases. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
