<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NAACP Sees Progress in Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The NAACP reported improvement Tuesday in how  
the hospitality and telecommunications industries treat blacks in 
hiring, contracting, marketing and philanthropic activities. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's largest and oldest civil rights organization issued  
report cards rating companies in both regards at its 90th annual 
national convention. 
</P>
<P>
	``We saw a whole lot of failures when we started this, but now  
we are seeing incremental improvement,'' NAACP President Kweisi 
Mfume said. ``We aren't satisfied, but we are seeing positive 
change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grades are based on how firms hire, promote, procure, contract,  
advertise and donate to minority causes. 
</P>
<P>
	When the first survey was conducted in 1997, the NAACP and 55  
other black organizations urged a boycott of 10 national hotel 
chains because of their hiring and promotion practices. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Westin Hotels, Best Western International, Radisson  
Hospitality Worldwide, Renaissance Hotels and Resorts, Choice 
Hotels International, Holiday Inn Worldwide and Omni Hotels refused 
to participate. All got ``F'' grades. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the 13 hotel firms studied in this year's survey got  
less than a ``C.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They included Marriott International, B+; Cendant Hotels, B+;  
Hilton Hotels Corp., B; Best Western International, B-; Promus 
Hotel Corp., B-; Choice Hotels International, C+; Hyatt Hotels 
Corp., C+; Radisson Hospitality Worldwide, C+; Four Seasons Hotels, 
C+; Bass/Holiday, C;, Wyndham, C; Starwood, C; and Omni, C. 
</P>
<P>
	Mfume said that since the Adam's Mark Hotels chain is involved  
in pending litigation with the NAACP, that company wasn't graded. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were laughed at three years ago by the hotel industry, but  
others took us very seriously,'' Mfume said. He said Bill Marriott, 
a principal in the Marriott Hotel chain, met with NAACP officials 
after the first grades were issued to see how his company could do 
better. 
</P>
<P>
	NAACP National Board Chairman Julian Bond called the report  
cards ``a new mechanism to achieve an old goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are interested in economic justice,'' Bond said.  
</P>
<P>
	Mfume said the improvement among telecommunications companies  
wasn't as dramatic as that of the hotels. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 15 companies studied, just one, Alltel, received a  
failing grade for not responding to the survey. Mfume said he was 
told by company officials they couldn't respond because of changes 
in their corporate structure. Mfume said, ``We take exception to 
that position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A company spokesman was not immediately available for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	BellSouth and Bell Atlantic both received B+; SBC, Ameritech and  
GTE, B; AT&AMP;T, B-; Cincinnati Bell and MCI WorldCom, C+; Excel, 
Sprint, Frontier, USWest and AirTouch, C; and QWest, D+. 
</P>
<P>
	Mfume said financial service companies would be the next  
industry surveyed. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
