<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Carpal Tunnel Symptoms Common </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Although only 2.7 percent of adults can be  
diagnosed with carpal tunnel syndrome, many more suffer pain, 
tingling and numbness in their hands, a new study has found. 
</P>
<P>
	The Swedish study is among a few to estimate the general  
prevalence of carpal tunnel syndrome, said the authors and experts 
not involved in the work, published in Wednesday's Journal of the 
American Medical Association. 
</P>
<P>
	And the study highlights the difficulty of diagnosis -- neither  
physical examination nor electrical-impulse testing alone 
consistently identified the nerve problem on which the potentially 
disabling disorder is blamed, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, no consensus exists on how to diagnose carpal tunnel  
syndrome, even though U.S. doctors perform 200,000 surgeries a year 
to treat it, and direct U.S. medical costs are estimated at more 
than $1 billion, the outside experts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Carpal tunnel syndrome has been on the rise in developed  
countries with increasing computer-keyboard use. It is also getting 
more attention in industries with jobs involving repetitive wrist 
or finger motions, ranging from meat processing to operating a cash 
register. 
</P>
<P>
	Given the enormous impact of carpal tunnel syndrome, a strong  
base of knowledge might be expected to exist about its cause, 
progression and diagnosis, said the experts, Drs. Alfred Franzblau 
and Robert A. Werner of the University of Michigan School of Public 
Health. 
</P>
<P>
	``Surprisingly, this is not the case,'' they wrote in an  
editorial accompanying the study. 
</P>
<P>
	Because disagreement exists about whether carpal tunnel syndrome  
is defined by results of physical examination or electrical 
nerve-function tests, both were included, said researchers led by 
Dr. Isam Atroshi of Hassleholm-Kristianstad Hospital in 
Kristianstad, Sweden. 
</P>
<P>
	``Symptoms of pain, numbness and tingling in the hands are  
common in the general population,'' reported the authors, who found 
symptoms in 14.4 percent of subjects. 
</P>
<P>
	About one-fifth of those have carpal tunnel syndrome, a  
prevalence of 2.7 percent, they said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
