<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Flyers Announcer Hospitalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- Former Philadelphia Flyers announcer Gene  
Hart was in critical condition Tuesday with illnesses stemming from 
a ``malignancy,'' but was holding his own, team doctor Jeff 
Hartzell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart became severely dehydrated and developed an infection  
following chemotherapy to treat a tumor, Hartzell said. He was 
admitted to the critical-care unit of Our Lady of Lourdes Hospital 
on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has shown some improvement over the last 48 hours,''  
Hartzell said. 
</P>
<P>
	The broadcaster was under sedation and on a ventilator, Hartzell  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some individuals do respond to these treatments and we're  
hoping and praying that Gene is one of them,'' Hartzell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart underwent heart bypass surgery in 1985 and has been on  
kidney dialysis for almost a year due to complications from 
diabetes. 
</P>
<P>
	Known for years as the ``Voice of the Flyers,'' Hart was the  
play-by-play man for the Flyers on radio and television from their 
inaugural season in 1967-68 until 1994-95. For the last two 
seasons, he has called the games for the Philadelphia Phantoms, the 
Flyers' American Hockey League affiliate, on cable. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart was inducted into the Hockey Hall of Fame in 1997, one of  
20 broadcasters so honored. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
