<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Basketball Star Recker Recovering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DURANGO, Colo. (AP) -- Former Indiana basketball star Luke Recker  
remained in good condition Tuesday at a southwestern Colorado 
hospital recovering from injuries received in a weekend car crash 
allegedly caused by a drunken driver. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercy Hospital spokesman Joe Wade Plunk said Recker may leave  
the hospital as early as Wednesday.` 
</P>
<P>
	Recker suffered a severe laceration on his left ear and a head  
laceration. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's getting better,'' Recker's father, Clair Recker, said.  
``There's no reason to believe he won't make a full recovery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Recker and four friends were injured in the three-car accident  
Saturday night on County Road 240 near Durango in southwestern 
Colorado. He was a passenger in a vehicle driven by John Hollberg, 
23, of Senoia, Ga., who was killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the most seriously injured were Kelly Craig, 19, of  
Jasper, Ind., identified by Plunk as Recker's girlfriend, who 
suffered a spinal fracture, and her brother, Jason Craig, 17, who 
suffered a closed head injury, Plunk said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Craigs were placed in the intensive care unit of the San  
Juan Regional Medical Center in Farmington, N.M. 
</P>
<P>
	Plunk said the medical center advised him late Monday that Kelly  
Craig had recovered movement in her arms but not in her legs. 
</P>
<P>
	A hospital spokeswoman said Kelly Craig was in serious condition  
Tuesday and Jason Craig, a high school football player, remained in 
critical condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Recker and his companions were traveling to a carnival in  
Durango when a truck driven by Bob Hardwick, 21, of Durango, 
drifted across the center line at about 70 mph, State Trooper Mike 
McGuire said. 
</P>
<P>
	The truck sideswiped a pickup carrying 11 people in Recker's  
group and collided head-on with the car in which Recker was a 
passenger. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardwick was being held for investigation of vehicular homicide,  
reckless driving, driving under the influence, careless driving 
resulting in bodily injury and vehicular assault. During a court 
appearance Monday, La Plata County Judge Martha Mino reduced 
Hardwick's bond from $500,000 to $50,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
