<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stocks Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed lower Tuesday, with  
the key index in Taipei tumbling 3 percent as tensions mounted 
between Taiwan and China after Taiwanese President Lee Teng-hui 
said Beijing should regard the island as a separate country. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taipei market's key Weighted Stock Price Index fell 259.40  
points, or 3.1 percent, to 8,204.50. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese officials have called Lee a ``liar and separatist''  
after he said in an interview with a German radio last week that 
Taiwan's relations with the mainland are ``state-to-state'' rather 
than a province within a country as China has claimed. 
</P>
<P>
	About one third of Taiwanese listed companies have investments  
in China, and their business could be hurt by tensions between the 
two sides, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell  
93.09 points, or 0.51 percent, to end at 18,181.09. On Monday, the 
average closed up 336.45 points, or 1.88 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese share prices fell as companies sold shares which they  
had held in other companies to cement business relations, a 
practice known as cross-shareholding. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors also took profits following the day-earlier surge,  
traders said. The biggest declines were in high technology sectors, 
they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, buying in internationally competitive blue chips  
continues to underpin the market amid hopes Japan's economy will 
recover, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 122.14 yen in  
late-afternoon trading, unchanged from late Monday in Tokyo and 
below its late New York level of 122.23 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Thai stock prices closed sharply lower in line with other  
declines in regional bourses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stock Exchange of Thailand index fell 11.62 points, or 2.2  
percent, to 500.25. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong shares fell on profit-taking.  
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, fell 80.91 points, or 0.6 percent, to close at 
13,980.93. On Monday, the index slumped 160.73 points, or 1.1 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said investors continued to take profits ahead of the  
impending slew of quarterly corporate profit reports in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	Bucking the trend was the Australian stock market, where prices  
rose following a positive outlook for interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sydney's All Ordinaries Index rose 13.7 points, or 0.4  
percent, to 3,063.9. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower. The benchmark  
NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 3.17 points, or 1.1 percent, to 
2,174.07. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed sharply lower for the second  
consecutive day on concerns that local interest rate will rise. The 
Korea Composite Stock Price Index fell 16.75 points, or 1.6 
percent, to 987.50. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed slightly lower. The Philippine  
Stock Index fell 1.72 points, or 0.06 percent, to 2,604.49. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed lower in listless trading. The  
Straits Times Index fell 20.29 points, or 0.92 percent, to 
2,178.49. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares closed mostly lower. The main  
Composite Index fell 9.48 points, or 1.1 percent, to 842.01. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed lower as political concerns  
weighed on investors. The Composite Index fell 6.937 points, or 1.1 
percent, to 656.187. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
