<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Children's Bodies Found in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- British forensic experts in Kosovo  
have uncovered the bodies of 11 children, some as young as 2 years 
old, shot at close range by Serb forces, Britain's foreign 
secretary said Tuesday. The revelation came as a top U.N. war 
crimes prosecutor said it was possible that Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic could be charged with genocide for the Serbs' 
campaign of atrocities in Kosovo, on top of other war crimes 
charges he already faces. 

</P>
<P>
	Rail Killings Suspect In Custody  
</P>
<P>
	EL PASO, Texas (AP) -- Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, the Mexican  
drifter suspected of killing eight people as he made his way around 
the U.S. on freight trains, turned himself in Tuesday. 
Resendez-Ramirez ended a six-week manhunt by walking with a brother 
across a bridge between Mexico and El Paso, Texas, where a Texas 
Ranger arrested him. The deal was set up by the fugitive's sister. 
Authorities say the surrender agreement includes assurances of 
family visits, a psychological evaluation and promises that 
Resendez-Ramirez will be safe in jail. 

</P>
<P>
	Company Charged in ValuJet Crash  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The airline maintenance company SabreTech has been  
hit with state murder and manslaughter charges and federal 
conspiracy charges in the 1996 ValuJet crash that killed 110 people 
in Florida's Everglades. The company and three of its employees 
were later indicted by a federal grand jury on charges of 
conspiracy, making false statements, and, in the case of the 
company, failing to train the personnel who handled the hazardous 
material. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Defeats HMO Amendments  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Republican-led Senate Tuesday defeated a  
Democratic effort to make insurance companies pay for any 
treatments that doctors say are medically necessary. Republicans 
also rejected a Democratic amendment that would have given women 
more flexibility in their health care and longer hospital stays 
after mastectomies. Republicans won both votes, 52-to-48, in the 
opening votes on the issue of patients' rights. Democrats want to 
cover more people with farther-reaching rules. Republicans prefer a 
more modest approach. 

</P>
<P>
	House GOP Pushes Adoption Option  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans are moving to require federally  
funded abortion clinics to talk about adoption when counseling 
pregnant women. ``We have a duty to inform young women about the 
adoption option. If we don't, fewer women will choose adoption,'' 
said a statement by Commerce Committee Chairman Tom Bliley, R-Va., 
who planned to introduce the legislation in the House tomorrow. A 
spokeswoman for Planned Parenthood, which receives much of this 
funding, said counselors already talk about adoption. 

</P>
<P>
	Albright To Travel to Middle East  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright plans to  
travel to the Middle East next month with a goal of brokering a 
settlement within a year. Albright is expected to stop in Damascus 
for talks with Syrian President Hafez Assad; meet in Jerusalem with 
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Foreign Minister David Levy; 
and meet with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in the 
Palestinian-controlled territory. 

</P>
<P>
	US Military Conducts Huge Y2K Test  
</P>
<P>
	FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) -- The Pentagon is conducting what is believed  
to be the largest-ever simultaneous test of computer systems to 
make sure Year 2000 problems won't prevent delivery of everything 
from bullets to toilet paper to American troops. Technical experts 
built a duplicate network -- what they called a ``parallel 
processing environment'' -- then rolled those computer clocks 
forward to simulate the week following Feb. 28, 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Stocks Rise in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose moderately in early trading  
Wednesday amid expectations for Japan's economic recovery. The 
Nikkei gained 63.81 points to 18,244.90. In New York, the Dow fell 
25.96 points to 11,175.02. 

</P>
<P>
	AL Beats NL 4-1  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Moments after Ted Williams threw out the first  
ball, Pedro Martinez pitched himself into the All-Star game record 
book Tuesday night. Martinez struck out five in two innings, 
leading the American League over the Nationals 4-1 for its third 
straight win. Martinez became the first pitcher to strike out the 
first three hitters in an All-Star game, fanning Barry Larkin, 
Larry Walker and Sammy Sosa. The Boston ace, already halfway to the 
magic 30-win mark at the break, kept up the streak by striking out 
Mark McGwire to begin the second inning. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
