<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.H. Teen Dies on Alaskan Glacier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- A teen-ager taking a mountaineering  
course apparently fell to his death down a deep hole in a glacier 
after he went to get water from a stream. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Nazzaro, 17, of Durham, N.H., disappeared Sunday evening  
on Matanuska Glacier. Searchers found no sign of him Monday, even 
after lowering a 250-foot fiber-optic cable with a video camera 
attached into the 7-foot-wide hole. The search was called off. 
</P>
<P>
	``They did not see anything but more ice and water. The hole is  
extremely deep,'' State Trooper Sgt. Rae Arno said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nazzaro was taking part in a month-long mountaineering class  
offered by the National Outdoor Leadership School. The 11 students 
had spent 26 days at the glacier 80 miles from Anchorage, climbing 
several peaks in the surrounding Chugach Mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	The students were traveling without their three instructors at  
the time. The instructors were several miles behind and felt 
confident in the students' abilities, said Don Ford, Alaska branch 
director for NOLS. 
</P>
<P>
	NOLS has been teaching mountaineering classes in Alaska since  
the early 1970s and has had one other death -- a student who fell 
during an expedition on Mount McKinley in 1971, Ford said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
