<DOCNO> APW19990713.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 09:00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston Globe Publisher Replaced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The New York Times Co. replaced Boston Globe  
publisher Benjamin B. Taylor, whose family had overseen the paper 
for 126 years, because of a ``difference in approach to 
management,'' a Globe spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor's successor, effective immediately, is Richard H. Gilman,  
a New York Times senior vice president. Taylor remains chairman of 
the Globe Newspaper Company Board. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur Sulzberger Jr., chairman of The New York Times Co., which  
owns the Globe, said Gilman would bring ``vision and leadership'' 
to the Globe, adding, ``Under Rich, The Globe will remain the voice 
of New England.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Times bought the Globe in 1993 in a $1.1 billion deal that  
guaranteed the Globe independence in news and management for at 
least five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Globe spokesman Richard Gulla said Taylor's ouster did not  
signal the end of that independence. He declined to elaborate 
beyond his comment about management differences. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Globe will remain editorially autonomous,'' Gulla said  
Monday. ``It is not in any way going to become an arm of The New 
York Times or anything like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The move came as a shock to Globe staffers and even to Gilman,  
who told the newsroom in a noon meeting Monday that ``this catches 
a lot of people, including myself, a little bit by surprise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though such a move had been rumored in the industry since the  
Times bought the Globe, officials from both papers said no other 
major changes -- including layoffs -- were planned. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no other shoe to drop,'' Gilman said.  
</P>
<P>
	Editor Matthew Storin was quoted by The Washington Post in  
Tuesday's editions as saying Gilman and Sulzberger had ``made it 
clear they not only wanted me to stay but hoped I would stay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``While it's a jarring change, and you can't expect them to have  
the emotional connection the Taylor family has, I have faith that 
they have our best interests at heart,'' Storin told the Post. 
</P>
<P>
	John Morton, media consultant and columnist for the American  
Journalism Review, said the Times likely wanted a Globe publisher 
with more experience on the business and management side. 
</P>
<P>
	``The paper is now controlled by the Sulzberger family, and it's  
inevitable that The Boston Globe ... is eventually going to be run 
by people who are in The New York Times' culture,'' Morton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they've been very respectful of the Taylor family,''  
he added. ``But clearly it is now a Sulzberger newspaper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sulzberger praised Taylor, whose family has led the publication  
for four generations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ben Taylor has made many important contributions to the Globe  
during the past 27 years. His commitment to the newspaper, service 
to the community and dedication to quality journalism are 
unquestioned,'' Sulzberger said. 
</P>
<P>
	At a meeting of department heads, William O. Taylor -- Benjamin  
Taylor's cousin, who retired in 1997 after 20 years as publisher -- 
said the appointment of Gilman was the end of an era for his 
family. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very sad day for both Ben and myself as our family  
winds up a long career managing this newspaper,'' he said. ``I hope 
the history books will be kind to both of us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gilman, 48, has been senior vice president of operations for the  
Times since 1993. He has, at various times, overseen production, 
systems and technology, the development of plant facilities and 
circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	He started his career as a reporter at The Arizona Daily Star in  
Tucson. During his tenure there, the paper won its first Pulitzer 
Prize in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Times, Gilman is credited with overseeing the newspaper's  
largest circulation growth since 1992. He also introduced color 
printing to the newspaper's weekday editions. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor, 52, has been with the Globe since 1972 and was named  
publisher in 1997. Before becoming publisher, he was a general 
assignment and political reporter, assistant business editor, 
assistant managing editor for local news and executive editor. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, he was named chairman and chief executive officer of  
the Globe Newspaper Company. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a bit of a sad day, I have to admit,'' Taylor said. ``But  
I'm focused on looking forward.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
