<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Assault Weapons Attacked in California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- California lawmakers have passed a  
measure that supporters say blocks gunmakers from evading a 
10-year-old ban on assault weapons by simply changing the names of 
the high-powered firearms. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure approved Monday by the state's Assembly and Senate  
ends 2 1/2 years of legislative wrangling over so-called copycat 
weapons that sprung up following passage of California's assault 
weapons ban in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Gray Davis is expected to sign the current bill as well as  
another already on his desk that would limit gun purchases to one a 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	``This bill closes the loophole that bans guns by name, not by  
capacity,'' said Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa, a Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	Under current law, California generally prohibits the sale,  
manufacture, distribution, import and, in many instances, 
possession of more than 50 military-style weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	But it has not prohibited gunmakers from selling guns with  
slight modifications under different names. While the TEC-9 is 
banned, for example, the TEC-DC9, one of the weapons used in the 
Littleton, Colo., massacre, has been legal in California. 
</P>
<P>
	The approved bill spells out physical characteristics of the  
weapons already outlawed -- such as fixed magazines that carry more 
than 10 rounds of ammunition, vertical handgrips and other features 
that allow rapid firing. 
</P>
<P>
	The Legislature last year passed a similar bill, but it was  
vetoed by then-Gov. Pete Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
	California's initial weapons ban was enacted after a man armed  
with an AK-47 assault rifle killed five children and wounded 
several others at a Stockton elementary school. 
</P>
<P>
	While supporters say Monday's action tightens the law,  
opponents, most of them Republicans, said the measure wouldn't 
reduce gun violence or stop criminals from getting weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	``It accomplishes nothing,'' said Republican Assemblyman George  
House. ``If you want to stop these killings, put more morality back 
in the public school curriculum, put more morality back into 
teachings in the home.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
