<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ESPN Will Replay World Cup Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The U.S. women's victory in the World Cup final  
was worth a second look, ESPN decided, especially for non-baseball 
fans in prime time. 
</P>
<P>
	The cable network replaced its taped Rock N' Roll gymnastics  
show from 1998 with a replay of the Americans' shootout victory 
over China after a 0-0 tie Sunday afternoon. It aired Tuesday night 
opposite the All-Star game. 
</P>
<P>
	The replay wasn't expected to attract 40 million viewers as it  
did the first time around on ABC, but should have drawn many 
viewers still caught up in the aftermath of the World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	There was speculation that ESPN went head-to-head with the  
All-Star game because of its court dispute with Major League 
Baseball. But the cable network described its decision as nothing 
more than counter-programming. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to show it on ESPN on prime time while it was still  
fresh and this was our first opportunity to do so,'' ESPN spokesman 
Josh Krulewitz said. ``Any other theory may sound like a great 
story, but it's simply fiction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN aired the Home Run Derby Monday night, will show the WNBA  
All-Star game on Wednesday night and has committed to showing taped 
coverage of the British Open on Thursday and Friday in prime time. 
</P>
<P>
	MLB terminated its contract with ESPN in June over the switch of  
three September games to a secondary outlet, and after ESPN sued, 
baseball countersued. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN's decision to broadcast the World Cup match didn't seem to  
bother Fox, which televised the All-Star game and has been a major 
rival. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's their decision,'' Fox spokesman Vince Wladika said. ``God  
bless them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball also didn't seem fazed.  
</P>
<P>
	``They're in charge of their own programming,'' baseball  
spokesman Rich Levin said. ``It wasn't live action last I saw.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The All-Star game posted a 13.3 national rating last year, up 13  
percent from 1997. The World Cup final had a surprising 11.4 
preliminary national mark. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans' victory was the most-watched soccer game on U.S.  
network television. The match will also air on ESPN Classic on 
Sunday at 5 p.m. EDT. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
