<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Called 'Stuffed Shirt' in N.Y. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Calling Vice President Al Gore a ``stuffed  
shirt,'' a powerful county Democratic leader in New York says Bill 
Bradley is ``more electable'' in the presidential race. 
</P>
<P>
	While stopping short of an outright endorsement of the former  
New Jersey senator's bid for the Democratic nomination, David 
Alpert of Westchester County said Monday that while he could ``live 
with either ... I think Bradley is the more exciting candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're putting together a whole package, I think he's  
more electable,'' Alpert said. ``I think Gore is a great guy, but I 
think he's -- I'm probably using the wrong word -- a stuffed shirt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alpert said he hoped to make an endorsement in the presidential  
race before the end of the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Westchester is the state's eighth largest of 62 counties in  
terms of Democratic enrollment, with 210,000 party members. It is 
located just north of New York City and is considered one of the 
linchpins to success in the politically crucial suburbs surrounding 
the city in statewide campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Gore, Chris Lehane, said: ``We're very pleased  
with the depth and breadth of our support throughout New York and 
we'll continue working to make that support even broader and 
deeper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, much of the state's top Democratic Party leadership,  
including more than a half dozen of the state's most powerful 
county chairmen have already lined up behind Gore in New York. Also 
supporting the vice president's candidacy are state Comptroller H. 
Carl McCall, state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer and state 
Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Saturday, top Gore advisers in New York said they  
expected Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan to back Bradley. Moynihan has 
had no comment on that. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore advisers said this weekend they were also concerned they  
might lose Dominic Baranello, a former state party chairman, to the 
Bradley camp. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
