<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Continue Falll / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices resumed their  
slide early today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for 
beneficial growing weather. 
</P>
<P>
	After a one-day breather that saw prices rise amid concern about  
dry weather, prices continued lower today on the National Weather 
Service's forecast for above-normal rainfall over the next 10 days. 
That will be accompanied by normal temperatures, the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Such conditions are near-ideal growing weather for  
spring-planted crops and help reinforce ideas that production this 
year will be large. The government currently is forecasting a third 
record year of soybean production and the third-largest corn crop 
on record. 
</P>
<P>
	The winter wheat harvest also is set to wrap up shortly, and is  
much larger than originally expected. 
</P>
<P>
	While overseas demand has picked up, ample world inventories are  
likely to translate to much lower asking prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 1 cent to $2.59 1/4 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1 cent to $1.95 3/4 a bushel; December oats fell 1 
cent to $1.08 a bushel; November soybeans fell 3 cents to $4.15 3/4 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures were mostly lower on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while pork futures fell sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell .15 cent to 63.65 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .05 cent to 77.42 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs fell 1.57 cents to 44.40 cents a pound; August pork bellies 
fell .75 cnet to 32.12 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
