<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Graves Found Under S.C. Arena </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Volunteers were expected to work through  
the week retrieving the remains of Confederate sailors from 
underneath The Citadel's football stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Archaeologists in recent weeks have found 16 bodies under  
Johnson Hagood Stadium, built atop an old sailors' cemetery. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, three graves and indications of five more were found  
beneath a room where school football boosters usually enjoy lunch 
and refreshments. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers hope two of the graves contain the remains of  
crewmen who died when the Confederate submarine H.L. Hunley sank at 
its moorings during a test run in 1863. The following year, the 
vessel was refloated with another crew and became the first 
submarine to sink an enemy warship, the Union blockade ship 
Housatonic. 
</P>
<P>
	Five sailors drowned when the Hunley sank and four are thought  
to have been buried at the cemetery. Their graves are distinguished 
from the others because they were buried in oversized coffins after 
their bodies were dismembered to remove them from the submarine. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhumed remains of all the sailors will be reburied in the  
city's Magnolia Cemetery this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The three graves confirmed Monday contained intact bodies, but  
none appear to be those of the Hunley crew, said Randy Burbage, 
chairman of the Confederate Heritage Trust and a member of the 
state Hunley Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The five other apparent graves have ``the proper features, but  
you don't know exactly what they are, of course, until you get to 
the bottom,'' said Jon Leader, deputy state archaeologist. 
</P>
<P>
	Confederate sailors were buried at the site when it was the  
city's cemetery for seamen. The site was covered over in 1948 when 
a 21,000-seat stadium was built at the state military college. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
