<DOCNO> APW19990713.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 09:10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Russia Sign Steel Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Russia has agreed to limit shipments of steel  
to the United States over a five-year period to avoid imposition of 
punitive American tariffs, Commerce Secretary William Daley 
announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	``These agreements deliver on the administration's commitment to  
guarantee that surging imports do not threaten the livelihoods of 
communities and workers around the nation,'' Daley told reporters 
in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides signed the agreements covering different types of  
steel following marathon bargaining talks in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	Daley said that final obstacles were overcome with the help of  
phone calls from Vice President Al Gore to Russian Prime Minister 
Sergei Stepashin Monday afternoon and again late Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, who is hoping to succeed President Clinton in the White  
House, had provided ``forceful advocacy on behalf of the U.S. steel 
industry and workers (that) was critical to the successful 
completion of these agreements,'' Daley said. 
</P>
<P>
	The deals will set annual quotas for Russian steel shipments,  
reducing imports for all Russian steel shipments by 64 percent this 
year compared to 1998, the Commerce Department said in a fact 
sheet. 
</P>
<P>
	The quotas will gradually rise over the four years, climbing to  
a high of 725,000 metric tons for hot rolled steel in 2003, the 
department said. That would still represent an 80 percent reduction 
from the 1998 level of imports of Russian hot rolled steel, U.S. 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's Tass news agency quoted Russian Trade Minister Mikhail  
Fradkov as saying the deal would preserve Russia's access to the 
U.S. market. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement represents ``a sufficiently difficult compromise  
for both sides, but for Russia it preserves an opportunity to 
supply steel to the American market,'' Fradkov was quoted as 
saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Fradkov told the Russian news agency that the deal was achieved  
only at the last minute following a number of concessions from the 
American side. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. steel industry and its supporters in Congress had been  
unhappy with the outline of the preliminary agreement the 
administration struck with Russia on steel back in February. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., had complained that  
the initial deal, which has now been modified with further 
negotiations, ``allows too much (Russian) steel to be imported at 
too low of a price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With political pressures rising, the administration has tried to  
show support for the U.S. steel industry. The industry has been 
hurt by a flood of cheap imports into the country following the 
global currency crisis, which sharply lowered demand for steel and 
other commodities because of the steep recessions in many Asian 
nations and Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	The steel industry has filed a number of dumping cases seeking  
to get the government to impose high tariffs to stem this tide of 
cheap foreign steel into the country. 
</P>
<P>
	High tariffs have been imposed in a case involving hot-rolled  
steel with Japan. But Russia entered into negotiations to avoid 
having the tariffs, which the industry favors because they are more 
effective at halting imports. 
</P>
<P>
	A number of Clinton administration officials argued that an  
agreement should be reached by which Russia could still ship steel 
to the United States as a way of helping that country out of its 
economic troubles. Steel is one of Russia's major industries, 
accounting for 7 percent of total economic output. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 16:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Service of 2000 Candidates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Military service of the presidential candidates:  
</P>
<P>
 *Republicans 
</P>
<P>
	Lamar Alexander -- No service. Received deferments for school and  
his work for a federal judge. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Bauer -- No service. Received educational deferments for  
undergraduate and law school studies. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Buchanan -- No service because of rheumatoid arthritis in his  
knees. 
</P>
<P>
	George W. Bush -- Six years in the Texas and Alabama Air National  
Guard. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole -- No service.  
</P>
<P>
	Steve Forbes -- Six years in the New Jersey National Guard,  
primarily as a clerk but also as a cook for six months at Fort Dix, 
N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	Orrin Hatch -- No service.  
</P>
<P>
	John Kasich -- No service. High draft number.  
</P>
<P>
	Alan Keyes -- No service. Received an educational deferment, then  
had a high draft number. 
