<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Company Buys Corporate Express </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOMFIELD, Colo. (AP) -- The acquisition of the Colorado-based  
Corporate Express by the Dutch company Buhrmann NV will create the 
world's biggest distributor of office supplies to companies and 
could pave the way for future takeovers, executives said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will be the No. 1 business-to-business provider in North  
America, Europe and Australia,'' Robert King, president and CEO of 
the Corporate Express, told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The $2.3 billion acquisition, which is expected to close in the  
fourth quarter, was announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The new combined company will have sales of over $9 billion with  
operations in 28 countries and 30,000 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to taking over Corporate Express' $1.2 billion debt,  
Buhrmann will pay $9.70 in cash for every share of Corporate 
Express, for a total of $1.1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined entity will generate cost savings of $100 million  
per year, executives from both companies said at a press conference 
held at Corporate Express' headquarters in Broomfield, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	Together, the companies have a customer base of about 170,000  
customers, including more than 90 percent of Fortune 500 companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger comes just five months after Corporate Express'  
founder stepped aside as chairman and the company announced plans 
to conduct a comprehensive review of its business operations. 
</P>
<P>
	At that time, shares of the company had fallen 30 percent in the  
past year as weakness in its delivery business dragged down 
earnings growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were also critical that Corporate Express lost  
direction and its focus on operating profitably when it started 
buying up smaller companies, acquiring its $1.2 billion in debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Buhrmann said the acquisition, which will see a merger of  
Buhrmann's North America operations based in Chicago with Corporate 
Express, would have little impact on jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Corporate Express stock rose 47 cents on Tuesday to $9.03 on the  
Nasdaq Stock Market. Buhrmann shares jumped 18 percent on the 
Amsterdam Stock Exchange. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
