<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Co. Buys Corporate Express </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Dutch business services and  
distribution group Buhrmann NV today announced the acquisition of 
U.S.-based Corporate Express for $2.3 billion, creating what it 
called the world's largest distributor of office supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dutch company will pay $9.70 in cash for every share of  
Corporate Express, a provider of office and computer supplies based 
in Broomfield, Colo. The new combination will have sales of more 
than $9 billion, with operations in 28 countries and 30,000 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
	``The acquisition of Corporate Express strongly advances  
Buhrmann's strategy to become the world's premier office products 
distributor in the business-to-business market, and we expect that 
it will create significant value for our shareholders,'' said Frans 
Koffrie, chief executive officer of Buhrmann. 
</P>
<P>
	The office products activities will now be Buhrmann's largest  
business. It also has paper selling activities and graphic systems 
operations in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Together, the companies have a customer base of about 170,000  
customers, including more than 90 percent of Fortune 500 companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Corporate Express founder Jirka Rysavy announced in February he  
was stepping down as chairman of the office supply company, whose 
investors had accused it of losing direction after it started 
buying up smaller companies and acquiring debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Buhrmann said today it would pay $1.1 billion for the Corporate  
Express shares, and take on $1.2 billion in debts, which it plans 
to refinance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
