<HEADLINE> Roche Sales Up 7 Pct. in First Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) -- Swiss pharmaceutical giant Roche's  
sales rose 7 percent in the first half, helped by demand for its 
new weight loss drug Xenical. 
</P>
<P>
	Roche said it also expects good results for the full year. Sales  
in the first half of 1999 were $8.5 billion, up from $7.9 billion 
in the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	First-half profit, which will be announced at a later date,  
should be up from a year ago, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Drug sales overall rose 12 percent in the first half of 1999,  
which help make up for the 7 percent drop in sales of vitamins and 
fine chemicals. 
</P>
<P>
	Xenical, Roche's weight-control drug, was a major contributor to  
increased pharmaceutical sales, the company said. It did not 
disclose specific sales figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Roche's high expectations exclude special charges related to its  
involvement in a vitamins price-fixing scheme, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, the U.S. Justice Department said Roche and BASF AG of  
Germany agreed to plead guilty and pay a record $725 million 
criminal fine for engaging in a worldwide conspiracy to raise and 
fix the prices of vitamins. Roche's share was $500 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The forecast also excludes the results of Roche's agreement to  
buy outstanding shares of U.S. biotech firm Genentech Inc. and then 
make a public offering to sell around 17 percent of the shares, 
Roche said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
