<HEADLINE> More Hate Crime Legislation Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Civil rights leaders urged Americans to voice  
their concern about hate crimes to encourage Congress to expand 
federal civil rights protections. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is certainly an increase in the number of hate groups in  
the country, and there is a wide increase in the incidence of hate 
groups violence,'' Wade Henderson, director of the Leadership 
Council on Civil Rights, said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 120 civil rights leaders joined at the White House in  
a Clinton administration-backed effort to build momentum for 
tougher protections. 
</P>
<P>
	The expansion of the Hate Crimes Prevention Act would allow the  
federal government to prosecute hate crimes sparked by sexual 
orientation, gender and disability, as well as give the Justice 
Department ``greater ability to prosecute hate crime in general,'' 
said Bill Lann Lee, acting assistant attorney general for civil 
rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Hate crimes are motivated by prejudice based on race, religion,  
color or national origin. 
</P>
<P>
	Under current law, the federal government may step in only if  
the crime in question occurred on federal property or during a 
federally protected activity, such as while a victim was voting or 
going to school. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are anxious to see it move. ... We're calling on all  
Americans to voice their concern'' about recent hate murders, 
Henderson added. 
</P>
<P>
	Fewer than half the states have hate crime laws that cover  
gender, sexual orientation and disability, according to Michael 
Lieberman of the Anti-Defamation League, who said the expanded law 
would work as a federal ``backstop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But few of the hate crimes tabulated by the FBI are motivated by  
sexual orientation, gender or disability, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1991, the FBI has tabulated almost 50,000 hate crimes, but  
of the indictments that resulted, only about 37 would fall under 
the proposed broader definition of hate crimes, Lieberman said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
