<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Group Raps Liability Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A consumer group opposed to liability law reform  
said Tuesday that legislation has failed to lower the price of 
insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	``States with little or no tort law restrictions have  
experienced the same level of insurance rates as those states that 
enacted severe restrictions on victims' rights,'' said the report 
released by Citizens for Corporate Accountability and Individual 
Rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The group has battled efforts in Congress and state legislatures  
to limit lawsuits that sometimes yield jury awards in the millions 
of dollars for accidents tied to defective products. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for a property and casualty insurers group disputed  
the report's conclusions, however. 
</P>
<P>
	``The removal of tort reform would clearly raise costs,'' said  
Steven Goldstein of the Insurance Information Institute in New 
York. ``We are constantly litigated against.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report's release comes on the heels of the largest  
product-liability award ever issued. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, a Los Angeles jury awarded a record $4.9 billion to  
six motorists who were severely burned when their Chevrolet 
exploded in a rear-end collision. General Motors Corp. plans to 
appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Authors J. Robert Hunter and Joanne Doroshow said that based on  
industry data, insurance costs that drive prices are not affected 
by legislation enacted by state lawmakers. The study looked at 
figures since the mid-1980s when liability insurance premiums 
skyrocketed and insurance was difficult to purchase. 
</P>
<P>
	The consumer group says 41 states have enacted legislation  
limiting liability to varying degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	The insurance industry seeks legislation that would reduce jury  
awards for claims of pain and suffering and to speed up litigation, 
Goldstein said. The industry's demands for smaller awards do not 
apply to medical costs, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact is, if you can reduce the costs of litigiousness you  
can reduce costs,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Doroshow said industry officials are wrong, however, when they  
insist that all that's needed is to ``rein in these out-of-control 
juries and you'll see insurance premiums drop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not true. It's a big lie. It's a hoax,'' she said. ``It's  
being played out in state legislatures across the country. 
Lawmakers have been duped. The public has been duped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Insurance rates already are ``near historic lows,'' according to  
Dan Zielinski, spokesman for the American Insurance Association in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Robin Albanese, an analyst with industry rating company A.M.  
Best, attributed this to competition in home and auto insurance and 
a soft market for other insurance policies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
