<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Engine Cracks Blamed in F-16 Crashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A special Air Force inspection program for a  
key component of F-16 jet engines failed to find cracks that led to 
two crashes this year, newly released reports found. 
</P>
<P>
	The crashes in February and March were traced to the jets'  
afterburner, which gives the planes a boost of power during takeoff 
or maneuvers. In both cases, the afterburner assembly fell apart in 
flight. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force was already keeping a close eye on the  
afterburners, which date to the 1980s, because of cracks that 
developed around spot welds in the metal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force has recorded 13 incidents of serious afterburner  
cracks since 1984, but until this year the problem caused no 
crashes of the $20 million jet fighter. 
</P>
<P>
	In the March 26 crash, the afterburner had very recently passed  
a special inspection, but the device failed after the plane flew 
just 18 1/2 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``The inspection procedures were ineffective,'' an Air Force  
report on the crash concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	The crash report, released last week, said a lab analysis  
revealed 30 cracks in the afterburner wall. A similar report on the 
Feb. 3 crash noted 50 cracks. 
</P>
<P>
	Both crashes involved student pilots at Luke Air Force Base in  
Arizona. In both cases, fireballs engulfed the rear of the 
students' F-16s. The pilots ejected safely. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the crashes, the Air Force has asked Congress for $45  
million for an emergency replacement program. Starting next year, 
the aging afterburners on 767 Pratt &AMP; Whitney engines would be 
replaced with a newer version that does not use welds, said Air 
Force spokesman Gary Emery. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress has not yet acted on the request.  
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, the Air Force is using a fluorescent dye to  
highlight cracks that may not be visible otherwise, Emery said. The 
Air Force is also checking the afterburners more often -- after they 
have been fired 1,000 times instead of 2,000 times, Emery said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've halved the time between inspection, and increased the  
sensitivity of the inspection,'' Emery said. 
</P>
<P>
	Through mid-June, 712 engines had undergone the enhanced  
inspections, and the Air Force found 63 cases of cracked 
afterburners, Emery said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force has about 1,450 F-16s, which Emery praised as the  
safest single-engine jet the service has ever had. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 02:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Suspects Called Mild-Mannered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDDING, Calif. (AP) -- Before he moved away from his home in  
Northern California, Matt Williams painted a strange sign on a shed 
in his back yard: a triangle with a star, a human eye at the point 
and a cross. 
</P>
<P>
	Its meaning is a puzzle, one of many in the case of Williams,  
31, and his 29-year-old brother, Tyler, men described by 
acquaintances as bright, personable, devoted Christians -- and by 
investigators as suspects in the killing of a gay couple and, 
possibly, three synagogue fires. 
</P>
<P>
	The brothers were in jail Monday on charges of receiving stolen  
merchandise, which police say are connected to the slayings. They 
pleaded innocent and have not been charged in the deaths or with 
the Sacramento fires being investigated by federal authorities as a 
hate crime. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of it makes sense to me,'' said Charles Bond, a landlord  
in the college town of Moscow, Idaho, who knew Matt Williams while 
he attended school there. ``I always thought Matt was real 
levelheaded and a real nice kid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Anderson, a teacher who bought the Williamses' Gridley  
home three years ago, has wondered anew about that symbol on the 
shed, which he says shows through even though he's painted over it 
a few times. He said Matt Williams painted it the day the family 
left for Redding. 
</P>
<P>
	That was a few years ago. The Williams brothers had never been  
arrested before this summer, when investigators say their quiet 
lives exploded into violence. 
</P>
<P>
	On July 1, Gary Matson and Winfield Mowder were found shot to  
death in their bed in Happy Valley, a community near Redding, an 
old Gold Rush town 215 miles northeast of San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Wednesday, after one of Matson's credit cards was used,  
police staked out a Yuba City business where the credit card 
purchase was to be delivered. The Williams brothers were arrested 
as they picked up equipment to assemble ammunition, Yuba City 
police said. 
</P>
<P>
	One was wearing a bulletproof vest, and both were armed with  
assault rifles, a shotgun and 9 mm pistols, police said. 
Authorities said the brothers were carrying Matson's wallet, his 
driver's license and his Social Security card. 
</P>
<P>
	The connection between victims and suspects? Apparently the  
gentle art of horticulture. 
</P>
<P>
	Mowder, 40, who had just earned a degree in anthropology from  
Chico State University, worked in the gardening department of a 
Redding hardware store. Matson, 50, was co-founder of a natural 
science museum and arboretum, and helped establish a farmers market 
where Matt Williams ran a booth, said Ed Smith, who owns a nursery 
where Williams worked for six months. 
</P>
<P>
	Matson and Williams were ``friends as far as I could tell,''  
Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators seeking a motive for the crime went to an  
apartment rented by Matt Williams and allegedly found a trove of 
white supremacist writings and guns. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said they also found a notebook containing the names of  
32 Jewish and civic leaders associated with three Sacramento 
synagogues that were set ablaze last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Also among the pamphlets were handouts from the World Church of  
the Creator, an Illinois-based white supremacist group being 
scrutinized in the Sacramento synagogue fires, all set June 18. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the Fourth of July weekend, a former group member targeted  
minorities in a shooting rampage in Indiana and Illinois, killing 
two and wounding nine before committing suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Hale, the leader of the World Church of the Creator,  
rejected any involvement with the Williams brothers and said 
attempts to link his group to crimes in California are part of a 
federal ``smear campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matt and Tyler Williams grew up in the farm town of Gridley,  
where they were home-schooled for a time, and later moved 120 miles 
north to Redding with their parents, who have declined to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson said the father, Ben Williams, ``used to walk up and  
down the street carrying a staff and preaching to no one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Friends from Gridley remembered the two as mild-mannered, always  
ready to preach but not belligerent. 
</P>
<P>
	Erick Dahl remembers Tyler Williams as smart but reserved, a boy  
who earned the right to wear a gold cord at graduation because of 
his academic record. But he also was a student who ``didn't have a 
lot of really close friends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember he talked a lot about religion but never to the  
point of trying to impose it on you,'' said Dahl, who played chess 
with Tyler over lunch. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond said the same of Matt Williams: ``My impression is that he  
would have been very firm in his own political, religious 
convictions, but I could never see that leading to violence.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
