<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Group Raps Liability Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Insurance data is being used against the  
industry by a consumer group battling efforts to limit jury awards. 
</P>
<P>
	Citizens for Corporate Accountability and Individual Rights said  
Tuesday that legislation has failed to reduce the price of 
insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	``States with little or no tort law restrictions have  
experienced the same level of insurance rates as those states that 
enacted severe restrictions on victims' rights,'' the consumer 
group said in a report that relies on industry data. 
</P>
<P>
	The group has opposed efforts in Congress and state legislatures  
to limit lawsuits that sometimes yield jury awards in the millions 
of dollars for accidents tied to defective products. 
</P>
<P>
	But a spokesman for a property and casualty insurers group  
disputed the report's conclusions. 
</P>
<P>
	``What do they want?'' asked Steven Goldstein of the Insurance  
Information Institute in New York. ``Do they want to eliminate tort 
reform? The removal of tort reform would clearly raise costs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report's release follows the largest product-liability award  
ever handed down. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, a Los Angeles jury awarded a record $4.9 billion to  
six motorists who were severely burned when their Chevrolet 
exploded in a rear-end collision. General Motors Corp. plans to 
appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	J. Robert Hunter and Joanne Doroshow, authors of the report,  
said insurance costs that drive prices are not affected by 
legislation enacted by state lawmakers. The study examined data 
since the mid-1980s when liability insurance premiums skyrocketed 
and insurance was difficult to purchase. 
</P>
<P>
	The consumer group says 41 states have enacted legislation  
limiting liability to varying degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry seeks legislation that would reduce jury awards for  
claims of pain and suffering and to speed up litigation, Goldstein 
said. The industry's demands for smaller awards do not apply to 
medical costs, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact is, if you can reduce the costs of litigiousness you  
can reduce costs,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Doroshow said industry officials are wrong, however, when they  
insist that all that's needed is to ``rein in these out-of-control 
juries and you'll see insurance premiums drop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not true. It's a big lie. It's a hoax,'' she said. ``It's  
being played out in state legislatures across the country. 
Lawmakers have been duped. The public has been duped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Insurance rates already are ``near historic lows,'' according to  
Dan Zielinski, spokesman for the American Insurance Association in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Robin Albanese, an analyst with industry rating company A.M.  
Best, attributed this to competition in home and auto insurance and 
a soft market for other insurance policies. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
