<HEADLINE> Ga. Suspect Won't Be Hospitalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- A judge refused Tuesday to allow a  
15-year-old boy accused in a shooting spree at his high school to 
be removed from jail and treated for depression at a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	District Attorney Richard Read said T.J. Solomon is receiving  
adequate care in a juvenile detention lockup despite contentions 
from his lawyer that the boy is suicidal. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got an opportunity for treatment in a very secure  
environment,'' Read said after Juvenile Court Judge William 
Schneider issued the ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	Solomon is charged with shooting and wounding six classmates at  
Heritage High School in suburban Conyers on May 20, a month after 
the Littleton, Colo., school shooting left 15 people dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Ed Garland said he plans to present a more  
detailed petition asking that Solomon be hospitalized. 
</P>
<P>
	``The judge said he would entertain more information,'' said  
Garland, who said defense psychologists have diagnosed Solomon as 
having acute depression. 
  	   	
