<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall; Dow Down 37.04 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks dropped today as concerns about Latin  
America's economic recovery muted investor optimism about strong 
second-quarter profit reports. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 37.04 at 11,163.94 after having achieved three closing highs 
in the past four sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also dropped. The Nasdaq composite  
index fell 24.48 to 2,765.45 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index 
slipped 7.31 to 1,391.79. 
</P>
<P>
	J.P. Morgan fell 1 3/16 to 138 3/4 and Citigroup slipped 1 5/16 to  
47 7/16 as the financial services sector stumbled on worries about 
its exposure to weak capital markets in Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	But Merrill Lynch rose 1 3/16 to 79 1/16 on  
stronger-than-expected second-quarter profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Latin American markets fell sharply Monday on what  
analysts described as lingering worries about the state of the 
region's economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``The good news of the earnings season is being overshadowed by  
concerns about Latin America,'' said Marshall Acuff, equity 
strategist at Salomon Smith Barney. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices, which rose markedly on Monday as investors sought a  
safe haven from a new Latin America crisis, held steady today. That 
helped limit the extent of any selloff of stocks to the financial 
services sector, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks also were under pressure from concerns that the brisk  
U.S. economy will prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest 
rates again this fall, a move that could undermine corporate 
profits later this year and into 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market has been overbought quite a bit in the few weeks  
and we expected it to have some kind of reaction,'' said Eugene 
Mintz, financial markets analyst at Brown Brothers Harriman &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks were mostly down as investors prepared for  
Intel to release its second-quarter earnings after the market 
closed. Intel, the world's biggest computer chip maker, was down 1/8 
at 64 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Biotechnology giant Amgen soared 6 3/8 at 72 11/16 7/8 after the  
company's profit report late Monday beat Wall Street estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com rose 5 7/16 to 123 after announcing it is expanding  
it Web site to include toys and electronics. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 2-to-1 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 590.91 million 
shares, up from Monday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 2.94 at 652.85, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 4.75 at 810.79. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
