<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Damages vs. Auto Industry Alarming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The second huge verdict by a California jury against an  
automaker in four days seems to reflect a change in juror 
attitudes, some legal analysts said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	A Superior Court jury in Ceres, Calif. on Monday awarded $5  
million in compensation and $290 million in punitive damages to the 
family of a couple and their son who were killed when a 1978 Ford 
Bronco swerved to avoid a collision and overturned on a freeway in 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Friday, a Los Angeles jury said General Motors Co. must pay  
$4.9 billion to six people who were severely burned when their 1979 
Chevrolet Malibu's fuel tank exploded in a rear-end crash. 
</P>
<P>
	In both cases, lawyers for the plaintiffs offered evidence that  
the auto companies were aware of potential structural weaknesses in 
the vehicles and did not correct them, charges that both Ford Motor 
Co. and GM have denied. Both companies plan to appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say the size of the awards may be indicative of a  
trend. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have started to see much larger verdicts in product  
liability cases than ever before,'' said Los Angeles attorney Ed 
Woodsome, who has defended companies in product-defect suits for 25 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is increased publicity about these cases, increased  
awareness by the general public. ... Jurors tend to believe people 
like themselves rather than faceless corporations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The chief executive of a Los Angeles-based trial consulting  
firm, Decision Quest, said a shift in juror thinking has been 
visible since the 1995 O.J. Simpson murder trial, in which the firm 
was a consultant for the prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	``It allowed a lot of people to recognize that if they serve as  
jurors, they have the power to change the course of an issue,'' 
said Philip K. Anthony. ``More and more juries view themselves as 
having authority to legislate social change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for the families in the Ford case described the trend  
more favorably. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that the American public is waking up to the carnage  
that's being visited upon the public by some American industries 
such as tobacco and automobiles,'' said attorney Laurence Drivon. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's $4.9 billion verdict against General Motors in Los  
Angeles prompted widespread predictions by experts that the 
punitive damages would be cut dramatically or overturned, by either 
the trial judge or an appellate court. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the punitive damages against Ford were closer to the  
compensation awarded in the case, Woodsome and Anthony said they 
expect Superior Court Judge Roger Beauchesne to reduce the damages. 
Drivon disagreed, saying the punitives were less than 10 days' net 
profits for Ford. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford asked for a mistrial early Monday, saying news of the GM  
verdict must be influencing the jury, but the judge refused. 
</P>
<P>
	The case stemmed from an accident on Interstate 5 near Turlock,  
Calif., in June 1993. Juan Romo, 19, driving the Bronco, swerved to 
avoid a van he was passing and rolled over. His mother, Salustia, 
40; his father, Ramon, 39; and his brother, Ramiro, 18, were 
killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Romo and his two sisters, Evangelina, 14, and Maria, 8, suffered  
minor injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Their lawyers sought to show that Ford knew the Bronco's roof  
was unsafe but decided to save the small extra cost of reinforcing 
the roof with steel, a change made on post-1979 Broncos. 
Plaintiffs' witnesses included a former Ford executive vice 
president, Tom Feeney, who said company officials knew the roof was 
virtually certain to fail in a rollover. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford spokesman Jim Cain said Feeney ``never worked in truck  
product development'' and was not credible. Ford said the Bronco 
was sound and met federal safety standards, and blamed the deaths 
on Romo and the driver he was passing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 15:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Displays Family-Man Image </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES (AP) -- Showing off family snapshots in a pocket-sized  
album, Vice President Al Gore courted Iowa's farm vote, labor vote 
-- and Grandpa vote -- on Tuesday. He said he now considers public 
policy with his 9-day-old grandson in mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I talk about education policy and school safety, I'm  
thinking about it now in quite a different way than I did just 10 
days ago,'' the presidential hopeful said. 
</P>
<P>
	He picked up the prize endorsement of Iowa's first lady and the  
overnight hospitality of the officially neutral Gov. Tom Vilsack. 
</P>
<P>
	While the vice president made this trip bearing gifts for  
steelworkers -- he boasted of his work with Russian Prime Minister 
Sergei Stepashin to broker a ``breakthrough'' deal on cheap Russian 
steel imports -- and promises for Iowa farmers, it was the 
grandparents he courted most enthusiastically. 
</P>
<P>
	With a routine now predictable to his traveling entourage, Gore  
touted the arrival of his first grandchild, born to the eldest of 
his four children, Karenna, on July 4. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any grandparents here? I'm collecting advice,'' he called out  
in the Kirn Junior High gymnasium. He called the experience ``one 
of those milestones in life that actually has a profound impact on 
the way you think about the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And, he said, the best counsel so far was ``just give that  
grandchild whatever he wants, then if it causes any problems, give 
him back to his parents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whether by coincidence or design, his emphasis on his family  
life at stop after stop -- he called his photographer over to snap 
him before a ``Go Grandpa Gore'' poster at the Omaha airport -- 
seemed to underscore a distinction between himself and the personal 
scandals of President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore offered some of those he met here a flip through his new  
mini-album of photos taken by his wife, Tipper. All but one -- of 
Karenna and baby Wyatt -- showed Grandpa gingerly cradling the tiny 
infant. 
</P>
<P>
	To Robert Honig, 81, Gore presented a welcome image, especially  
when juxtaposed to Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a good, honest man who's handled himself real nice,''  
said the Council Bluffs grandfather of two. ``It hasn't been easy, 
either, with a partner like that always getting into trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later Tuesday, Gore was working to plump up his statewide  
organization in back-to-back dinners -- first with 17 black 
activists who he hopes will help get Iowans to next winter's 
caucuses, then with some five dozen local women. 
</P>
<P>
	While Gov. Vilsack has said he'll stay neutral in order to  
preserve a ``level playing field'' in the state's caucuses -- the 
traditional start of the nation's presidential nominating contests 
-- his wife, Christie, campaigned at Gore's side on this two-day 
swing through Council Bluffs and Des Moines. 
</P>
<P>
	On the same day that Mrs. Vilsack announced her support for  
Gore, which state campaign director Steve Hildebrand called a 
``huge boost'' to the organizational drive, the vice president 
pointed out to audiences along the way that he would, for the first 
time, be the house guest of the governor at his Victorian mansion, 
Terrace Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's only rival for the  
Democratic nomination, had also personally courted Mrs. Vilsack's 
endorsement. 
</P>
<P>
	Wooing Iowa's farmers, Gore railed against what he called  
``Republican-passed'' farm legislation signed three years ago by 
Clinton. The Freedom to Farm Act, which ended the link between farm 
prices and government subsidies to farmers, ``is not working as it 
was advertised,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he asked House Speaker Dennis Hastert and Senate  
Republican leader Trent Lott, during their Oval Office meeting 
Monday with Clinton, to work with him on provisions to increase 
subsidies to family farmers in crises of weather and economics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't say they jumped at the chance,'' Gore told a  
backyard gathering in Council Bluffs. ``I'd rather do it on a 
bipartisan basis, but if that's not possible then we'll back up and 
head straight at them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
