<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SUV Sales Growth Still High but... </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Demand for some sport utility vehicles is  
leveling off as the segment becomes more crowded, but SUV sales 
continue to increase faster than any other segment of the 
automotive market. 
</P>
<P>
	The slackening demand is mostly among models that have not been  
redesigned in several years. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's more competition, more entries, more good stuff from  
the Japanese and European producers,'' analyst David Healy of 
Burnham Securities Inc. said Tuesday. ``It's more of that than the 
whole segment slowing down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Industrywide, SUV sales were up 11 percent in the first half of  
the year, while the entire car and light truck market was up 7 
percent. While the torrid sales pace of the last few years is 
unlikely to be sustained, analysts don't forecast a drop in SUV 
sales anytime soon. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler AG surprised the industry late last week when it  
announced production of the redesigned Jeep Grand Cherokee would be 
scaled back starting next Monday, even though sales were up 12 
percent in the first six months of the year and 9 percent in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman Dan Moore said the automaker had been overly  
optimistic about demand for the '99 version. When the '99 went into 
production a year ago, the Detroit plant had been upgraded to make 
it more efficient and was able to produce at a higher rate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jeep plant is returning to the same production rate it had  
before the '99 model went into production to allow large 
inventories on dealer lots to be scaled back. Jeep also is offering 
a discounted lease deal to reduce dealer inventories. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very market-driven,'' Moore said. ``We've cut back all  
the overtime, but that may only last another month or so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newer models continue to sell robustly. Sales of  
DaimlerChrysler's Dodge Durango, for example, were up 37 percent in 
the first half and 27 percent in June. Ford's big Expedition was up 
13 percent in the first half, while the midsize Lexus RX300 was up 
a whopping 149 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan Motor Co., which just began selling the compact Xterra  
SUV to compete in the lower end of the market, also reports brisk 
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't keep 'em in the showrooms,'' spokesman Fred Standish  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Models that have not been redesigned in several years are not  
experiencing the same demand. 
</P>
<P>
	At General Motors Corp., sales of the big, profitable GMC  
Suburban were off 13 percent in the first half of the year, while 
sales of the slightly smaller Chevrolet Tahoe were down 26 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Suburban and its Chevrolet twin as well as the Tahoe and its  
GMC twin, the Yukon, are being redesigned for the 2000 model year. 
GM plans to begin producing the first of the new models in 
September. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of GM's Blazer midsize SUV were off 4 percent in the first  
six months of the year, while sales of its GMC twin, the Jimmy, 
were down 6 percent. Those models are not scheduled for a redesign 
before 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for Ford Motor Co.'s Explorer were up 4 percent in the  
first half but down 5 percent in June, in large part because of the 
comparison to record truck sales in June 1998. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
