<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Screening Process Suggested to IOC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Cities interested in staging future Olympic Games  
must meet certain qualifications before being allowed to submit a 
bid, a special panel proposed Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	A working group of IOC 2000, a reform commission set up in the  
wake of the Salt Lake City scandal, reached consensus on the need 
for a ``bid acceptance'' procedure. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would make sure that before a city could become a candidate  
they would have to meet certain technical standards,'' said Anita 
DeFrantz, an IOC vice president who heads the working group. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will save money for the cities that really are not properly  
prepared to bid and will ensure that cities that are accepted are 
cities that have the qualifications to be selected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DeFrantz spoke in a telephone interview with The Associated  
Press after a daylong meeting of the 18-member panel in Lausanne, 
Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Olympic Committee is studying ways of  
reforming the bidding and selection process to avoid the type of 
vote-buying abuses which marked Salt Lake City's choice as host of 
the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Other details, including the timetable for the bid screening  
procedure, still have to be worked out. The panel will meet again 
Sept. 2 and make its final recommendations on Sept. 25. 
</P>
<P>
	The new bid procedure will apply immediately to the race for the  
2008 Summer Games. Ten cities have expressed their intention to 
bid, including Beijing, Paris and Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	DeFrantz said it was ``premature'' to discuss who would judge a  
city's readiness to bid or what the specific technical requirements 
would be. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC has previously used a ``pre-selection'' procedure to  
reduce a field of candidates to a short list of finalists, but this 
took place far into the bid process. The new proposal would 
eliminate some cities right from the start. 
</P>
<P>
	DeFrantz said the panel was also considering the possibility of  
having an additional ``filtering out'' process to winnow the field 
later in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	A possible cap on the number of bid cities was discussed, as was  
the question of rotating the games among continents. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC has already mandated that the bid process for 2008  
cannot start before Feb. 1, 2000. The host city is scheduled to be 
selected at the IOC session in Moscow in Sept. 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	DeFrantz said the panel also addressed the issue of member  
visits to bid cities. Following the Salt Lake scandal, IOC members 
were banned from visiting the candidate cities for the 2006 Winter 
Games. Many members have pushed for the visits to be reinstated 
under tighter controls. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know there are some plusses and minuses to the visits,''  
DeFrantz said. ``We're reviewing it. It's not conclusive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DeFrantz suggested other changes from the 2006 process were  
likely. A small panel chose two 2006 finalists from the six-city 
European field, with the full general assembly selecting the winner 
immediately afterwards. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian city of Turin defeated the Swiss town of Sion in  
last month's vote in Seoul, South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	``We talked about 2006 and the things that worked well,''  
DeFrantz said. ``But the Summer Games and Winter Games are not the 
same. So while that worked well for 2006, for 2008 we need to keep 
in mind there's likely to be bid cities from more than one 
continent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 80-member IOC 2000 also has working groups studying ways of  
reforming the IOC structure and examining the overall role of the 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC has scheduled a special session for December to adopt  
the reforms. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 23:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flu Vaccine Spray May Be on the Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A nasal spray has proved effective in protecting  
healthy adults against the flu virus and researchers say the 
painless vaccine could reach the market within two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are significant hurdles, but our goal is to have it  
available for the flu season of 2000-2001,'' said Dr. J. Leighton 
Read, chairman of Aviron Inc. of Mountain View, Calif., which 
developed the vaccine and helped pay for the research published in 
today's Journal of the American Medical Association. 
</P>
<P>
	The spray, called FluMist, would offer an alternative to the  
standard flu shot millions of Americans get in the arm each year. 
The vaccine needs Food and Drug Administration approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The research looked at the vaccine's effectiveness in healthy,  
working adults, who are not normally urged to get flu shots. 
</P>
<P>
	In the study, 4,561 adults were given either the nasal vaccine  
or a placebo. Those who got the vaccine lost 18 percent to 28 
percent fewer days of work to illness with fever, got 23 percent to 
27 percent fewer fevers and made 25 percent to 41 percent fewer 
health-care visits than those who got the placebo. Other research 
has shown the vaccine is effective in young people. 
</P>
<P>
	Even more intriguing, the strains of flu virus used in making  
the vaccine that was tested in 1997 and 1998 did not match the 
strain of flu that was prevalent that year. 
</P>
<P>
	Each year, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the  
World Health Organization and the FDA guess which three strains of 
flu are most likely to be problems during the upcoming flu season. 
The vaccine shot, which consists of dead flu viruses, is then made 
up of those strains. 
</P>
<P>
	FluMist uses live strains of the virus. That triggers a response  
in the body's immune system that might help protect against other 
strains, said Dr. Kristin Nichol of the Minneapolis Veterans 
Administration Hospital, who led the FluMist study. 
</P>
<P>
	She said did not know how FluMist would compare with a shot in a  
head-to-head comparison. 
</P>
<P>
	Read said a dose of FluMist would cost somewhat more than a  
standard flu shot, which averages between $10 and $15. 
</P>
<P>
	It will probably be available only with a visit to a health-care  
provider at first, but Nichol said FluMist eventually might be 
available with a prescription that would enable people to give 
themselves the vaccine. 
</P>
<P>
	The flu kills about 20,000 people in the United States during an  
average flu season, according to the CDC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 09:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DoubleClick To Buy NetGravity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Internet advertising company DoubleClick  
Inc. announced today it will acquire rival NetGravity Inc. in a 
deal valued at $530 million. 
</P>
<P>
	DoubleClick, based in New York, sells advertising on a network  
of more than 1,500 Web sites. NetGravity, based in San Mateo, 
Calif., sells and maintains a computer software system that allows 
Web publishers to manage the advertising displayed on their sites. 
They are the two largest Internet advertising solutions companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company will be named DoubleClick and will be based  
in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock-for-stock transaction will be accounted for as a  
pooling of interests and will require regulatory and NetGravity 
stockholder approval, which is expected early in this year's fourth 
quarter, the companies said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's move comes a month after DoubleClick announced its  
purchase of Abacus Direct Corp., which manages databases that track 
what people buy, for about $800 million in stock. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
