<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 09:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Renews Shelling of India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MUSHKOH VALLEY, India (AP) -- Pakistan renewed its attack on a  
remote Indian highway tonight as Islamic guerrillas withdrew from 
the mountains of Kashmir. 
</P>
<P>
	After a daylong silence, the Pakistani anti-aircraft guns and  
artillery struck at National Highway No. 1 snaking through the 
mountains of Kaksar region near the front line town of Kargil. 
</P>
<P>
	The bombardment followed a barrage unleashed by Pakistan on  
Monday night. On Sunday, the two nuclear-armed neighbors had agreed 
to stop shooting and let the Islamic fighters withdraw from the 
mountain posts they had been occupying on India's side of the 1972 
cease-fire line that divides Kashmir. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistani officials in Islamabad said they had no immediate  
comment on the shelling. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian officers speculated the Pakistani fire was a normal  
technique to cover the retreat of its forces. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were told to expect a lot of artillery fire, under which  
the enemy will get away,'' a commander at one post in Mushkoh 
Valley said. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was injured on the road Monday night, but a boy and a  
young woman in a small village outside Kargil were injured by the 
shells. 
</P>
<P>
	In Mushkoh Valley, and in Kaksar to the east, where shelling  
continued into early today, Indian officers had confirmed seeing 
the first Pakistan-based fighters leaving their stone bunkers. 
Indian troops took control of the abandoned positions, then began 
clearing land mines, officers said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 1,200 combatants have been reported killed in fighting  
since India discovered in early May that its positions on the 
Himalayan peaks had been taken over. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said today that separatist militants attacked a heavily  
guarded paramilitary police camp 10 miles from the cease-fire line 
and shot dead a senior officer in his quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	The attack took place at a Border Security Force camp in  
Bandipora. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Deputy Inspector General S. K. Chakravorty, the  
militants also killed three other soldiers and the wife of one 
soldier. Two children were injured, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	No militant organization has claimed responsibility for the  
killings, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's withdrawal accord came a week after Pakistani Prime  
Minister Nawaz Sharif promised President Clinton to take ``concrete 
steps'' to end the fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	India has said it would consider resuming a peace dialogue with  
Pakistan that began in February only after the last intruder has 
left Indian territory. 
</P>
<P>
	India asserts that most of the intruders are Pakistani soldiers.  
Pakistan says the fighters are Kashmiri militants. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the three wars India and Pakistan have fought since gaining  
independence from Britain in 1947, two have been over Kashmir. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
