<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Madison Ave.'s Latest Hot Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The U.S. women's soccer team got together to  
pitch Disney's theme parks. The maker of Wheaties is talking about 
putting the team on a cereal box. And the players plan an 
exhibition tour this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Star Brandi Chastain created a sensation all by herself for  
Nike's new sports by taking off her jersey in the emotional 
aftermath of the Women's World Cup win in the Rose Bowl last 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	But marketing experts still caution that the burst of attention  
the U.S. women are enjoying this week may be fleeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we take a look back at this a month from now, I think  
you'll have a hard time remembering most players' names,'' said Bob 
Williams, who heads Burns Sports, a Chicago-based firm that matches 
advertisers and athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Women's World Cup matches drew unexpectedly large crowds to  
arenas across the country over the past three weeks and the TV 
ratings grew as the tournament climaxed with the United States 
beating China in the finale. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Solomon, a top commercial buyer at SFM Media, said Tuesday  
that team members captured Americans' imagination ``not only by 
their playing but by their demeanor'' and expects the feeling will 
have ``some staying power.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They didn't argue, they didn't bad-mouth anybody, they were  
always going out of their way to be gracious. The whole idea of the 
teamwork aspect captured the fancy of the public,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Williams said the lack of a professional league for women's  
soccer and tough competition for attention from established sports 
like baseball and football mean it will be hard for the women's 
soccer players to sustain the interest of marketers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Walt Disney Co. shot two ads with the soccer team Saturday  
in the Rose Bowl after its victory. The team shouted ``We're going 
to Disneyland'' in one ad and ``We're going to Disney World'' in 
the other. The television spots were airing around the nation 
Monday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has been using the approach in similar ads for its  
theme parks for the past 12 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, General Mills Inc. is talking with the team and the  
players about an appearance on a Wheaties cereal box, company 
spokesman Greg Zimprich said Tuesday. ``We are definitely 
interested,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company from Golden Valley, Minn., has heard from hundreds  
of people wondering if the team will be featured on the boxes as 
champions like the U.S. women's hockey team was after winning gold 
in the 1998 Olympics in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been inundated with calls,'' said company spokeswoman  
Natalie Peterson. 
</P>
<P>
	Kathryn Reith, a spokeswoman for Nike, said Chastain was one of  
10 U.S. team members wearing the new Nike Inner Actives sports bra 
that goes on sale for $40 on July 25. 
</P>
<P>
	She insisted Nike had not scripted Chastain's decision to rip  
off her jersey and expose the black bra. She noted Chastain has 
described it as a moment of ``temporary insanity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, she said Nike ``certainly will capitalize on it.''  
The company will use a photo of Chastain in her sports bra for 
displays in stores and may have Chastain make extra personal 
appearances promote the bra. But Reith was unaware of any broader 
advertising plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The team will stay in the public's eye for at least several  
months thanks to a planned soccer exhibition tour. 
</P>
<P>
	It will compete against a world all-star team in 11 matches  
starting Oct. 22 in Pittsburgh and ending Dec. 12 in Tacoma, Wash. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee Berke, a vice president at the sports marketing firm SFX  
Sports Group which helped organize the tour, said it will allow the 
players to earn money from soccer, stay close to their fans and 
demonstrate the viability of a professional league. 
</P>
<P>
	He said a number of sponsors including beverage, financial  
services and packaged goods companies have expressed interest in 
the tour. He said talks are underway about producing a TV special 
during the tour. 
</P>
<P>
	Keith Bruce, head of sports marketing for the ad agency Foote  
Cone &AMP; Belding, San Francisco, said he thinks the team could also 
be useful in advertising for products that stress dependability and 
performance under pressure. He suggested delivery companies, energy 
drinks, automotive companies and financial services concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the star players like Chastain, Mia Hamm, Julie Foudy  
and Briana Scurry may get more endorsement opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamm already has a number of deals with companies like Nike and  
Gatorade and ``stands to get more'' from them as well as additional 
companies, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chastain's performance may endear her to ``brands with more  
edge'' like sunglass makers, energy drinks and those that value 
strength and independence, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
