<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Community Mourns Slain Student </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- Debarah Galyan was outraged when a  
Korean college student in her community was gunned down during a 
white supremacist's killing spree over the Fourth of July weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to be with my community to stand against this kind of  
tragedy,'' Galyan, 21, said Monday as she headed into funeral 
services for Won-Joon Yoon. ``You can't have this sense of 
detachment anymore. You have to stand up and say no.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Galyan joined U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno and about 2,000  
of Yoon's family, friends and community members to pay tribute to 
him and decry the circumstances surrounding his death. 
</P>
<P>
	``Haters are cowards,'' Reno told the assemblage. ``When  
confronted, they usually back down. And if they don't back down, 
you must continue to confront them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yoon, 26, who was one of two people slain during the spree.  
Authorities believe the Indiana University undergraduate was killed 
July 4 by Benjamin Smith, a former student who committed suicide 
later that day. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, 21, was a former member of the World Church of the  
Creator, a white supremacist group based in East Peoria, Ill. 
Authorities said he also killed a former basketball coach outside 
Chicago and wounded nine other people -- all of them black, Jewish 
or Asian. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoon, the only son among four children, came to Bloomington  
after earning a master's degree in economics. His goal was to earn 
a doctorate and become a teacher. 
</P>
<P>
	At the service, his parents remained largely stoic even as a  
cousin raised the glasses and Bible that Yoon had with him when he 
was shot outside the Korean United Methodist Church. The Rev. 
Kil-Sang Yoon of the United Methodist Church asked them to express 
their pain. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to invite my brother and sister to cry today, until  
you come to the point, that yes, in this senseless death of our 
son, there is redemptive reason,'' said the clergyman, who is not 
related to the family. 
</P>
<P>
	As the ceremony ended, a beige urn containing Yoon's ashes was  
unveiled in front of his picture. Yoon's father, Shin-Ho Yoon, 
stood and lifted a Bible. 
</P>
<P>
	By then, his expression of grief was unmistakable.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
