<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Company Said Bowing on Nasdaq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Tokyo (AP) -- Internet Initiative Japan, Inc., an Internet  
service provider, plans to go public on the U.S. stock market in 
what would be the first case of a Japanese company listing its 
shares overseas before it does so at home, a news report said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet Initiative Japan (IIJ) hopes to raise about $150  
million in its share offering, which may come as early as August on 
the Nasdaq Stock Market, the Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Japan's leading 
business daily, reported in its evening edition. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for the company refused to either confirm or deny  
the report. 
</P>
<P>
	If the report is true, the move by IIJ to list its shares  
abroad, instead of at home, would be a blow to the standing of 
Japan's stock market, which is trying to raise its international 
competitiveness, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The news also comes just days after Japan's largest stock  
exchange said it will set up a new market for smaller start-up 
companies. The Tokyo Stock Exchange will open the new market early 
next year with relaxed listing requirements to attract smaller, 
lesser known companies that are now unable to raise money on 
Japan's financial markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nihon Keizai newspaper said IIJ is turning to the Nasdaq  
market because it is facing increasing competition from Japan's 
telecommunications giant Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, which, 
because of its size, can easily raise money to develop its Internet 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	IIJ was established in 1992 as the first domestic Internet  
access provider. The company has about 300 employees. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
