<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Say Banking Secrecy Rules Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERN, Switzerland (AP) -- The number of reports of suspected  
money laundering have quadrupled since Switzerland introduced rules 
last year aimed at cracking down on the practice, Swiss authorities 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The change in Switzerland's banking secrecy law, which came into  
force in April 1998, obliges bankers and other money managers to 
report suspected money laundering and freeze the assets in 
question. 
</P>
<P>
	The law, which brought Switzerland up to basic international  
standards for dealing with money laundering, was enacted after a 
series of embarrassing episodes involving assets deposited in 
Switzerland by former foreign rulers. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 210 cases involving a total of $268 million in assets have  
been reported by financial institutions, the Swiss Office of Police 
Affairs said. Before the law was tightened, 30 to 40 cases per year 
were reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The number still appears low given Switzerland's importance as a  
financial center, police said. But the increase shows that the new 
law is working, said Daniel Thelesklaf, who heads the special 
police branch dealing with these cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Two-thirds of the cases have been passed on to state judicial  
authorities, but Thelesklaf cautioned it will be some time before 
the authorities produce results. In the other cases, authorities 
have found insufficient evidence of criminal wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	In the vast majority of the cases -- 80 percent -- the assets had  
a foreign link, Thelesklaf said. Fraud is suspected in many cases, 
while only seven reports involved suspicions of drug money. 
</P>
<P>
	Failure to comply with the law brings a fine of $127,000.  
</P>
<P>
	One case leading up to the law came in 1997, when the country's  
high court ordered the transfer of assets belonging to the late 
Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos to the Philippines. The court 
said it was against Swiss interests ``to serve as a safe haven'' 
for flight capital or criminal proceeds. 
</P>
<P>
	Also frozen in Switzerland pending legal action are assets  
belonging to the late Zairian dictator Mobutu Sese Seko. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
