<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Dole: No Two-For-One Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT DODGE, Iowa (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole said Tuesday that she and  
her husband, 1996 GOP presidential nominee Bob Dole, don't believe 
in a two-for-one deal as she runs for the party's 2000 nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bob and I have never felt that's the way it should be,'' she  
said during a campaign stop here. ``You are casting your vote for 
me, not for Bob, in this instance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his first campaign for president, Bill Clinton said that with  
his wife's law degree and work experience, Americans would be 
electing two candidates for the price of one if they voted for him. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole said that if she is elected, her administration will  
not be ``a co-presidency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She joked she needs help in deciding what the title would be for  
the husband of the country's first woman president. 
</P>
<P>
	``First gentleman? First man? What?'' she asked. ``And any  
suggestions you have as to what his function should be also is wide 
open right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole said that her husband's experience as a senator,  
presidential candidate and advocate for the disabled makes him a 
valuable adviser to her. 
</P>
<P>
	``The man is very talented, so you certainly want to utilize  
that, but in a specific way,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	On other subjects, Mrs. Dole said that as president, she would  
outlaw the late-term abortion critics call ``partial-birth 
abortion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She also said the nation's campaign finance laws need to be  
changed, with candidates required to disclose more of their 
financial records. But she said she thinks the $1,000 federal cap 
on individual campaign contributions needs to be raised, possibly 
to as high as $5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``The $1,000 that a person can give, that goes back to the  
1970s,'' she said. ``It doesn't even reflect the rate of 
inflation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During one of her campaign stops, a member of the audience asked  
her what she thinks about the proposals for gun registration. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like it,'' she said. ``I don't think it's necessary.''  
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic front-runner, has  
suggested photo licenses for those who buy handguns. Gore's rival 
for the nomination, former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, advocates 
that move, plus registration of all handguns in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole continued to offer veiled criticism of Texas Gov.  
George W. Bush, saying that she'll tell voters exactly where she 
stands on an issue. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
