<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Cos. Criticize Tariff Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The country's biggest oil companies spoke out  
Tuesday against a coalition of small domestic producers who are 
asking the government to impose price tariffs on certain oil 
imports. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Petroleum Institute, which represents the major  
U.S. oil producers, said oil prices are set by world markets and 
there's no evidence that any of the foreign producing countries are 
illegally dumping oil on the U.S. market. 
</P>
<P>
	The government can impose a tariff if an imported commodity is  
being sold at less than normal value or below what it costs to 
produce it. This practice is called illegal dumping. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago, an Oklahoma-based coalition of independent oil  
producers calling itself Save Domestic Oil filed a petition with 
the Commerce Department charging Iraq, Mexico, Saudi Arabia and 
Venezuela with illegally dumping oil on the U.S. market. 
</P>
<P>
	The move was unprecedented and caught major U.S. oil companies,  
which generally have large overseas production as well, by 
surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the big oil companies said they were ``sympathetic''  
to the economic problems of the small U.S. producers but 
nonetheless vowed to challenge the illegal dumping charge every 
step of the way. 
</P>
<P>
	``This anti-dumping petition will only make matters worse  
because it will have the unintended consequence of making the oil 
supply system less efficient,'' API president Red Cavaney told 
reporters. He said that ``reliable historic information shows that 
prices are established by world oil markets'' and not illegal 
dumping strategies by certain producing countries. 
</P>
<P>
	As a first step, the API planned to challenge the idea that the  
Oklahoma-based group has legal standing to file an anti-dumping 
petition. By law, anyone filing a petition must demonstrate at 
least 25 percent of domestic production. 
</P>
<P>
	The API will argue before the U.S. International Trade  
Commission and the Commerce Department, which together deal with 
anti-dumping complaints, that U.S. production data shows that the 
Oklahoma group does not meet the 25 percent production requirement. 
</P>
<P>
	In its petition the Oklahoma group excluded the West Coast oil  
markets, including Alaska, where more than a quarter of U.S. oil is 
produced, mostly by major companies. 
</P>
<P>
	But API lawyers will argue that domestic production in those  
areas should be included in considering the dumping issue, making 
it more difficult to meet the 25 percent production rule. ``U.S. 
production is U.S. production,'' said Cavaney. 
</P>
<P>
	Harold Hamm of Enid, Okla., chairman of Save Domestic Oil, did  
not immediately return a telephone call Tuesday seeking response to 
the API action. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oklahoma petition argued that regional domestic oil  
producers were economically harmed by these ``unfairly traded 
imports'' and threaten to cause additional harm if the U.S. 
government does not intervene. 
</P>
<P>
	The Independent Petroleum Association of America, the principle  
organization of small and medium gas and oil companies, estimates 
the domestic oil industry has lost 52,000 jobs and shut down 
136,000 oil wells since November, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Trade Commission was expected to decide on the  
Oklahoma group's standing in early August. If the commission finds 
the petition to be valid, it will decide on whether the domestic 
industry has been harmed by illegal dumping. The Commerce 
Department then would decide on an import duty. 
</P>
<P>
	Cavaney made clear that even if the large oil companies lose the  
first round, they intend to challenge the dumping argument on its 
merits. 
</P>
<P>
	An import tariff would mean higher prices for U.S. consumers  
because imports would shift from targeted countries to other 
producers whose oil may be more expensive or of inferior quality, 
he said. ``Over the long term, it's difficult to see who would 
benefit from this action.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 10:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Alleged Railway Killer in Custody  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, the rail-riding  
fugitive suspected of killing eight people who lived along railway 
lines, is in FBI custody in Texas, a spokeswoman said today. The 
39-year-old drifter is charged in two murders and linked to six 
other slayings. One FBI official said Resendez-Ramirez turned 
himself in to law enforcement officers near El Paso, Texas. The 
official said members of his family helped arrange his surrender. 
His ability to elude law enforcement had been an embarrassment, 
topped by his release to Mexico by Border Patrol agents June 2, 
although he was wanted by the FBI and Houston police had told the 
immigration service they wanted him for questioning in a murder. 

</P>
<P>
	Indictments Coming in ValuJet Crash  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A federal grand jury investigating the 1996 crash  
of ValuJet Flight 592 will indict the airline's maintenance 
contractor and some employees, an unprecedented step in an aviation 
accident, Justice Department sources said today. Indictments will 
name several individuals involved in the packing of the illegal 
cargo blamed for the crash. Investigators found that workers for 
ValuJet's maintenance contractor, SabreTech Inc., improperly packed 
oxygen canisters that were loaded into the cargo hold. A fire 
burned through the floor of the passenger cabin, causing the DC-9 
to plunge into the Everglades, killing 110 people. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton, Congress Argue Over HMOs  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton accused Republicans today of  
buckling under pressure from health insurance companies and backing 
a ``watered-down'' plan to protect people in health-maintenance 
organizations. ``It is nowhere near what the American people 
deserve and need,'' Clinton said. The GOP bill is a much more 
modest version of the Democratic ``patients' bill of rights,'' 
covering fewer people and leaving out the right to sue if a patient 
is harmed by a denial of care. Debate began yesterday on the bill 
and a final vote on the entire bill is set for Thursday. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S., Russia Sign Steel Agreement  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Russia has agreed to limit shipments of steel  
to the United States over a five-year period to avoid imposition of 
punitive American tariffs, Commerce Secretary William Daley 
announced today. ``These agreements deliver on the administration's 
commitment to guarantee that surging imports do not threaten the 
livelihoods of communities and workers around the nation,'' Daley 
said. The two sides signed the agreements covering different types 
of steel following bargaining talks in Paris. The deals will set 
annual quotas for Russian steel shipments, reducing imports for all 
Russian steel shipments by 64 percent this year compared to 1998, 
the department said. 

</P>
<P>
	Police Investigate Atlanta Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Police are investigating whether the slaying of  
eight people at a southwest Atlanta home was a murder-suicide. 
Eleven-year-old Santonio Briskey, who hid in a closet for eight 
hours after being shot in the elbow yesterday, was the only 
survivor. The gunman killed his mother, aunt and four siblings. The 
boy allegedly told a neighbor that his stepfather had shot 
``everyone in the house.'' Santonio was in stable condition at a 
hospital. 

</P>
<P>
	Indianapolis News Closing Down  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The afternoon Indianapolis News will shut  
down in October, ending 130 years of publication, its publisher 
announced today. Changing reader needs brought about the closing of 
the newspaper, Dale A. Duncan, president and publisher of the News 
and The Indianapolis Star, said in a statement. The Oct. 1 edition 
will be the last. According to the most recent figures, the average 
daily circulation for The Indianapolis News for the six-month 
period ending March 27 was 33,175, compared with 111,000 in 1989. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Move Lower; Dow Off 60.47  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell from their lofty highs today as  
banking and financial stocks were hit hard by concerns about Latin 
America's economic recovery. Just before 1 p.m. EDT, the Dow Jones 
industrial average was down 60.47 at 11,140.51 after having 
achieved three closing highs in the past four sessions. NYSE 
decliners lead advancers 1,788-995. The Nasdaq composite index fell 
23.12 to 2,767.32. 

</P>
<P>
	China Welcomes Home Soccer Team  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- President Jiang Zemin led an official welcoming  
ceremony today for the Chinese women's soccer team, which brought 
home a World Cup silver medal. The 5-4 loss to the United States on 
penalty kicks chagrined Chinese fans. But their sorrow has been 
tempered by pride that China's women made it to the finals and held 
the Americans scoreless in regular play. ``You didn't disappoint 
the wishes of the masses,'' Jiang said during a reception at the 
Great Hall of the People in Beijing. ``You showed on the playing 
field the self-reliance and self-confidence of Chinese women.'' 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
