<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ohio Killing Spree Suspect Captured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIDNEY, Ohio (AP) -- A man suspected of killing three teen-age  
girls and a Bible teacher surrendered Tuesday after taking three 
people hostage at a gas station. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence Michael Hensley was spotted in a car loaded with guns  
shortly after a driver was wounded on a nearby highway. He led 
police on a chase and took hostages at a filling station before 
surrendering at 5 a.m., authorities said. The hostages were not 
hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	Hensley, 30, has been sought since the deaths of his neighbor,  
Sherry Kimbler, 16, Tosha L. Barrett, 16, and Amy Mikesell, 14, who 
were all found dead in Hensley's home Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He was also wanted in the death of Brett Wildermuth, 37, a  
Bible-study teacher who had helped minister to Hensley. Police say 
Hensley killed the girls, then drove with his wife to Wildermuth's 
house for a prayer session and shot him. 
</P>
<P>
	Hensley was charged with four counts of aggravated murder and  
ordered held on $1 million cash bond during a brief court 
appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's drama began shortly before 3 a.m. when a man driving  
on Interstate 75 was shot by a passing motorist. A few minutes 
later, about a mile away, a shot was fired at the home of John 
Bruce, one of Hensley's Bible-study teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers giving chase said Hensley pulled into a gas station in  
Sidney, about 35 miles north of Dayton, jumped out and ran inside. 
Hensley took two men hostage. A female clerk locked herself in an 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	After telephone negotiations over the next hour, Hensley  
released the hostages unharmed and emerged. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel relief, like tons of bricks have been lifted off my  
shoulders,'' said 15-year-old Mindy Swiger, who lived near Hensley 
and was a classmate of one of the teen-age victims. 
</P>
<P>
	No motive for the shootings has been provided by police. The  
Dayton Daily News reported Hensley was twice convicted in four 
years for public indecency. 
</P>
<P>
	His pastor, the Rev. Ben Davis of the First Church of God, said  
Hensley had been involved in devil worship but was trying to mend 
his ways. 
</P>
<P>
	The shot motorist was in serious condition, according to  
officials. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
