<DOCNO> APW19990713.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 01:10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Plans First Fund-Raiser </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Getting into the real nitty gritty of  
politics, Hillary Rodham Clinton has begun raising money for 
herself for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman said Monday that Mrs. Clinton has begun dialing for  
dollars from the White House for her Senate campaign in New York 
and will have her first fund-raising event this week in Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard Wolfson said Mrs. Clinton has been making calls to  
potential donors from the residential quarters of the White House 
using a private phone line or a personal cellular phone. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can tell you three things'' about the fund raising, Wolfson  
said. ``One is, it's a necessity. Two is, it's going very well. 
And, three is, that it's all being done appropriately and 
legally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore came under heavy  
criticism for fund-raising activities during their 1996 re-election 
campaign and several of their fund-raisers have faced criminal 
charges in connection with that. The Democratic National Committee 
had to return $3 million in donations from the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolfson refused to say how much money Mrs. Clinton has raised.  
She formed her exploratory committee last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolfson said Mrs. Clinton would hold a $1,000-a-person event in  
Manhattan on Thursday morning for fewer than 100 people. That 
session will also serve as an organizational meeting for her 
fund-raising efforts with those on hand forming her core group of 
campaign fund-raisers. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those expected to attend the event are Wall Street tycoon  
Roger Altman, who was deputy treasury secretary during President 
Clinton's first term, and millionaire businessman Erskine Bowles, a 
former White House chief of staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton spent part of Monday in New York working on her  
fund-raising effort. Her campaign is expected to cost $20 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 20:30:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fans Flock to Fenway for Big Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Unshaved and haggard, David Deems walked slowly  
around Fenway Park, a sign in his hand and a dream in his heart. 
</P>
<P>
	``Came from China 4 a ticket,'' the sign read.  
</P>
<P>
	Deems, 31, wore a tired smile as he described the long flight  
from Shanghai to New York, then the trip to Boston on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm here to see the history of baseball,'' Deems said. ``I've  
got to get around to all these old ballparks before they die.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Deems, a Cleveland native, the visit to 87-year-old Fenway  
Park for the All-Star Game was the latest chapter in a personal 
mission that included a stop at Chicago's Comiskey Park three days 
before it closed, as well as visits to Detroit's Tiger Stadium and 
Cleveland's Municipal Stadium during their final seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Others among the thousands of fans milling past the program  
vendors on Yawkey Way and beneath the shadow of the Green Monster 
on Lansdowne Street echoed the sentiment that somehow, Fenway Park 
was different from all those antiseptic modern ballparks named for 
high-tech companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Fenway belongs to an older generation, a time when players wore  
mitts barely bigger than their hands and chewed wads of tobacco as 
big as baseballs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just seems like a very friendly, very personal place,''  
said Greg Packer, 34, who took a bus from Long Island and slept on 
a park bench for a chance to score a ticket. ``There's less of that 
around in today's world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Packer, like thousands of others, was still without a ticket as  
Pedro Martinez threw the first pitch of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	So was Scott Marathas, 27, who flew up from Orlando, Fla., for  
the game. Marathas didn't seem to mind, as he held up a single 
finger showing that he was looking for one ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is it! I'm at Fenway Park for the All-Star Game, for  
God's sakes!'' said Marathas, a lifelong Red Sox fan who grew up in 
New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	Marathas, a trainer for an Internet television company, said  
people had offered to sell him tickets worth $175 for as much as 
$2,500. He said he hoped ticket prices would sink as the game went 
on. 
</P>
<P>
	Just up Yawkey Way, Gus Farian was no luckier. Farian, four days  
short of his 75th birthday, wore a special shirt made to improve 
his chances of getting a ticket. ``Help me celebrate my 75th 
birthday. I need a ticket!'' the shirt said. 
</P>
<P>
	By game time, Farian, who had been slowly circling the park for  
4 1/2 hours, hadn't had any offers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things are tough,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Just then, a young man in a blue sports shirt walked by and  
handed him a $100 ticket to the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Farian tried to pay the man, but he kept walking. ``No, no, just  
enjoy the game,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Farian, a wide smile on his face and a bounce in his step,  
joined the throngs filing through the turnstiles -- an aging man 
turned young by the promise of a timeless game in a classic 
ballpark. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 12:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Soccer Team Celebrates in N.Y. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Unaffected by a night of dining and dancing,  
members of the World Cup-winning U.S. women's soccer team today 
welcomed a few hundred fans in midtown by thanking them for their 
support. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no idea what to say. I'm completely overwhelmed,'' said  
Brandi Chastain, who scored the game-winning penalty kick on 
Saturday. ``We need you to be successful, so thank you very much 
for coming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The players swapped jerseys with a handful of young girls, while  
others in the crowd were just happy to see their idols. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great because, I mean, they represent our country so  
well,'' said Caitlin Cittarelli, a 13-year-old soccer player for 
her hometown of Stratford, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if she favors the women's team over their male  
counterparts, the teen quickly replied, ``The women. Everybody 
knows the women try harder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. women's soccer team will return to the city next week  
for an appearance on ``Late Show with David Letterman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The get-together marked day two of the champions' visit to New  
York. The first day stretched late into the night as the women 
danced with their fans at The China Club. Earlier, some of them 
enjoyed a dinner of Chinese food. 
</P>
<P>
	The cuisine and nightlife choices were just coincidence and were  
not intended as jabs at the defeated Chinese team, insisted backup 
U.S. goalkeeper Saskia Webber with a slight grin. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, it has nothing to do with it,'' she said Monday night as  
she and a handful of teammates entered the China Grill in midtown 
Manhattan to a standing ovation from patrons. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the diners was Jim Hook, a youth soccer referee from  
Memphis. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a tremendous thrill,'' he gushed. ``All my kids love  
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another diner, lawyer Lisa Babiskin, was thrilled to meet the  
players. 
</P>
<P>
	``They should absolutely go out and celebrate their  
accomplishment,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	After dinner, around 11 p.m., eight of the players headed to The  
China Club, a celebrity nightclub in midtown Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	Chastain said she and the other players worked hard to win the  
World Cup and needed a relaxing night of boogieing to disco tunes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tonight we just want to forget about being soccer players and  
listen to the music,'' she said at the club at about 12:30 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a good time just dancing,'' Webber said as the players'  
partying drew to a close about 4 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	The club's disc jockey congratulated the players, who bumped  
hips with each other and friends on the crowded dance floor while 
other clubgoers applauded. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-week World Cup tournament ended Saturday at the Rose  
Bowl in Los Angeles, setting off their whirlwind of activities. The 
players were welcomed at Disneyland on Sunday, then flew overnight, 
landing at Newark Airport in New Jersey at 4:30 a.m. and piling on 
a bus to Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's fun,'' said Mia Hamm, the U.S. team's biggest star. ``I  
love New York. There's so many things to do and so many things to 
see.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 12:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
