<DOCNO> APW19990713.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 12:40:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Capel Helps U.S. to Relay Sweep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALMA DE MALLORCA, Balearic Islands (AP) -- This U.S. men's  
sprint relay team finally got it right, and led a gold sweep for 
the Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising stars John Capel, Coby Miller and their teammates avoided  
the baton blunders that have derailed the United States at major 
events recently, and won the 400-meter relay at the World 
University Games on Tuesday in 38.55 seconds, the fifth fastest 
time of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	South Africa was second in 39.08 and Italy finished third in  
39.31. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States also triumphed in the women's 400 relay and  
both 1,600 relays as the 11-day Olympics-style event wrapped up at 
Son Moix Stadium. The Americans won the men's 1,600 in 3:00.88, the 
third fastest time of 1999, to beat Britain by more than 3 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Other winners Tuesday were Kenya's Bernard Lagat in the 1,500  
meters, Eriks Rags in the javelin for Latvia's only medal of the 
games, and Britain's Ben Challenger in the high jump. Among the 
women, Rie Ueno of Japan won easily in the 5,000, while Olena 
Shekhovisova of Ukraine took the long jump. 
</P>
<P>
	Flubbing relays in big meets has become commonplace for American  
400-meter teams in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	At the World Championships two years ago, they blew the first  
handoff, between leadoff runner Brian Lewis and Tim Montgomery, in 
the first round. They failed to finish their first-round heat at 
the 1995 World Championships, when Jon Drummond and substitute Tony 
McCall failed to connect on the second exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	They were disqualified at the 1988 Olympics because of a handoff  
outside the zone, and were beaten by Canada at the 1996 Atlanta 
Games -- the only U.S. 400 relay Olympic loss other than by 
disqualification. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem with the U.S. in relays is the short time they  
have to work together. In the long relay it's not a problem, but in 
short relay it is,'' said Clyde Hart, who like the rest of the U.S. 
track coaches here will also guide the team at the 2000 Sydney 
Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very proud of our guys here. This is the team of the  
future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The men's 400 victory marked a measure of redemption for Capel,  
the track and football standout from the University of Florida, who 
finished a disappointing second to Brazil's Andre Domingos Da Silva 
in the 100 dash here Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	A rematch in the relay never materialized, though, because  
Brazil dropped the baton in the first exchange and Da Silva didn't 
get the chance to challenge Capel in the anchor leg. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was not worried about the Brazilian. I know he's not faster  
than me,'' said Capel, who starts football practice with Florida 
Friday. ``The Brazilian said that we cannot run, that we talk too 
much trash. So we proved that we can win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller added the gold to his earlier triumph in the 200 meters,  
while Terrence Trammell, who ran the second leg Tuesday, had 
already won gold here in the 110-meter hurdles. 
</P>
<P>
	In the women's 400 relay, U.S. anchor Nanceen Perry pulled away  
from Poland's Zuzanna Radecka down the stretch. Angela Williams, 
who won the women's 100 dash Sunday, Torri Edwards and Lakeisha 
Backus completed the American quartet, which finished in 43.49. 
</P>
<P>
	Poland took the silver in 43.74, with Germany third in 43.96.  
</P>
<P>
	The United States took the women's 1,600 in 3:27.97.  
</P>
<P>
	The five American medals Tuesday -- Adrien Sawyer took silver in  
the women's long jump -- brought the country's total to a games-high 
63, 30 gold. Russia finished second overall with 43 medals, 14 
gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers said a record total of 4,030 athletes participated in  
the 12 sports. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2001 Summer University Games are in Beijing, China.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
