<HEADLINE> Stallone Settles Lawsuits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- The woman who accused President Clinton of  
making a sexual advance in the White House six years ago is engaged 
to be married. 
</P>
<P>
	Kathleen Willey said she is preparing for a fall wedding to  
longtime friend Bill Schwicker, who proposed in June. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to get married and try to put all this behind me,''  
she told The Associated Press on Tuesday. ``It's all over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Willey said Clinton groped her in 1993 near the Oval Office,  
one day before her husband was found dead of a self-inflicted 
gunshot wound. He had been distraught over financial troubles. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has denied any such encounter.  
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with the magazine Style Weekly, Ms. Willey said  
she fled to Schwicker's home in Florida to duck the press last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a while it was indescribable,'' she said. ``I got to the  
point where I found it laughable what people would say and do to 
get me to talk.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Gov. Jesse Ventura has slapped down any  
suggestion that his return to wrestling threatens the dignity of 
his office. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no rule that says a governor can't have fun. There's  
no rule that says a governor on his own time can't be a human,'' he 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, who wrestled professionally as ``The Body'' until  
retiring in 1986, has hinted that he may return to the ring Aug. 22 
at Target Center in Minneapolis. The sold-out ``SummerSlam'' event 
will be on pay-per-view. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura refused to discuss details of the event, though he has  
said a contribution would go to two charities. 
</P>
<P>
	``The perception is that people need to be professional  
politicians and that therefore being a politician is your entire 
life. Well, it's not Jesse Ventura's entire life and I think I was 
elected upon the fact that I came from being a private citizen,'' 
said Ventura, a Reform Party politician. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, state GOP Chairman Ron Eibensteiner called the  
governor's return to the ring ``an absolute outrage'' and said 
Ventura was ``using the office of governor to promote his own 
personal enrichment.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The surgeon who reshaped Paula Jones' nose has  
been sued by his office assistant, who claims he demanded sex as a 
condition for keeping her job. 
</P>
<P>
	Christine Sabia said in court papers that immediately after Dr.  
Thomas W. Loeb did Mrs. Jones' surgery in July 1998, he went into 
his office, dropped his pants and demanded oral sex. 
</P>
<P>
	Sabia, 36, also said Loeb had planned to videotape Mrs. Jones'  
surgery and sell it to the highest-bidding tabloid. The suit did 
not say whether the videotape was made. 
</P>
<P>
	Loeb admitted he had an affair with Sabia but said it was brief,  
consensual and initiated by her. Loeb said he ended the affair and 
Sabia has been demanding money ever since. 
</P>
<P>
	``The easiest thing to do would have been to pay her off, but I  
was not willing to be extorted,'' Loeb said Tuesday. ``I trust in 
our legal system and I'm sure I'll be vindicated in court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sabia said in papers filed in Manhattan's State Supreme Court  
that she submitted to Loeb for nearly nine months because she 
needed the salary. Her lawsuit asks for unspecified damages and 
attorneys' fees. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Rocky's contentious two-year court battle is  
over. 
</P>
<P>
	Sylvester Stallone and his brother settled breach-of-contract  
lawsuits with two entertainment firms over the movie ``The Good 
Life,'' which starred Frank Stallone and featured a cameo by the 
star of ``Rocky'' and ``Rambo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement between DEM Productions Inc., FM Entertainment and  
the Stallone brothers was reached Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the settlement were confidential, said Frank Stallone's  
attorney, Barry Cohen. A DEM attorney didn't return a telephone 
message left Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stallones filed separate lawsuits against the entertainment  
companies in 1997. DEM and FM Entertainment filed a $50 million 
countersuit against the brothers saying they ``behaved like the 
gangsters they portray.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The countersuit said the Stallones tried unsuccessfully to take  
over production of ``The Good Life'' and later tried to destroy 
DEM. The brothers denied the charges. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Michigan has joined 13 other states in a  
suit against entertainer Robin Leach and two Florida companies, 
claiming they misled consumers about tropical vacation packages. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan Attorney General Jennifer Granholm said Tuesday that  
Ramada Plaza Resorts and National Travel Services of Fort 
Lauderdale, Fla., mailed ``official-looking'' documents telling 
consumers they had won a Florida vacation and a cruise to the 
Bahamas. 
</P>
<P>
	Accommodations were described as ``world class,'' Granholm said.  
Leach, best known for the TV series ``Lifestyles of the Rich and 
Famous,'' endorsed the travel package. 
</P>
<P>
	Granholm said consumers actually won a chance to pay $1,000 for  
a 7-day trip to Florida. The cruise to the Bahamas consisted of a 
ride on a car ferry, she said, and ``Las Vegas-style'' gambling was 
a game of bingo. 
</P>
<P>
	Granholm said the companies also failed to tell participants  
that they would have to sit through a lengthy presentation on 
timeshares. ``Having to sit through a sales presentation and pay 
inflated prices for a `free' vacation is nothing more than a 
scam,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rich Epstein, an attorney representing Leach and the two  
companies, did not return a message Tuesday. A spokesperson for 
Leach has said that the entertainer cut his ties with the Florida 
companies last year. 
  	   	
</P>
