<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women Urge Senators About Bankruptcy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A diverse mix of 30 groups involved with  
women's and children's issues, including the National Organization 
for Women and Church Women United, are urging senators to oppose 
legislation that would make it tougher to erase debts through 
bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	The groups signed a letter sent to the 100 members of the  
Senate, which is expected to consider soon the sweeping bill to 
rewrite the bankruptcy laws being pushed by banks and credit card 
companies. The groups maintain the bill would hurt single women and 
their children owed support payments by bankrupt fathers. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would put ``economically vulnerable women and  
children at greater risk,'' the women's groups said in the letter 
sent late last month. By expanding the legal claims against debtors 
of credit card companies, finance companies and auto lenders, they 
said, ``the bill would set up a competition for scarce resources 
between parents and children owed child support and commercial 
creditors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill awaiting Senate action could worsen the situation of  
women at a time when they already are under mounting financial 
pressure, opponents of the overhaul claim. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics of the bill cite new data from Harvard law professor  
Elizabeth Warren indicating that women have been turning to the 
shelter of bankruptcy court in greater proportion than men and 
married couples. 
</P>
<P>
	First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, who complained publicly last  
year that the legislation would put credit card companies ahead of 
single mothers and children owed support, has been pushing behind 
the scenes in recent months to amend it. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue has divided the Democrats, allowing a bankruptcy  
overhaul bill to pass the House in May by a veto-proof 313-108 
margin. The Clinton administration has opposed the House measure, 
sponsored by Reps. George Gekas, R-Pa., and Jim Moran, D-Va., which 
is stricter toward debtors than the Senate version. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, chief author of the Senate bill,  
has been trying to work out compromises with opponents. Sen. Robert 
Torricelli, D-N.J., is co-sponsor of the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley and the House measure's sponsors say the legislation  
helps women whose husbands or former husbands have filed for 
bankruptcy by giving child support and alimony payments a higher 
priority than credit card debt and other obligations. Under current 
law, some debts -- such as bankruptcy lawyers' fees -- must be paid 
before child support or alimony. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything possible has been done (in the bill) to protect  
child support payments,'' Grassley spokeswoman Jill Kozeny said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	She said that includes a new provision allowing debtors who owe  
child support to erase more debts in bankruptcy proceedings than 
those who don't. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, Ms. Kozeny said, when a parent who owes child  
support files for bankruptcy, ``there will be a smaller number -- 
not a larger number -- of debts that will compete with child support 
and alimony after a bankruptcy has been completed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But opponents maintain that the legislation, by barring certain  
credit card debts from being erased in bankruptcy, would force 
single mothers and children owed support by bankrupt fathers to 
compete with credit card companies in collecting debts. 
</P>
<P>
	By sending the letters to senators, the women's groups showed  
``an understanding of how much bankruptcy is a woman's issue,'' 
Joan Entmacher, vice president of the liberal National Women's Law 
Center, said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the liberal National Organization for Women and  
the faith-based Church Women United, the 30 groups signing the 
letter included the Association for Children for Enforcement of 
Support, the American Medical Women's Association, Business and 
Professional Women USA, the National Black Women's Health Project, 
the National Council of Jewish Women, the Women's Institute for 
Freedom of the Press and the YWCA. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 12:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Wins Interracial Adoption Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Ending a long legal battle, the  
state has let a white woman adopt the 4-year-old black boy she has 
raised since birth, and agreed to pay her $135,000 in legal costs 
for the discrimination lawsuit she filed. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a settlement approved Monday, the Florida Department of  
Children and Families also apologized to Shirley Fitzgerald and 
acknowledged it made a mistake in trying to place the boy with 
black relatives whom Fitzgerald said ignored his medical needs. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy, named Shaq (pronounced ``Shay'') was born to a  
drug-addicted woman and has asthma, epilepsy, damaged hearing and 
delayed speech development. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement says medical opinions clearly establish it is  
best for Shaq to remain with Ms. Fitzgerald and her two adopted 
daughters, the only family he has known. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, Ms. Fitzgerald agreed to drop her civil rights  
lawsuit, one of the first in the nation to challenge an adoption 
decision under state and federal anti-discrimination laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit alleged state officials discriminated against Ms.  
Fitzgerald because she is white and against her adopted daughters 
because they have the AIDS virus. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement provides for supervised, three-hour visits once a  
month between Shaq and his relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very progressive agreement,'' said Ms. Fitzgerald's  
lawyer, Alan Mishael. ``A lot of time and effort went into this to 
try to give this child the best of both worlds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fitzgerald, 63, of Palm Beach Gardens, is a longtime foster  
parent for children with medical problems, primarily the AIDS 
virus. The state placed Shaq with her just days after he was born; 
he was HIV-positive at the time but tested negative a year later. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaq's great-aunt and great-uncle, Carolyn and Paul Simmons of  
Clewiston, are raising two of his five half-siblings as foster 
children and sought custody of him in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fitzgerald alleged that the aunt didn't give Shaq  
medications as needed and that the couple's smoking triggered his 
asthma attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Simmons said Monday she didn't know anything about the  
settlement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
