<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Mostly Unchanged / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices of most Treasury securities held steady  
Tuesday as many investors stayed out of the market, deciding to 
wait for the government's upcoming release of key economic 
statistics for June. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the government's benchmark 30-year Treasury bond  
was unchanged from Monday's close as its yield remained at 5.90 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors awaited the release of June data on retail sales,  
producer prices and consumer prices, due out on Wednesday and 
Thursday. These figures are considered important indicators of 
inflation, which tends to erode the value of fixed-rate securities, 
such as bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader Treasury market, prices of short-term and  
intermediate securities also were unchanged, reported Bridge 
Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading, yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to  
4.69 percent while the discount fell 0.03 percentage point to 4.57 
percent. Six-month yields fell to 4.69 percent, as the discount 
fell 0.02 percentage point to 4.52 percent. One-year yields fell to 
4.95 percent as the discount fell 0.01 percent to 4.71 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4.94 percent from 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 1/8 point to 119 3/8. The average yield to 
maturity was unchanged at 5.51 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
