<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Women Set TV Ratings Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- These American women don't just win, they set  
records -- for biggest crowds and TV ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	The final match, which drew a women's sports-record 90,185 to  
the Rose Bowl, turned out to be the most-watched soccer game in 
U.S. television history. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States' victory over China posted a 11.4 preliminary  
national rating and a 31 share, according to ABC. That was 20 
percent higher than the 1994 men's World Cup final between Italy 
and Brazil, which had a 9.5/24. 
</P>
<P>
	The success even prompted ESPN to replay the game Tuesday night  
opposite baseball's All-Star game. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 11.3 million homes and 40 million viewers watched  
the American women's shootout victory. The 1994 championship game 
was seen in 8.9 million homes on ABC and another 1.6 million homes 
on Spanish-speaking Univision, a total of 10.5 million households. 
This year's game was not available on Univision. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's rating was double ABC's 5.7 rating for last year's  
men's World Cup final between Brazil and France. 
</P>
<P>
	The American men in last year's World Cup didn't come close to  
the women. The three games involving the men in the 1998 World Cup 
averaged just a 3.0 national rating, partially because of the 
team's lack of success and also due to the fact that the tournament 
was played in France instead of the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The Women's World Cup finale easily topped the NHL's Stanley Cup  
ratings, a 3.4 average for the three games on Fox. It was even 
higher than the 1999 NBA Finals average of 11.3/21 and just shy of 
last year's World Series average of 14.1. 
</P>
<P>
	The American women began the tournament on ABC and received a  
1.7 national rating in an opening-round victory over Denmark. That 
game was watched in 1.7 million homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory against Nigeria was seen in 1.4 million homes on  
ESPN, the win over Germany was watched in 1.67 million households 
and the semifinal match against Brazil was viewed in 2.9 million 
homes, making it the largest number of households to watch a 
telecast on the cable network. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a fantastic success story,'' ESPN president George  
Bodenheimer said. ``We were just pleased to be the television 
carrier, along with ABC. The tournament was a remarkable success.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rating is the percentage of TV households in the United  
States tuned to a program, and each point represents 994,000 homes. 
Each cable point represents 766,000 homes on ESPN. The share is the 
percentage tuned to a program among televisions in use at the time. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 09:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indianapolis News Closing Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The afternoon Indianapolis News will shut  
down in October, ending 130 years of publication, its publisher 
announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	Changing reader preferences brought about the closing of the  
newspaper, Dale A. Duncan, president and publisher of the News and 
The Indianapolis Star, said in a statement. The Oct. 1 edition will 
be the last. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the most recent figures, the average daily  
circulation for The Indianapolis News for the six-month period 
ending March 27 was 33,175, compared with 111,000 in 1989. By 
contrast, average daily circulation for the Star in the period was 
235,790 daily and 385,869 on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Indianapolis is a solid, healthy newspaper market, as  
indicated by the circulation of the morning Star,'' said Louis A. 
Weil III, chief executive officer of Central Newspapers Inc., which 
owns both newspapers. ``However, the eroding circulation numbers 
for the News have also made it increasingly apparent that our 
customers prefer to read the paper in the morning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The shutdown of the News reflects a continuing trend in daily  
newspaper publishing that favors morning papers over afternoon 
dailies. In 1998, according to the latest Editor &AMP; Publisher Year 
Book, 30 evening dailies converted to morning publication. 
</P>
<P>
	The News closing will leave 47 cities with two or more  
newspapers, according to the figures compiled by The Associated 
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Central Newspapers also owns The Arizona Republic and several  
smaller newspapers, as well as related media and information 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The two news operations will be merged, resulting in the  
elimination of about 20 newsroom positions, which will come 
primarily through voluntary severance offers. Twelve positions in 
other departments will be eliminated and there will be reduced 
shifts in some areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The closing is expected to result in a one-time, pretax charge  
for Central Newspapers of about $1.25 million. By closing the News, 
Central Newspapers expects to save $3 million to $3.5 million. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 16:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Extradited To Face Murder Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- A man accused of shooting a woman, slitting  
her throat and leaving her 2-year-old quadruplets crawling in her 
blood was extradited Tuesday from Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Luis Del Toro was brought to Miami by federal agents and  
put in jail, pending a trip to Sarasota later Tuesday or Wednesday. 
James Bellush, the victim's husband, asked a House subcommittee in 
June for help in pressuring the Mexican government to hand Del Toro 
over. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors had to agree not to seek the death penalty to win  
extradition of Del Toro, 22, a U.S. citizen who had put up a 
vigorous fight against his return to Florida. Mexico does not have 
the death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	He is charged with murder in the 1997 death of Sheila Bellush,  
35, who had moved from Texas to Florida to start a new life. 
</P>
<P>
	Two men have been convicted for their roles in the crime, and  
authorities say they have compelling evidence against Del Toro, who 
was arrested in Mexico weeks after the killing. He was in the 
country illegally. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Rocha, who was convicted of murdering Mrs. Bellush, has  
said he is willing to testify that Mrs. Bellush's ex-husband, San 
Antonio businessman Allen Blackthorne, planned her death. 
</P>
<P>
	A grand jury in Texas is investigating Blackthorne's role.  
Blackthorne has denied any involvement in the killing. 
</P>
<P>
	In a transcript of an interview published in the Sarasota  
Herald-Tribune, Del Toro told Mexican authorities he hit Mrs. 
Bellush twice, leaving her unconscious, but a man he knew only as 
Jorge actually killed her. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
