<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Family Awarded $295M in Ford Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CERES, Calif. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. has been ordered to pay $295  
million to the family of a couple and their son who were killed in 
the rollover of a Ford Bronco. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors on Monday awarded $5 million in compensation to three  
family members and $290 million in punitive damages. A spokesman 
for the automaker said Ford would appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The verdict came three days after a Los Angeles jury awarded a  
record $4.9 billion to six people who were severely burned when 
their Chevrolet exploded in a rear-end collision. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Ford lawsuit, Juan Romo and his two surviving sisters  
claimed the automaker knew the Bronco's mostly plastic roof would 
not hold up in a rollover. 
</P>
<P>
	Romo was driving the 1978 Bronco in June 1993 when he swerved to  
avoid a van he was passing. The vehicle rolled over, killing Romo's 
mother, father and brother. 
</P>
<P>
	A former Ford executive, Tom Feeney, testified on behalf of the  
Romos, saying company officials knew the roof was virtually certain 
to fail, said plaintiffs' lawyer Laurence Drivon. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford argued that the vehicle was sound and that the accident was  
Romo's fault. 
</P>
<P>
	``We conducted tests on the Bronco and it surpasses handily all  
of the federal motor vehicle safety standards, even though it's not 
required to do so,'' Ford spokesman Jim Cain said after the 
verdict. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
