<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schumacher Hit Wall at 67 MPH </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Michael Schumacher was traveling at 67 mph when  
his Ferrari slammed into a tire wall after its front wheels locked 
during the British Grand Prix, auto racing's governing body said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	An analysis of the ``black box'' data recorder in Schumacher's  
car showed that he had been traveling at 191 mph when he started to 
brake on the first lap of Sunday's race at Silverstone, England, 
according to the International Automobile Federation (FIA). 
</P>
<P>
	The front wheels locked at 127 mph, sending the car hurtling off  
the track, on to a gravel trap and into the tire wall. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-year-old Schumacher, a two-time world champion from  
Germany, broke his is right leg in two places. He was released 
Tuesday from a hospital at Northampton, England. 
</P>
<P>
	He had been airlifted to the hospital, where surgeons inserted a  
foot-long pin in the leg to fix the fractures of his tibia and 
fibula. 
</P>
<P>
	Schumacher said he was lucky to be alive and that he expected to  
be out of action for two to three months. He wrote off any chance 
of winning the Formula One drivers' championship, but he added he 
was confident of racing for Ferrari again before the end of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	FIA said in a statement the gravel trap had performed as  
expected in slowing down Schumacher's car, but it was still 
traveling at high speed when it hit the wall. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite much comment, there are no simple answers to the  
problem of slowing an out-of-control car,'' the statement said. 
``The relevant measures are under constant review.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
