<DOCNO> APW19990713.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 16:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House GOP Proposes Huge Tax Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans rolled out their $864  
billion tax relief package Tuesday, including a gradual 10 percent 
cut in income tax rates. President Clinton said the bill was far 
too big and urged the GOP to focus budget surpluses on Social 
Security and Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bill Archer, chairman of the tax-writing House Ways and  
Means Committee, brushed off veto threats and insisted his bill 
properly ensures that all taxpayers receive a refund from the 
projected surplus they have created. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we are talking about is a defining difference between the  
Republicans and Democrats,'' said Archer, R-Texas. ``We believe the 
people can spend their money more wisely than the bureaucrats in 
Washington.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a projected $2.9 trillion over 10 years, Archer said the  
surplus is big enough to enact a huge tax cut and still reinforce 
both Social Security and Medicare to withstand retirement of the 
baby boomers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can do all three,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	But in a speech in Miami, Clinton said it would be a mistake to  
divert too much for a tax cut before Social Security and Medicare 
are fixed, including a new prescription drug benefit for Medicare 
recipients. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also said such a large tax cut would threaten future  
spending on key programs ranging from defense to education to 
medical research and would do nothing to reduce the national debt. 
</P>
<P>
	``So I ask again the Republican leaders in Congress, for the  
sake of saving Medicare and strengthening our future, to reduce the 
size of your tax cut and join us in putting first things first,'' 
the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, echoing Clinton's concerns,  
also voiced his ``strong opposition'' to Archer's bill, making 
clear that the president would veto the measure as currently 
structured. ``If a bill encompassing these proposals were to pass 
the Congress this year, the president would veto it,'' Summers said 
in a letter to Archer on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ways and Means Committee began consideration of the bill  
Tuesday, although votes on amendments were not likely until 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said they planned to force votes in an attempt to show  
they are more concerned with Medicare and Social Security than the 
Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Democrats said the bill's primary purpose was to provide  
campaign material for Republicans in the 2000 races and had no 
chance of becoming law. They said they were willing to consider a 
more modest tax cut of perhaps $250 billion, if the breaks are 
targeted at the middle class. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope the public will see through this as a campaign  
gimmick,'' said Rep. Fortney ``Pete'' Stark, D-Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	There was some early Republican grumbling as well. A letter to  
Archer from about 50 House conservatives complained that provisions 
to fix the ``marriage penalty'' were too meager, although the 
lawmakers did not threaten to vote against the overall bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe this bill doesn't go far enough in providing relief  
to families,'' said the group, which is led by Rep. David McIntosh, 
R-Ind. ``Republicans are the party of small government, strong 
economic growth and strong families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Archer, however, said the measure reflected longstanding GOP  
goals of reducing taxes and limiting government -- and that 
upper-income people who pay the most taxes also deserve a break. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're giving it to everybody. We shouldn't be taking that  
money in the first place, because we don't need it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the plan, which would be the largest tax cut since  
President Reagan's in 1981, was released piecemeal last week. These 
previously known provisions include the 10 percent cut in all 
income tax rates over 10 years, an immediate reduction in the top 
capital gains tax rate from 20 percent to 15 percent, gradual 
elimination of estate taxes and new breaks for education and health 
care costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The finalized plan included several new items:  
</P>
<P>
	--Fixing the ``marriage penalty'' paid by millions of two-income  
couples by allowing them a standard deduction of $8,600, instead of 
$7,200 in current law. 
</P>
<P>
	--Phasing out the alternative minimum tax, which was created to  
ensure the wealthy don't escape taxes through legitimate tax moves 
but which has increasingly affected middle-class taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
	--Prohibiting taxes on the first $400 in savings interest for a  
married couple, $200 for singles. 
</P>
<P>
	--Cutting capital gains taxes for corporations from 35 percent to  
25 percent over nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	--Several small business provisions, including the restoration of  
the deductibility of business meals to 80 percent from 50 percent 
and allowing health insurance premiums to be fully deductible for 
the self-employed. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Republicans are developing a competing proposal that  
costs roughly $792 billion over 10 years. That measure attempts to 
aim benefits more at the middle class by cutting the bottom income 
tax rate from 15 percent to 14 percent and raising limits on 
individual retirement account contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate version also includes no capital gains tax cut and  
only limited reductions in estate taxes, both of which are seen by 
critics as primarily concerns of the wealthy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
