<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hospital Releases Kentucky Player </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Kentucky wide receiver Jimmy Robinson, who  
was shot twice in the left arm during a fight at an off-campus 
party, was released from the hospital Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, a senior, had been at UK Hospital since Friday night,  
when a group of people crashed a party at the University Commons 
apartment complex, and fighting broke out, followed by gunfire. 
</P>
<P>
	One shot broke the humerus bone in Robinson's upper left arm and  
another fractured the base of his left thumb. He was the only 
person wounded in the shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson had pins inserted in his thumb during surgery Monday.  
His upper left arm has been placed in a cast. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors have said the pins could come out within five weeks,  
while it likely will take three to four months for his broken arm 
to heal. His playing status for this season is uncertain. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, of Stone Mountain, Ga., played the last two seasons  
for Kentucky after transferring from Georgia Military College in 
1997. Last season, he caught 26 passes for 285 yards and two 
touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	No arrest has been made in the shooting.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
