<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Medicare Contractors Implicated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Contractors responsible for spotting Medicare  
fraud have themselves been implicated in wrongdoing, paying at 
least $235 million in civil and criminal penalties since 1993, 
according to a congressional report obtained Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The General Accounting Office said the contractors that were  
assessed the penalties were charged with numerous fraudulent 
practices including improperly paying claims, destroying or 
deleting backlogged claims, failing to recoup money owed Medicare 
and manufacturing documentation to support claims payments that 
should have been rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO testimony was backed up by the Department of Health and  
Human Services inspector general's office, which concluded the 
contractors -- the first line of defense in detecting Medicare fraud 
-- had ``problems with their own integrity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In testimony prepared for a House Commerce subcommittee and  
obtained by The Associated Press, GAO official Leslie G. Aronovitz 
concluded that a lack of attention to the contractors by Medicare 
officials could make the insurance program ``more vulnerable to 
fraud, waste or abuse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aronovitz said six current or former contractors, hired for  
Medicare's fee-for-service program, paid the penalties. The 
contractors are responsible for paying health care providers for 
the services provided to Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Thomas Bliley, chairman of the House Commerce Committee,  
called the findings ``deeply disturbing.'' He said the contractors 
were able ``to dupe'' officials of the Health Care Financing 
Administration because the agency ``routinely gave them advance 
warning about the dates of any reviews and about the records the 
agency wanted to review.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Peacock, spokesman for HCFA, which administers the huge  
Medicare program, responded that over the past two years, HCFA has 
cut the Medicare error rate in half, and, working with other 
agencies and officials, has returned $1.2 billion to the Medicare 
trust fund. 
</P>
<P>
	HCFA has taken steps to cut down on Medicare fraud and toughen  
oversight on Medicare contractors, Peacock said. He said HCFA has 
asked Congress to pass legislation that would enable Medicare to 
impose stiffer penalties and make it easier to take work away from 
contractors who fail to protect Medicare funds, but Congress has 
not done so. 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO said the health care agency was able to identify only  
three of 17 contractors with ``integrity problems.'' The others 
were discovered through whistleblowers and federal investigators 
familiar with the contractor practices. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that HCFA may have placed too much trust in its  
contractors,'' the report said, including acceptance of their 
self-certification that their systems were working. 
</P>
<P>
	George F. Grob, deputy inspector general at HHS, said in his  
prepared testimony that the contractors were ``misusing government 
funds and actively trying to conceal their actions, altering 
documents and falsifying statements that specific work was 
performed. 
</P>
<P>
	``In some cases, contractors prepared bogus documents to falsely  
demonstrate superior performance for which Medicare rewarded them 
with bonuses and additional contracts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grob said his office's investigations resulted in nine civil  
settlements and two criminal convictions, while 21 former or 
current contractors remain under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	He said a review of 12 contractors found deficiencies at all of  
them in documenting the amount of money that providers owed 
Medicare -- due to overpayments and claims that should have been 
paid by other insurers. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Grob reported, electronic security was so weak at  
11 of the 12 contractors that ``we were able to penetrate the 
security systems and obtain access to sensitive Medicare data.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
