<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> International Paper's Earnings Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- International Paper reported  
better-than-expected earnings in the second quarter as the company 
benefited from higher prices for its products and signs of recovery 
in Asian economies. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's biggest paper and forest products company said  
Tuesday that excluding acquisition charges and other one-time 
items, it earned $99 million, or 24 cents a share, compared with 
earnings of $32 million, or 8 cents a share, a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales were $6 billion, compared with $5.8 billion a year ago.  
</P>
<P>
	The results topped estimates of 23 cents a share by analysts  
surveyed by First Call Corp. But the company's stock fell by 50 
cents to $53 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	During the quarter, International Paper took about $157 million  
in after-tax charges to cover costs associated with its $5.8 
billion purchase in May of Union Camp, another paper and forest 
products company. 
</P>
<P>
	Including those charges, International Paper had a net loss of  
$71 million, or 17 cents a share, in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	International Paper chief executive John Dillion said that the  
Union Camp acquisition is already contributing to the company's 
earnings. International Paper has also raised its anticipated 
savings from the merger to $425 million from $300 million. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said that the company's efforts to reduce costs in  
recent years helped to boost its profits, as did the improvement in 
prices of all of its products and the beginning of a recovery in 
Asia and other world economies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Looking forward, market conditions are more favorable than  
we've seen in some time,'' Dillon said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
