<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Michigan Football Players Charged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Two Michigan football players have been  
arraigned on felony embezzlement charges for allegedly taking 
merchandise from a Kmart store. 
</P>
<P>
	Jonathan Goodwin and Maurice Williams each were charged Monday  
in Ann Arbor with felony counts of embezzling and conspiring to 
embezzle. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodwin and Williams, both offensive linemen, were allowed to  
remain free on $5,000 personal recognizance bonds while the cases 
are pending, the Detroit Free Press reported in Tuesday editions. 
</P>
<P>
	They are to appear at a preliminary examination later this  
month. 
</P>
<P>
	The players are accused of being part of a six-person ring that  
allegedly took thousands of dollars worth of merchandise through a 
checkout lane at a Kmart store in Ypsilanti Township in June. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation continues on three additional suspects,  
including ex-Michigan football player Demitrius Smith, chief 
assistant Washtenaw County prosecutor Joe Burke told The Ann Arbor 
News. 
</P>
<P>
	The accusations are contained in affidavits filed in 14th  
District Court by the Washtenaw County Sheriff's Department, which 
was seeking search warrants. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspects would face a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison  
and a $5,000 fine upon conviction. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
