<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Russia Sign Steel Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Russia has agreed to limit shipments of steel  
to the United States to avoid imposition of punitive American 
tariffs, U.S. officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was signed after marathon bargaining talks in Paris.  
</P>
<P>
	If an agreement had not been reached by today, the United States  
was set to impose the penalty tariffs, which would have resulted in 
an even steeper drop in demand for Russian steel in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	Commerce Secretary William Daley was briefing reporters on  
details of the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's Tass news agency quoted Russian Trade Minister Mikhail  
Fradkov as saying the deal would preserve Russia's access to the 
U.S. market. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement represents ``a sufficiently difficult compromise  
for both sides, but for Russia it preserves an opportunity to 
supply steel to the American market,'' Fradkov was quoted as 
saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Fradkov told the Russian news agency that the deal was achieved  
only at the last minute following a number of concessions from the 
American side. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. steel industry and its supporters in Congress had been  
unhappy with the outline of a preliminary agreement the 
administration struck with Russia on steel back in February. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., had complained that  
the initial deal, which has now been modified with further 
negotiations, ``allows too much (Russian) steel to be imported at 
too low of a price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With political pressures rising, the administration has tried to  
show support for the U.S. steel industry. The industry has been 
hurt by a flood of cheap imports into the country following the 
global currency crisis, which sharply lowered demand for steel and 
other commodities because of the steep recessions in many Asian 
nations and Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	The steel industry has filed a number of dumping cases seeking  
to get the government to impose high tariffs to stem this tide of 
cheap foreign steel into the country. 
</P>
<P>
	High tariffs have been imposed in a case involving hot-rolled  
steel with Japan. But Russia entered into negotiations to avoid 
having the tariffs, which the industry favors because they are more 
effective at halting imports. 
</P>
<P>
	A number of Clinton administration officials argued that an  
agreement should be reached by which Russia could still ship steel 
to the United States as a way of helping that country out of its 
economic troubles. Steel is one of Russia's major industries, 
accounting for 7 percent of total economic output. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
