<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Mac Conquers Green Monster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Mark McGwire made the Green Monster look like any  
old picket fence. 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't win Monday night's Home Run Derby. And he didn't even  
dent The Wall. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because he flicked baseballs over Landsdowne Street as if  
they were golf balls. One went soaring off a light tower, about 100 
feet above the field and 60 feet over the wall's top. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to question a lot of those measurements on some of  
those balls,'' Boston's Nomar Garciaparra said. ``I don't think 
it's 480 feet to the Mass Pike.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Big Mac didn't actually make it to the highway, but a few balls  
seemed to soar over the turnpike toward the Citgo sign in Kenmore 
Square. Even on an off-day, he set another home run record. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was having fun,'' Big Mac said. ``I love doing these things.  
Earlier in my career, when I didn't accept myself as a home-run 
hitter, I didn't like doing these things. But now I enjoy them. I 
think sometimes it's better than the game because I haven't really 
had a great All-Star game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By the time Ken Griffey Jr. repeated as Home Run Derby champion  
Monday night, it was all anticlimactic. Fenway Park was buzzing 
about McGwire's record 13 home runs in the first round, one more 
than Cal Ripken Jr. hit in 1991 at Toronto's SkyDome. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire, who hit 18 home runs at Fenway while he played for the  
Oakland Athletics, powered the NL to a 27-10 victory. But when it 
came to the individual title, he got just three in the second round 
and was knocked out. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sitting and waiting tired me out,'' he said. ``I probably  
tried a little too hard. I was more relaxed in the first round.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire's homers averaged 438 feet in the first round, and his  
longest shot was his finale, a 488-foot drive deep over the screen 
and into the summer night. The eight longest shots were his, all 
450 feet or longer. 
</P>
<P>
	``(You're) watching Mark hit them 500 feet when you're getting  
them over like 420, 430, and his balls are doing the postal 
service, just flying by you and dropping mail off at your house,'' 
said Griffey, who averaged 419 for his 10 homers in the second 
round. 
</P>
<P>
	Big Mac's attack totaled 5,692 feet -- more than a mile -- and a  
lot more than he hit one mile up at Denver's Coors Field last July. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year, I didn't do so good in the home run contest,'' said  
McGwire, who hit four at Coors and apologized to the fans. ``In 
these home run contests, it's up to the pitcher. Tim got me in a 
good grove.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey, like Ted Williams showing left-handed hitters can flash  
power at Fenway, hit a 460-foot shot to the back of the 
center-field triangle and an opposite-field drive over The Wall and 
into the screen. Milwaukee's Jeromy Burnitz hit six and also 
advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just sad Mac didn't make it because I know that's why  
everybody's here to watch.'' Burnitz said, sounding apologetic. 
``Best show on Earth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey, despite a sore knee, won the final 3-2, winning the  
Derby for the third time since it began in 1990. He didn't seem to 
take it that seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there is 'defending the title,' '' he said.  
``It's just going out there and having a lot fun.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
