<DOCNO> APW19990713.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 18:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Votes To Revive Parks Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House voted Tuesday to revive a moribund  
program that has helped states purchase parkland, handing a 
symbolic victory to pro-environment lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	By 213-202, lawmakers voted to spend $30 million next year from  
the land and water conservation fund for grants to all 50 states. 
Under the program, states receiving the federal grants must provide 
an equal amount of money. 
</P>
<P>
	The language was sponsored by Reps. James McGovern, D-Mass.; Tom  
Campbell, R-Calif.; Joseph Hoeffel, D-Pa.; and Rush Holt, D-N.J. It 
was included in a $14.1 billion measure financing the Interior 
Department and cultural programs for the upcoming fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	The lands provision was supported 157-45 by Democrats and  
opposed 157-55 by Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund has not distributed money to the states since 1994,  
said McGovern spokesman Michael Mershon. It collects $900 million 
annually from offshore oil and gas drilling leases and is designed 
to use 60 percent of the money for state grants and the rest for 
federal land acquisition. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the sponsors' victory, the bill provides less than  
one-third of the nearly $800 million President Clinton requested 
for federal and state land purchases under his so-called ``lands 
legacy'' proposal. And the amendment's fate is uncertain because 
the Senate version of the bill contains no such language. 
</P>
<P>
	The $30 million would come from cutting coal research and other  
programs in the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same measure, the House rejected an effort by Rep. Tom  
Coburn, R-Okla., to cut $2 million from the Fish and Wildlife 
Service's $711 million resource management program. The 287-131 
vote marked a setback for ongoing conservative efforts to trim 
spending bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, the Interior measure contains nearly $200 million less  
than this year's bill and nearly $1.2 billion less than Clinton has 
requested. The House planned to continue debating the bill on 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would also provide less than Clinton wants for land and  
water conservation, restoration of Florida's Everglades and energy 
conservation. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, the House approved an $8.4 billion measure financing  
construction at U.S. military bases in the United States and abroad 
for the coming year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
