<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Stocks Fall on China Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Taiwan's main stock index tumbled 3.1 percent Tuesday on rising  
tensions between China and Taiwan after Taiwanese President Lee 
Teng-hui said Beijing should regard the island as a separate 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taipei market's key Weighted Stock Price Index fell 259.40  
points to 8,204.50. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese officials have called Lee a ``liar and separatist''  
after he said in an interview with a German radio last week that 
Taiwan's relations with the mainland are ``state-to-state'' rather 
than a province within a country as China has claimed. 
</P>
<P>
	About a third of Taiwanese listed companies have investments in  
China, and their business could be hurt by tensions between the two 
sides, traders said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 18:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McVeigh Moved to Federal Death Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TERRE HAUTE, Ind. (AP) -- Oklahoma City bomber Tim McVeigh and 19  
other prisoners facing federal death sentences were moved Tuesday 
to a new death row outside this western Indiana city. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Penitentiary a few miles southwest of Terre Haute will  
house all men under federal death sentence, said Dan Dunne, a 
spokesman for the U.S. Bureau of Prisons. The inmates were 
transferred from several different states and arrived by plane and 
bus throughout the day. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just worked like clockwork,'' said Harley Lappin, warden of  
the Terre Haute facility. 
</P>
<P>
	The penitentiary contains the only federal death chamber.  
Equipped for lethal injections, it was completed in 1995 and 
contains a 50-bed death row unit. 
</P>
<P>
	McVeigh was sentenced to death two years ago for the April 1995  
Oklahoma City bombing that killed 168 people. At the time he became 
the 14th person sentenced to die under the relatively new federal 
death penalty law. 
</P>
<P>
	He had been held under maximum security at a federal prison in  
Florence, Colo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 02:50:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *James A. Barnes Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) -- James A. Barnes Jr., a U-2 spy  
plane pilot whose photographs of Soviet missile sites in Cuba led 
to a superpower showdown, died June 6 after suffering a stroke. He 
was 70. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnes was a civilian pilot working for the CIA in October 1962  
when he took pictures of Soviet missile sites in Cuba. Another Air 
Force U-2 pilot, Maj. Richard Heyser, also took photos of missile 
sites at about the same time, and there is some debate over which 
pilot was the first to detect launching pads for missiles that 
could reach the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Photos by both pilots landed on President Kennedy's desk as  
evidence of a Soviet threat, and Kennedy warned in televised speech 
on Oct. 22, 1962 that the United States was on the brink of nuclear 
war. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnes served as an Air Force fighter pilot during the Korean  
War. He flew a mission over the Soviet Union on the same day in 
1960 that another U-2 pilot, Francis Gary Powers, was shot down and 
captured. 
</P>
<P>
	Powers was eventually tried in Moscow, forcing President  
Eisenhower to admit he had lied when he denied the U-2 program's 
existence. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Charles R. English    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Charles R. English, a Hollywood attorney  
whose clients included Jack Nicholson, Alec Baldwin, James Woods 
and rocker Tommy Lee, died Saturday due to complications from a 
brain tumor. He was 61. 
</P>
<P>
	English was a firm advocate of due process guarantees. As  
chairman of the American Bar Association's national standards 
committee, he was critical of new court efficiencies that he felt 
infringed on defendant's rights. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, he was named Outstanding Defense Attorney by the Los  
Angeles County Bar Association in 1998. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Howard Flieger    	
</P>
<P>
	POTOMAC, Md. (AP) -- Howard Flieger, who retired in 1976 as  
executive editor of U.S. News and World Report, died Sunday of 
cardio-respiratory failure. He was 89. 
</P>
<P>
	Flieger began working at U.S. News in 1945 as a political  
writer. He later became managing editor of World Report, a separate 
publication. He was named international editor in 1948 after the 
two publications merged. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Denver, Flieger also worked at The Associated Press  
in Missouri and Washington. He was one of three reporters allowed 
to attend President Roosevelt's funeral in 1945. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by two sons.  

</P>
<P>
                         *Carlos D. Ramirez    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Carlos D. Ramirez, the publisher of el diario/La  
Prensa who helped modernize and bring financial security to the 
city's largest and oldest daily Spanish-language newspaper, died 
Sunday of pancreatic cancer. He was 52. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his illness, Ramirez continued to come into the office  
several days a week, said his business partner, Peter Davidson. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez was hired by el diario's former owner Gannett Co. as a  
comptroller in 1981 and became publisher in 1984. The newspaper, 
founded in 1913, is believed to be the oldest Spanish-language 
daily in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1989, when Gannett first started shopping the newspaper  
around, Ramirez, Davidson and 15 others formed an investment group 
-- El Diario Associates -- and bought the newspaper for a reported 
$20 million to $25 million to keep it under Hispanic ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	Under their ownership, Ramirez remained publisher and Davidson  
became president. The investment group, now called Latin 
Communications Group Inc., owns several Spanish-language newspapers 
and 18 radio stations around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last few years, el diario has had one of the fastest  
growing circulations in the city, along with the New York Post. 

</P>
<P>
                          *J. Howard Rogers    	
</P>
<P>
	PARIS, Texas (AP) -- J. Howard Rogers, a longtime gospel singer  
who was a member of the Texas Music Hall of Fame, died Sunday. He 
was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogers' gospel career stretched back 74 years and included  
numerous awards. He was a charter member of the Southern Gospel 
Music Association and was a dean of the SGMA School of Music for 14 
years. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Geno Saccomanno    	
</P>
<P>
	GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. (AP) -- Dr. Geno Saccomanno, who devoted a  
50-year career to lung cancer research, died Saturday. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Saccomanno also was credited for inventing medical instruments,  
including a brush to take cervical samples for Pap smears. 
</P>
<P>
	Saccomanno received his medical degree from St. Louis  
University. He joined the St. Mary's staff in 1948 and later that 
year established the only pathology service between Denver and Salt 
Lake City. 
</P>
<P>
	During the next four decades, Saccomanno studied 17,700 uranium  
miners in the Four Corners area to help shed light on lung cancer. 
He and his research team tracked personal data, smoking habits, 
work history and medical records. 
</P>
<P>
	Saccomanno received the Energy Department's highest award for  
exceptional public service in 1993, among other lifetime 
achievement awards. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
