<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Electronic Airline Tickets Gain Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- After years of trying to convince  
travelers to abandon paper tickets, the airline industry has 
reached a milestone -- with about half of all travelers using 
electronic tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	With little fanfare, passengers like Stan Quintana have been  
bidding farewell to their cardboard traveling companion. 
</P>
<P>
	Quintana, 29, booked an electronic ticket with US Airways for a  
recent trip to Washington because it eliminated a major worry. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have to be concerned about losing a ticket on the way  
to a plane,'' Quintana said as he waited at Reagan National Airport 
for his flight home to Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta-based bargain carrier ValuJet in 1993 was one of the  
first to embrace the simple tickletless technology, and Southwest 
and United soon followed. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, all major U.S. airlines offer e-tickets and their  
popularity has nearly doubled since the beginning of 1998, industry 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	United Airlines, based in Chicago, said recently that 51 percent  
of the more than 7 million tickets used in May were electronic -- 
the first time ticketless passengers outnumbered those with paper 
tickets. United offers e-tickets on 95 percent of its routes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our society is one where people are looking for more and more  
convenience,'' spokesman Kurt Ebenoch said. 
</P>
<P>
	And US Airways, based in Arlington, said that the number of  
electronic tickets sold surpassed the 50 percent mark for the first 
time in late June. It offers electronic ticketing on all of its 
flights. 
</P>
<P>
	Other airlines report similar use of e-tickets, but no agency  
keeps precise numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Airlines Reporting Corp. in Arlington, which tracks tickets  
sold by travel agents for the major U.S. airlines, said that 40 
percent of those tickets are paperless. Spokesman Allan Muten said 
he expects that to increase to 50 percent by year-end. 
</P>
<P>
	The numbers of e-tickets are higher for tickets sold directly by  
the airlines, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Holders of electronic tickets need to bring only their luggage,  
credit card and a photo ID to the airport. Airlines usually mail or 
fax an itinerary, and international customers are usually asked to 
carry the paper receipt. 
</P>
<P>
	Business travelers with many flights over numerous days  
especially like e-tickets because they are easy to change over the 
phone and eliminate the fumbling and frantic searching for the 
correct paper ticket. It can cost $75 to replace a lost paper 
ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	The airlines like e-tickets because they can save up to a couple  
of dollars per ticket by eliminating the labor costs involved with 
printing, mailing, handling and storing paper tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	It takes 11 employees to handle a paper ticket -- which ends its  
journey in a warehouse -- from start to finish at Southwest 
Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Paper tickets are laborious and take up a lot of space and  
time,'' said Beth Harbin, a spokeswoman for the Dallas-based 
carrier, which reports that 70 percent of its tickets are 
electronic. 
</P>
<P>
	The airlines also claim that e-tickets result in faster lines  
for passengers, although those holding an e-ticket must still wait 
in line to get a boarding pass and check luggage. 
</P>
<P>
	And some say the ``e'' doesn't always mean ``easier.''  
</P>
<P>
	Ticketless passengers have more problems transferring to a  
different airline when a flight is canceled or delayed because the 
companies' computers do not always communicate with one another. 
The traveler has to first convert the e-ticket to a paper ticket 
before going to the other airline. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is being eliminated as airlines develop standardized  
software. 
</P>
<P>
	American Airlines, based in Dallas, announced last month that it  
had formed a partnership with Canadian Airlines to sell electronic 
tickets for each other. 
</P>
<P>
	American and United had planned to be able to read one-another's  
e-tickets by this summer. Now it won't happen until at least next 
year at the earliest. 
</P>
<P>
	Muten said he anticipates rapid growth of e-tickets, especially  
from foreign carriers, as more airlines are able to log on to one 
another's electronic ticket reservation systems. 
</P>
<P>
	So, are paper tickets going the way of lavish meals and free  
movies? Many airline officials declined to say, perhaps for fear of 
frightening those not yet ready to join the e-revolution. 
</P>
<P>
	``More and more, we will head in that direction,'' Ebenoch said.  


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 09:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pros, Cons of Electronic Tickets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Q: I'm planning to travel a lot for business in the next few  
months and I'm wondering if I should use electronic tickets for the 
flights. What are the pros and cons? 

</P>
<P>
	A: People like electronic tickets because there's nothing to  
misplace or lose, but they aren't ideal for everyone -- at least not 
yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one less piece of paper to carry around,'' says Jim Glab,  
acting managing editor of Frequent Flyer magazine and a regular 
e-ticket user. ``It makes it easier, especially if you do online 
booking. You don't have to wait for the ticket to come in the mail 
and hope it gets there before you leave. 
</P>
<P>
	``Online booking and electronic ticketing really go  
hand-in-hand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While ticketless travel is only just now becoming widespread,  
with some airlines reporting that they sell as many e-tickets as 
paper tickets, Glab explains that the concept isn't that novel. 
People don't need a paper ticket to check into a hotel or rent a 
car, he notes. 
</P>
<P>
	But electronic ticketing does have some drawbacks.  
</P>
<P>
	It's still not available on all international routes, and the  
airlines haven't yet coordinated their electronic ticketing 
systems. 
</P>
<P>
	If you were planning to fly from New York to Chicago on United  
Airlines, then connect to a Northwest Airlines flight to continue 
on to Fargo, N.D., you can get one paper ticket written up for both 
flights and it would be priced as if you were taking the same 
airline the whole way through. Since the airlines don't share 
e-ticket technology, you'd have to buy two completely separate 
electronic tickets, and that would cost a lot more. 
</P>
<P>
	There are other times when a paper ticket is an advantage -- if  
your flight is canceled or delayed and you switch to another 
airline, you'll need to first convert your electronic ticket to 
paper before heading over to the other airline. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course all this is going to change, this is just the way  
things are right now,'' Glab says. 
</P>
<P>
	The bottom line?  
</P>
<P>
	``The people who shouldn't use electronic tickets are people who  
have complicated itineraries, people who are traveling oversees and 
people who need that extra little bit of confidence with a piece of 
paper,'' Glab says. 
</P>
<P>
	But even they should prepare for a paperless future.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be coming in the next couple of years,'' he  
says. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 17:50:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Selig Won't Reinstate Pete Rose </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- While Pete Rose is on the ballot for baseball's  
All-Century team, he was banned from Fenway Park for Tuesday 
night's All-Star game. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose, who was in Boston on Tuesday for a corporate appearance,  
wasn't invited for a pregame ceremony on the field that included 
most of the living players who are on the 100-man ballot for the 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	And baseball even banned his face.  
</P>
<P>
	Pictures of 98 of the 100 were hung on banners draped around the  
grandstand of the ballpark. The only ones missing were Rose and 
Shoeless Joe Jackson, both banned from baseball for life. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, Bud Selig said that, as long he's  
commissioner, Rose can pretty much forget about reinstatement to 
baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's anything new or if there's anything new  
that I would do to change what Bart Giamatti did,'' Selig said, 
referring to the former commissioner who kicked Rose out of 
baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the lifetime ban he signed with Giamatti in August  
1989, Rose is ineligible for the Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose declined comment when Selig's statements were relayed  
through his business agent. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the same old thing, business as usual,'' said agent  
Warren Greene, who was with Rose in Boston. ``Right now, I don't 
think Pete wants to start trading any barbs or make any comment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rose applied for reinstatement in September 1997, but Selig  
hasn't announced a decision. From his statements Tuesday, it's 
clear the only two options Selig is considering are rejection or 
never acting on the petition. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without question, Pete Rose in one of the top players in the  
century,'' Hall of Fame third baseman Mike Schmidt said. 
</P>
<P>
	That said, Schmidt agreed with those who claim Rose hasn't  
reconfigured his life in the past decade. While no formal finding 
was made, Giamatti said he was convinced Rose bet on the Cincinnati 
Reds while he was managing the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I truly believe the ball's in Pete's hands,'' Schmidt said.  
``Pete needs to take some serious steps in his life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 100 players on the ballot, 85 are in the Hall of Fame.  
The exceptions include eight active players: Barry Bonds, Roger 
Clemens, Ken Griffey Jr., Tony Gwynn, Rickey Henderson, Greg 
Maddux, Mark McGwire and Cal Ripken. Also not in the Hall are 
recent retirees Dennis Eckersley, Paul Molitor, Eddie Murray and 
Ozzie Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	The only other three are Carlton Fisk, who fell 43 votes short  
of the hall this year; Shoeless Joe Jackson, who was bypassed by 
the baseball writers and the veterans committee before the 
prohibition against banned players took effect in 1991; and Rose. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson was among eight Chicago White Sox players banned for  
throwing the 1919 World Series, and former Red Sox great Ted 
Williams has led a campaign to reinstate him. Selig said he expects 
to make a decision on Jackson's case later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Rose and Jackson were featured in a lengthy video  
presentation during the new conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``Neither Pete Rose nor Joe Jackson's official status has  
anything to do with the selection of the All-Century team,'' Selig 
said. ``They're great players, they're entitled to be on the 
ballot. ... I want to be very precise in the way I say it: It 
doesn't in any way affect their status with major league baseball. 
However, they are two great players that have made an impact on the 
field, and they're entitled to be on the ballot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-nine of the 54 living players on the ballot attended the  
news conference, including 22 Hall of Famers, among them Hank 
Aaron, Willie Mays and Stan Musial. 
</P>
<P>
	When Kevin Costner introduced them for the ceremony on the  
field, they were joined by Steve Carlton, Carl Yastrzemski and 
Roger Clemens, who was booed by most of the sellout crowd. Clemens, 
a former Boston star, now pitches for the hated New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans can vote for two players at each infield position, two  
catchers, nine outfielders and six pitchers, and a committee can 
select up to five additional players to make up for any imbalance 
slighting the early part of the century, bringing the total to 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Much like All-Star balloting, fans can vote at ballparks and on  
the Internet. The promotion is sponsored by MasterCard 
International, which will put ballots in Sports Illustrated, TV 
Guide and Kmart stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Balloting runs through Sept. 10 and the team will be announced  
before Game 1 of the World Series. A panel selected by baseball 
will pick and All-Century starting lineup from the team. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 10:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tergesen Does Time As `Oz' Inmate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In the history of television, there are many  
pioneers. To name a few: Edward R. Murrow; Milton Berle; J. Fred 
Muggs. Each brought something new to the tube. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Lee Tergesen, in his role as Beecher on HBO's prison drama  
``Oz,'' can point with pride to his own crop of firsts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was the first man ever to be branded with a swastika on  
TV,'' he begins. 
</P>
<P>
	Over a recent lunch, he then lists even more stomach-turning  
milestones of Beecher's stay at the Oswald State Correctional 
Facility (known by insiders as Oz). 
</P>
<P>
	``Five, 10 years from now,'' Tergesen breezily sums up, ``you'll  
be sitting at lunch with someone who'll be going, 'I was the first 
guy ever to be forced to dress up like a woman and sing, ``I Got It 
Bad and That Ain't Good.''' And YOU'LL say, 'Ah! No, no, no, my 
friend!''' 
</P>
<P>
	Until such a day, suffice it to say that Tobias Beecher reigns  
as a singular character among the many fiercely singular characters 
on ``Oz.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He's had a rough go of it,'' Tergesen says with a laugh, and  
that's not about to change as the superb ``Oz'' begins its third 
riveting season Wednesday at 10 p.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	But along with the wide variety of, er, indignities to which  
he's been a party, Beecher stands out from his fellow jailbirds for 
another chilling reason: He might be any of us in the audience. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Oz, he was an attorney and family man safely sheltered in  
the middle class -- that is, until he happened to kill a little girl 
while driving drunk. 
</P>
<P>
	The other inmates are society's designated losers, fated for Oz  
as surely as if they'd followed a 12-step program for misfits. 
Beecher, by contrast, washed up in Cell Block 5 fresh from 
society's mainstream. 
</P>
<P>
	The stricken, clerkish look he brought with him is long gone. By  
now, Beecher is untamed and mercurial, insolent and sullen. And yet 
he remains the ``ordinary'' viewer's captive surrogate. However 
depraved he may be (and more depraved all the time), Beecher 
remains too close for our comfort. 
</P>
<P>
	A ``normal'' guy cast into hell and forced to deal with the heat  
-- Tergesen says he pitched that for his character when he signed to 
do ``Oz.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By then, he had starred on the USA comedy ``Weird Science,''  
done a lot of stage work and been a guest star on ``Homicide: Life 
on the Street,'' which was created by ``Oz'' mastermind Tom 
Fontana, a longtime friend. 
</P>
<P>
	``The great thing about Tom is, he's willing to listen,'' says  
Tergesen, 33, ``and I think that he knew I was going to be able to 
trust him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never went to him and said, `I'm not going to do this, I  
can't do this.' If you start to limit what your character would do, 
you're limiting yourself as an actor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On ``Oz,'' Tergesen joined a large ensemble including Ernie  
Hudson, Terry Kinney, Rita Moreno, B.D. Wong and Edie Falco, who 
also co-stars in HBO's hit ``The Sopranos.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But through it all, Beecher's chief foe has remained Vern  
Schillinger (J.K. Simmons), the cell block's neo-Nazi potentate 
who, in a shocking scene in the series' premiere, ``claimed'' 
Beecher by burning a swastika on his buttock. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really harkens back to the Skipper and Gilligan, doesn't  
it?'' cracks Tergesen. And for this ``Oz'' gruesome twosome, it's 
been downhill from there. 
</P>
<P>
	``My character came in terrified and defenseless, thinking the  
only way to survive was to just take it, because nothing he knew 
from the outside would work,'' Tergesen recalls. ``But eventually 
he decides, `I'd rather die than go on like this,' and he starts 
rolling the dice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beecher's hard-learned lesson: If he picked the lock of  
civilized behavior, he was free to be the person it confined. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never thought that he was an innocent,'' says Tergesen.  
``The fact that he had the alcohol problem ... and he was a lawyer! 
You know what I mean? 
</P>
<P>
	``Being a lawyer, the guy is manipulative. He's a smart guy. He  
just has to learn to use his strengths to manipulate a different 
system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	We don't see Beecher for much of this week's episode. After all,  
he's been laid up since last season when Schillinger and his 
cohorts broke Beecher's arms and legs. 
</P>
<P>
	But 45 minutes into the hour, he gains release from the prison  
hospital, returns to his cell and primes himself to inflict sweet 
comeuppance. His is a scheme so diabolical, so untraceable, that 
somewhere Alfred Hitchcock is nodding with approval. 
</P>
<P>
	So score this week's round for Beecher. But the anti-violent  
message of ``Oz'' reminds us that the match will never end. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can do whatever you want, but you better be ready to pay  
for it,'' says Tergesen. In the long run, no one, certainly not 
Beecher, ever comes out first. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	`HOME IMPROVEMENT': Jill's psychology professor hears her  
voicing some personal objections about him. Now she fears that she 
is at odds with the thesis committee on which he serves, on ``Home 
Improvement'' tonight at 8 p.m. EDT on ABC. Patricia Richardson as 
Jill Taylor, Tim Allen stars as Tim Taylor, Zachery Ty Bryan as 
Brad, Taran Smith as Mark, Earl Hindman as Wilson, Richard Karn as 
Al Borland and Debbe Dunning as Heidi, the ``Tool Time'' girl. Tim 
Allen makes his debut as a director. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore ``at'' ap.org  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
