<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 04:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Close Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stock prices closed down today as  
companies unwound cross held shares. The dollar was unchanged 
against the yen in late afternoon trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 93.09 points,  
or 0.51 percent, to end at 18,181.09. On Monday, the average closed 
up 336.45 points, or 1.88 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.14 yen in late afternoon trading,  
unchanged from late Monday in Tokyo and below its late New York 
level of 122.23 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices fell as companies sold shares  
held in other companies to cement business relations, a practice 
known as cross shareholding. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors also took profits following the day earlier surge,  
traders said. The biggest declines were in high technology sectors, 
they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, buying in internationally competitive blue chips  
continues to underpin the market amid hopes Japan's economy will 
recover, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Economic Planning Agency said today that the economy is  
improving somewhat with private consumer spending recovering and 
government support measures taking effect. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section fell 0.42 points, or 0.03 percent to 1,483.69 points. 
The TOPIX closed up 19.71 points, or 1.35 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar stabilized against the yen  
after Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said Tokyo doesn't intend to 
take radical action in currency markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar had risen in recent weeks as the Bank of Japan  
repeatedly intervened to weaken the yen in an attempt to help the 
nation's economy recover from its worst recession since World War 
II. 
</P>
<P>
	A higher yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad and  
thus less competitive, reducing dollar denominated earnings of 
export oriented Japanese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the Japanese government is probably comfortable  
with the current exchange rate. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 123.64 yen, down  
from 124.10 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese  
government bond fell to 1.6000 percent from Monday's finish of 
1.6400 percent, driving its price up to 101.74 yen from 101.39 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 15:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Rain and storms were scattered throughout the United States on  
Tuesday, with fair conditions in much of the Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain dampened Cape Cod, Mass., with scattered showers in  
Virginia and the Carolinas. Thunderstorms hit the Florida 
Panhandle. 
</P>
<P>
	A stationary front triggered widely scattered showers and  
thunderstorms from Wisconsin to Montana. 
</P>
<P>
	In the West, rain and storms stretched from southern Nevada and  
southwestern Utah, south into western Arizona and extreme 
southeastern California. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacific Northwest and northern Rockies were mostly fair and  
dry. 
</P>
<P>
	The afternoon high in the lower 48 states was 95 degrees in  
Redding, Calif. The low was 36 degrees in Jackson, Wyo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
