<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 13:30:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Concert Ticket Prices Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A rock 'n' roll concert is no longer a cheap  
date. 
</P>
<P>
	The average concert ticket costs $38.56, up $5 in one year and  
$13 since 1996, according to a survey by the industry trade 
publication Pollstar. 
</P>
<P>
	Dancing their way to the bank are the Rolling Stones, who  
charged an average of $109.62 per seat at the 34 shows it performed 
in the United States this year. Opera star Luciano Pavarotti 
charged a $130.77 average at four shows. 
</P>
<P>
	``The artists have really dropped the pretext that they are not  
doing it for the money,'' said Gary Bongiovanni, Pollstar editor. 
</P>
<P>
	For the hottest shows, fans don't seem to mind. Two concerts at  
New York's Madison Square Garden by Latin sensation Ricky Martin -- 
with tickets priced between $38 and $78 -- sold out in 20 minutes on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The actual cost to fans is usually several dollars higher than  
the ticket price, since many venues and ticket agencies add 
surcharges that weren't figured in Pollstar's average. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathy Berkman, an epidemiologist from New York City, paid $125  
apiece for two tickets to Bob Dylan and Paul Simon's upcoming show 
at Madison Square Garden. She and her husband have ticket stubs 
from a Dylan concert with the Band in 1974 for $9.50. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do wish it were more affordable,'' Berkman said on Tuesday.  
``If I were a college student now, I wouldn't be seeing Dylan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Concert tickets were undervalued for many years, judging by the  
stiff premiums that shady brokers were able to get for premium 
seats. Promoters saw how much people were willing to pay brokers, 
so they decided to charge more themselves, Bongiovanni said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ego and greed quickly became involved. When some musicians  
tested the waters with high prices, their competitors figured they 
deserved as much or more and raised their prices accordingly, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixties-era rock fans now have more money and are willing to  
spend it on their heroes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Twenty years ago, if you were a rock 'n' roll star you had  
certain countercultural connections. You couldn't maintain that and 
charge a high level ticket price,'' Bongiovanni said. ``That's gone 
by the boards.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three old favorites -- Neil Young, Elton John and Rod Stewart --  
were in Pollstar's top 10 list of most expensive tickets this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The cheapest average tickets among the 50 most lucrative tours  
this year were sold by the heavy metal double bill of Poison and 
Ratt, at $18.09. The Offspring charged an average of $18.45. 
</P>
<P>
	Veteran concertgoer Berkman said that along with the high  
prices, concert venues do little to ensure that fans are 
comfortable, secure and enjoy the show. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems like fans have an infinite tolerance to put up with  
this kind of abuse,'' she said. ``I wish there would be a 
boycott.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 09:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indictments Coming in ValuJet Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A federal grand jury investigating the 1996 crash  
of ValuJet Flight 592 has decided to indict the airline's 
maintenance contractor and some of its employees, an unprecedented 
step in an aviation accident, sources said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Indictments will name several individuals involved in the  
packing of the illegal cargo blamed for the crash, Justice 
Department sources told The Associated Press. The U.S. Attorney's 
Office announced an afternoon news conference ``regarding a matter 
of significant importance to the community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is believed to be the first time in U.S. aviation history  
that criminal charges are filed against maintenance workers after 
an accidental airplane crash, said Mike Boyd, president of the 
Evergreen, Colo.-based Mike Boyd Group, which researches aviation 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Crash investigators found that workers for ValuJet's maintenance  
contractor, SabreTech Inc., improperly packed oxygen canisters that 
were loaded into the jetliner's cargo hold. Flames from a cargo 
fire tore through the floor of the passenger cabin, causing the 
DC-9 to plunge into the Everglades on May 11, 1996, killing all 105 
passengers and five crew members. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Transportation Safety Board investigation spread  
the blame among SabreTech, ValuJet and the Federal Aviation 
Administration for lax oversight. 
</P>
<P>
	Relatives of the victims have pushed for criminal charges  
against SabreTech and ValuJet executives, complaining that too much 
time had passed without action. Federal and state investigators 
have been looking into the cause of the crash, which led to tougher 
requirements for transporting hazardous cargo aboard commercial 
airplanes. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of those expected to be indicted were the mechanics who  
removed the oxygen generators from two planes SabreTech was 
overhauling for ValuJet. They were expected to be charged with 
falsifying documents for signing work cards that said they had 
installed plastic safety caps on the generators, although no caps 
had been installed. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at SabreTech said Monday they were aware charges were  
imminent. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this happens it will not only be unfair and inappropriate  
but a sad day for civil aviation,'' said Kenneth Quinn, an attorney 
representing SabreTech. 
</P>
<P>
	Oxygen generators, about the size of a Thermos bottle, normally  
are installed in jetliners in compartments above passengers' heads. 
The generators contain chemicals that, when mixed in emergencies, 
produce about 15 minutes' worth of oxygen. 
</P>
<P>
	The chemical mix that takes place once an oxygen generator is  
activated also produces heat that can reach 500 degrees. Safety 
caps are used to keep the generators from activating when they are 
being transported as cargo. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA has proposed a record fine of $2.25 million against  
SabreTech for improperly handling the canisters. The company is 
challenging the fine. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA grounded Atlanta-based ValuJet after the crash. The  
airline later merged with the Orlando-based discount carrier 
AirTran and now flies under the name AirTran. 
</P>
<P>
	SabreTech's maintenance operation, which was owned by St.  
Louis-based Sabreliner, has since been sold. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Associated Press Writer Michael J. Sniffen  
contributed to this report from Washington. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990713.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 00:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canseco May Be Facing Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Jose Canseco feels betrayed, again.  
</P>
<P>
	A week after saying he had overcome so many injuries that he  
didn't think there was anything else he could hurt on his body, the 
Tampa Bay Devil Rays slugger is headed back to the disabled list. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors expect him to make a full recovery from back surgery,  
but he conceded retirement might be an option he has to consider if 
he doesn't come back and swing the bat the way he's accustomed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously it has been a lot of surgeries and a lot of pain ...  
I'm not taking it for granted,'' he said Monday of the prospect of 
returning and continuing to produce like he did the first half of 
the season. 
</P>
<P>
	After hitting a career-high 46 homers for the Toronto Blue Jays  
last year, Canseco was on pace to post even better numbers in 1999 
when stiffness in his lower back was replaced Sunday by 
excruciating pain that prompted surgery to repair a herniated disc. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes you have to have a little bit of luck, and I don't  
have it,'' the Devil Rays designated hitter said from his hospital 
bed in Fort Lauderdale. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just incredible,'' Canseco added. ``I compare it to a  
high-performance car. One little spark plug can be loose, and the 
whole car won't run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Canseco, who leads the AL with 31 homers and is hitting .276  
with 69 RBIs, was selected as the league's starting DH for 
tonight's All-Star game in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	He apologized to fans who voted for him and who were also hoping  
to see him in Monday night's home run derby competition at Fenway 
Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``This to me is a nightmare with the year I'm having, the  
consistency I've had ... The timing couldn't be worse,'' he added. 
``I was given all the ability in the world. Not to be able to use 
it is one of the worst things that can happen to a human being.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Canseco and the Devil Rays are not sure what caused the intense  
pain that left the 35-year-old no alternative than to undergo 
surgery similar to the operation he had for a ruptured disc on his 
left side in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Although doctors said he could have opted for non-surgical care,  
Canseco said he was in such discomfort that he was almost certain 
that he had the same type of injury that had forced him to undergo 
surgery the last time. 
</P>
<P>
	The only difference was, this time, the bad disc was on his  
right side. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just happens. There aren't too many indications,'' said  
Canseco, who left in the eighth inning of Friday night's game 
against Florida in Miami because of stiffness in his back. 
</P>
<P>
	Canseco sat out Saturday night's game, then had an MRI Sunday  
that revealed a severely compressed nerve was causing weakness in 
the toes of his right foot. 
</P>
<P>
	Canseco said surgery eliminated the pain, but it will be several  
weeks before the scar tissue from the incision in his back heals 
enough for him to start rehabilitation. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors said he will be sidelined up to six weeks. Canseco  
recalled it took about two months to return from back surgery three 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Canseco, who signed a one-year contract with the Devil Rays last  
winter with a base salary of $2 million, already has earned 
$250,000 in bonuses for making 300 plate appearances ($200,000) and 
the All-Star team ($50,000). He's not likely to make the 500 plate 
appearances that would guarantee him a $3 million contract for next 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if his mention of possible retirement was out of  
frustration or if it was a serious consideration, Canseco 
emphasized that he wants to continue to play -- preferably in Tampa 
Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's definitely frustration. But you have to consider it if  
you can't come back and play the way you want to. ... I don't want 
to hurt a lineup,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``My future is unsure right now. And it's not because of a lack  
of ability, but a lack of health. There are not a lot of guys in my 
shoes who can say they have the ability to hit 50 or 60 home runs, 
but won't get a chance to do it because they can't stay healthy. I 
don't know what I could do if I stayed healthy all year round.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Devil Rays would like to give him a chance to see.  
</P>
<P>
	``Everything he did for us the first half of the season would  
lead to believe that if everything goes well with the surgery and 
he handles the rehab the way it should be handled that he'll be 
with this club next year,'' general manager Chuck LaMar said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
