<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tenn. TV Station Rescinds Ad Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- How much is a favorable news story worth to  
business executives? Approximately $15,000, one Tennessee 
television station figured. 
</P>
<P>
	A Fox affiliate in Chattanooga, Tenn., offered to produce and  
air three ``positive'' stories about local companies on its news 
programs in exchange for a $15,000 payment. 
</P>
<P>
	The affiliate, WDSI Fox-61, begin broadcasting news shows this  
year for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	An executive who oversees the station said Monday a rogue  
salesperson at WDSI made a mistake and the offers were quickly 
rescinded before any were accepted. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's out of ignorance that this happened, because they don't  
understand the ethics of journalism,'' said David Janecek, vice 
president for news at Pegasus Broadcast Television, a 
Pennsylvania-based company that owns Fox-61. 
</P>
<P>
	A Fox spokesman in New York said the network had no prior  
knowledge of the offer and had nothing to do with the conduct of 
its affiliate stations. 
</P>
<P>
	A one-page sales circular distributed by the station said that  
Fox-61 News was producing a series of news segments highlighting 
prominent businesses in the Chattanooga area. ``We want your 
company highlighted!'' said the sales pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fox-61 News is the most credible programming for the image of  
your company,'' the solicitation continues. ``When an organization 
is involved with positive news coverage, that organization is 
looked upon extremely favorable (sic) in the community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $15,000 fee entitled companies to news segments that would  
be repeated during the morning, midday and evening news programs, 
along with 18 promotional spots drawing attention to the stories. 
</P>
<P>
	Albert Waterhouse, a public relations executive who represents  
businesses in the Chattanooga area, received the solicitation and 
was ``shocked it was so blatant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I just think there needs to be an extremely clear division  
between advertising and news,'' Waterhouse said. ``The public needs 
to understand that you can't buy favorable news stories about your 
clients or anybody else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Erlanger Health System, which owns clinics and a hospital in  
Chattanooga, also received the offer. ``Pretty much everyone agreed 
that it was not only a high price, it was somebody putting a price 
on news,'' spokeswoman Carolyn Peak said. 
</P>
<P>
	The station's general manager, Jim Wright, referred all calls to  
Janecek. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pegasus executive said the salesperson who devised and  
distributed the offer acted against policy and without permission. 
He wouldn't name the person involved or discuss what action the 
company might take. 
</P>
<P>
	Waterhouse suggested, however, that more than one person might  
have been involved: He said the offer was dropped off at his office 
by two people, including the Fox-61 sales manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked how this would affect the station's credibility as a news  
organization, Janecek said, ``It's not going to help.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
