<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Ends Over $20 a Brrel  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures prices finished above $20 a barrel Tuesday on  
the New York Mercantile Exchange for the first time since 1997 as 
investors bet inventories will continue to tighten. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, silver and copper futures retreated sharply.  
</P>
<P>
	Crude rose to its highest levels since Nov. 19, 1997 as a  
refinery outage on the West Coast fueled new concern about 
tightening inventories of crude, gasoline and distillates. 
</P>
<P>
	Chevron shut its 65,000 barrel a day gas-making unit at its  
Richmond, Calif., refinery over the weekend due to a mechanical 
problem and was forced to heavily buy gasoline on the spot market 
to make up for an expected shortfall, market participants said. 
</P>
<P>
	The news pushed crude past $20 a barrel, where it had stubbornly  
hovered for weeks, as investors squared positions in advance of 
weekly inventory data, which was expected to show another decline 
in crude stockpiles. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude inventories have been on the retreat, according to the  
American Petroleum Institute and the U.S. Energy Department, as 
world oil producers show unusual cooperation in keeping excess 
supplies off the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Such action in the past month has helped erase a year-over-year  
surplus and spurred talk that supplies of gasoline and heating oil 
may become critically tight later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Petroleum Institute reported after the close of  
Tuesday's trading, that the nation's crude oil inventories fell 
from 327.22 million barrels to 324.63 million in the week ended 
July 9, while gasoline supplies slipped to 212.79 million barrels, 
from 214.69 a week earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude for August delivery rose 24 cents to $20.15 a barrel;  
August heating oil rose .57 cent to 51.72 cents a gallon; August 
unleaded gasoline rose .18 cent to 59.77 cents a gallon; August 
natural gas rose .32 cent to $2.176 for each 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Copper futures fell sharply on the New York Mercantile Exchange  
as warehouse inventories rose sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants were taken unawares by a steep rise in  
stocks moving into warehouses owned by the London Metal Exchange. 
Copper has been on the rise in recent weeks as suppliers reduce 
production in the face of a supply glut. 
</P>
<P>
	But the increasing prices apparently attracted a wave of  
selling. The London Metal Exchange reported stocks rose 8,775 
metric tons to 766,100 metric tons. The report threw cold water on 
a heated market, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are still going to have a supply surplus this year,'' said  
metals analyst David Meger at Alaron Trading. ``The situation will 
get better down the road, but it doesn't fix the immediate 
problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	September high-grade copper fell 1.7 cents to 76.20 cents a  
pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver futures also tumbled on the New York Merc as the cost of  
borrowing the metal fell, a sign that heavy recent demand from both 
physical users and investors may be waning. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver also had risen on the copper production cuts because  
silver often is produced as a byproduct of copper mining. 
</P>
<P>
	September silver fell 10 cents to $5.16 an ounce.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
