<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indianapolis News Closing Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indianapolis News will cease publication  
with its Oct. 1 edition, joining the growing number of newspapers 
ignored by readers who have little time or inclination to read an 
afternoon daily. 
</P>
<P>
	The 130-year-old newspaper, the oldest in Indianapolis and one  
that billed itself as ``the great Hoosier daily,'' had seen its 
circulation dwindle to 33,175 for the six-month period ending March 
27, compared to 111,000 a decade ago, president and publisher Dale 
A. Duncan said Tuesday in announcing the closing. 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan and executive editor Frank Caperton cited declining  
numbers of stay-at-home moms and blue-collar workers who worked 
night shifts, as well as morning papers' ability to deliver their 
editions earlier and the growing influence of evening television 
news as contributing to the decline. 
</P>
<P>
	In comparison, the News' sister paper, the morning Indianapolis  
Star, has a daily circulation of 235,790 readers. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is just nobody at home in American families before 5, 6,  
sometimes 6:30 in the evening, and therefore there's nobody there 
to read,'' Caperton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The shutdown of the News reflects a continuing trend in daily  
newspaper publishing. In 1998, according to the latest Editor &AMP; 
Publisher Year Book, 30 evening dailies converted to morning 
publication. 
</P>
<P>
	Although 46 of Indiana's 69 daily newspapers are published in  
the afternoon, only five of those afternoon dailies have a 
circulation of more than 20,000, said Dave Stamps of the Hoosier 
State Press Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``People come home from work now and they're not as likely to  
dive into a newspaper as they are other activities,'' Stamps said. 
``The idea of Ozzie Nelson coming home, putting his feet up and 
whipping out the newspaper (is dead); our lifestyles have just 
changed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The News closing will leave 47 cities with two or more  
newspapers, according to figures compiled by The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The closing seemed inevitable to reporters and editors, said  
Marc Allan, president of Local 70 of the Communications Workers of 
America/Newspaper Guild. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've worked here for 11 and a half years, and it's been  
rumored every day that I've been here. So I don't think they're 
shocked. They're sad,'' Allan said. 
</P>
<P>
	The News' late-afternoon final, dubbed the Blue Streak, ceased  
publication shortly after the Jan. 21 death of longtime publisher 
Eugene S. Pulliam. Saturday editions of the News and the Star were 
combined in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The News and Star merged their newsroom staffs in 1995.  
</P>
<P>
	The News won a Pulitzer Prize for a 1930-31 campaign to reduce  
government spending and educate readers about how government 
worked. 
</P>
<P>
	The closing of the News is expected to result in a one-time,  
pretax charge of about $1.25 million for its parent company, 
Central Newspapers Inc. By closing the News, Central expects to 
save between $3 million and $3.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's stock rose 75 cents Tuesday, or by 1.8 percent, to  
close at $42.50 a share on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Central Newspapers is a media and information company. Through  
its flagship newspapers, The Arizona Republic and The Indianapolis 
Star, it publishes the only major dailies in Greater Phoenix and 
central Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Central Newspapers also owns and operates several smaller  
newspapers as well as other related media and information 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Vice President Dan Quayle served on the board of Central  
Newspapers Inc. until January, when he decided to run for 
president. Quayle is the grandson of Pulliam. 
</P>
<P>
	Closing the paper will eliminate about 20 newsroom jobs, but  
most will be absorbed through existing openings and voluntary 
severance. No layoffs are expected, Duncan and union leader Allan 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 12 transportation positions will be eliminated and there  
will be reduced shifts in other areas, the company said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
