<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Capitol Architect Ups Safety Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The architect of the Capitol, cited for health  
and safety violations in the congressional workplace, formed a new 
division Tuesday to confront the problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The Life Safety Program Division will focus on workplace safety,  
fire protection and environmental concerns, architect spokesman 
Herb Franklin said. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest five citations were announced Monday by the  
congressional Office of Compliance. The report concluded the 
architect's office endangered lives at the Library of Congress when 
untrained employees -- working on poorly maintained equipment -- 
accidentally started a fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire occurred April 30 at the library's Madison Building,  
which opened in 1980 and houses rare manuscripts, maps, books, 
musical instruments and a rough draft of the Declaration of 
Independence. The documents escaped damage, but an electrician was 
burned as the flash fire started. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to fire safety problems in other congressional  
buildings, including the U.S. Capitol, the architect's office has 
been criticized for improper storage of chemicals, the highest 
lost-time accident rate in the federal government, failure to 
monitor power plant water for the bacteria that causes Legionnaires 
Disease and futile attempts to start a recycling program. 
</P>
<P>
	Franklin said the director of the division will be Phillip  
Tapper, a safety engineer from the Goddard Space Flight Center in 
Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	Pennie Hardesty, a safety and occupational health professional  
from the Air Force, will be deputy director. 
</P>
<P>
	Franklin said the architect's office has reduced its workforce  
from 2,400 to 2,000 in the last five years, and ``We're now 
regrouping and building up with new competencies. Life safety is a 
high priority.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
