<DOCNO> APW19990713.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-13 05:40:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Immigration Changes Detention Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new interpretation of U.S. law could mean  
freedom for hundreds of nonviolent immigrants with criminal records 
being held awaiting deportation hearings. 
</P>
<P>
	Several court decisions concluded that the Immigration and  
Naturalization Service has more discretion under a 1996 immigration 
law than had been thought. 
</P>
<P>
	The INS action, announced Monday, affects certain criminal  
aliens who completed their criminal sentences prior to Oct. 9, 
1998, when mandatory detention provisions took effect. 
</P>
<P>
	The action essentially restores the discretion INS once enjoyed  
to free noncitizens with criminal records who are not believed to 
pose a danger to the community or a flight risk in advance of their 
final deportation hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Provisions of the 1996 law that took effect in October 1998  
mandated that INS detain virtually all noncitizens whose criminal 
convictions -- occurring before or after passage of the law -- made 
them deportable. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the law also broadened the definition of crimes that  
would trigger deportation and included retroactivity provisions 
covering convictions prior to 1996, some noncitizens who had 
steered clear of crime after an earlier brush with the law suddenly 
found themselves behind bars under mandatory detention. 
</P>
<P>
	With the changes announced Monday, INS will initiate a  
case-by-case review. 
</P>
<P>
	INS Commissioner Doris Meissner stressed that no one deemed to  
pose a threat to public safety will be released under the new 
policy. Release decisions are subject to review by immigration 
judges. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 1996 act gave INS important new tools that have helped us  
reach record levels in the removal of criminal aliens,'' Meissner 
said in a news release. ``In one provision of the new law, at least 
13 federal courts have ruled that INS has greater flexibility in 
implementing the law's mandatory detention requirements than we had 
thought.'' 
</P>
<P>
	INS officials, who had worried the mandatory detention  
provisions would overburden their already strained detention 
system, estimate their new interpretation could reduce the 
detention population of 17,400 by about 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	An author of the 1996 law, Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, who chairs  
the House Judiciary immigration subcommittee, had no comment 
pending review of the new INS policy, said spokesman Allen Kay. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Ciro Rodriguez, who had written Attorney General Janet Reno  
seeking a change to the mandatory detention policies, welcomed the 
INS action. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they are criminals and they are terrorists, yes, deport  
them,'' the Texas Democrat said. ``But if they are people who have 
been here 20, 30 years and are not a threat to our nation and are 
working, have a family, then we need to be conscious of that. They 
have a right to (be released on) bond.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
