<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Cops in Fatal Shooting Fired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIVERSIDE, Calif. (AP) -- The Riverside police chief has fired  
four white officers who shot and killed a 19-year-old black woman 
as she sat in her car, seemingly dazed with a gun in her lap, 
police union and city officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Jerry Carroll gave the officers a piece of paper Monday  
outlining why they were being fired, said Detective Jeffrey Joseph, 
president of the Riverside Police Officers' Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Carroll had informed the officers of his intentions a month ago.  
He declined comment on the firings Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers fired were Paul Bugar, 24; Wayne Stewart, 26;  
Daniel Hotard, 23; and Michael Alagna, 27. 
</P>
<P>
	City Manager John Holmes said the officers were fired for  
violating department policies, although he would not disclose what 
those policies were, the Press Enterprise of Riverside reported 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Riverside County district attorney previously had criticized  
the officers' tactics but decided there was no criminal intent in 
the Dec. 28 shooting of Tyisha Miller. 
</P>
<P>
	Police found Ms. Miller apparently unconscious in a locked car  
parked at a gas station. The four officers fired 23 bullets at her, 
hitting her 12 times, when she suddenly reached for a gun after an 
officer broke into her car to remove the weapon, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The shooting and subsequent decision by the district attorney  
prompted repeated demonstrations in the city 60 miles east of Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller family attorney Andrew Roth said he supports the chief's  
decision but added that he wished it had come sooner. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't predict what the police union or police officers'  
attorneys are going to do, but I fear they are going to fight 
this,'' Roth said. 
</P>
<P>
	The firings come four days after federal prosecutors announced  
they will conduct an investigation into whether the department has 
engaged in repeated civil rights violations 
</P>
<P>
	The state ended its own criminal investigation of the shooting  
by concurring with the district attorney's decision, but continues 
to review whether any state civil rights were violated. 
</P>
<P>
	In Chicago on Monday, the city police superintendent recommended  
the firing of four officers for their part in the fatal shooting of 
an unarmed black woman. 
</P>
<P>
	LaTanya Haggerty, 26, was a passenger in a car involved in a  
police chase on June 4 when she was shot and killed. Investigators 
said an officer mistook her cellular phone for a gun. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers will be suspended 30 days without pay while the  
police board takes up the recommendation of Superintendent Terry 
Hillard. He said the officers ignored an order to call off the 
chase, fired without justification and failed to notify a 
supervisor promptly that shots had been fired. 
</P>
<P>
	Civil rights leaders and members of the clergy have staged  
several protests since the fatal shootings of Ms. Haggerty and an 
unarmed black man, a 22-year-old Northwestern University football 
player. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
