<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brokerages Report Strong Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The stock market was good to Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.  
and Paine Webber Group in the second quarter, and both brokerage 
firms posted profits that beat analysts' expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch on Tuesday reported net earnings of $664 million,  
or $1.57 a share, compared with $540 million, or $1.31 a share in 
the second quarter last year. Industry analysts had forecast the 
New York brokerage firm would earn $1.46 a share, according to 
First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The positive news came less than 24 hours after Merrill's  
president and chief operating officer abruptly resigned. Herbert M. 
Allison Jr., 55, once the heir-apparent for the top job at Merrill 
was told over the weekend he was no longer in the running to 
succeed David Komansky, 60, chairman and chief executive officer, 
according to news reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch is trying to redefine its business by allowing  
customers to trade stocks on the Internet. The strategy, which 
caused internal conflicts in the executive suites, has been 
embraced by customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill's new Unlimited Advantage investment accounts, which now  
allow online trading, grew an eye-popping 65 percent in the past 
five weeks to a total of $16.6 billion in assets. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's army of stock brokers, however, did a brisk  
business between April and June. Strong underwriting for stock and 
bond offerings coupled with fees for advising companies on mergers 
and acquisitions also helped the bottom line. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch reported net revenues of $5.44 billion, up 9  
percent from $5.27 billion in the second quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We showed strength across the board,'' said Stanley O'Neal,  
chief financial officer of Merrill. He added that if the stock 
market continues on its upward path ``there's no reason in my mind 
why we shouldn't be able to perform at similar levels.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investors pushed the company's shares up $1.37 1/2 to close at  
$79.25 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first half of the year, Merrill earned $1.28 billion, or  
$3.02 per share, up 21 percent from $1.04 billion, or $2.57 per 
share, in the first half of last year. Net revenues were $10.71 
billion vs. $9.62 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Paine Webber reported profits of $157.6 million, or $1.02 a  
share, surpassing Wall Street's estimate of 94 cents a share, 
according to First Call. Those results were 27 percent better than 
the year-ago quarter when Paine Webber earned $123.6 million, or 82 
cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Net revenues totaled $1.35 billion vs. $1.16 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	For the first half of the year, profits totaled $324 million, or  
$2.02 a share, up from $250 million, or $1.59 a share, in the first 
half of 1998. Net revenues were $2.66 billion, compared with $2.28 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Paine Webber's shares fell 37 1/2 cents to close at $45.12 1/2 on the  
Big Board. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
